[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Classical Slav − Introduction"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

( { Before you is a project that started some time ago already, but, as these things go, was delayed considerably before I finally managed to complete it. It is a Lifetime Repertoire against the move }1.d4 { .    After making my Lifetime Repertoire on the Caro-Kann back in 2020, I was often asked which opening against }1.d4 { is a good fit for the Caro. I always felt that opening is the Classical Slav, which starts with the moves }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 dxc4 { .    Just as in the Caro-Kann, this is an opening where Black doesn't have any bad pieces. With a bad piece, I mean, for instance, Black's light-squared bishop in the French after   }1.e4 e6 2.d4 d5 { . Both in the Caro, and the Classical Slav, such a piece does not exist. That is usually a good sign, meaning an opening is fundamentally healthy.    Another common theme is the solidity of both openings. In this intro, I'd like to introduce the topics we will be discussing throughout the course. } )1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5  before going ... e7 - e6 .    In 1886, Zukertort and Steinitz played a match for the World Championship. The story of the match was an amazing one, far exceeding the topic of this course, but where I am going to is the fact that in games 1, 3, and 5, Steinitz used the Slav Defense − a rare opening at the time.    In game 1, Steinitz won in great style, a game that is usually added to his collection of best games. Game 3 saw Steinitz getting a big advantage from the opening, and later a completely winning position, before inexplicably giving his opponents counterplay and even the win shortly thereafter.    For Game 5 though, Zukertort came better prepared and got a big advantage from the opening. Steinitz continued to lose a miserable game and dropped the Slav altogether. This loss had a devastating effect on the opening, as for decades(!) it did not get the proper attention.    It was only during the match between Alekhine and Euwe in 1935, that the Slav found its rightful place once again, back into the limelight. } )
3. Nf3( { Of course, we will also spend considerable time on the Exchange Variation }{ ( }3.cxd5 { ) }{ . Play here is obviously rather dry, but that is not the same as a draw. Practice has shown both White and Black winning their fair share of games in the Exchange Variation. Apart from }3.Nf3 { , the move order }3.Nc3 { is very relevant as well and has its own chapters. } )
3. Nf6( { The big alternative here is }3...e6 { , which is aptly called the Triangle Slav. I made a course on that, together with Christof Sielecki, and I think it's fully playable. It is not for the faint-hearted though, as the Noteboom Variation that arises after }4.Nc3 dxc4 { , and the Stonewall setup after   }4.e3 f5 { , require an aggressive mindset. } )( 3...Nf6 { feels more sound. We develop the knight and don't yet block the road }{ for our  c8 -bishop. Last but not least, I should briefly mention }3...dxc4 { . This is an attempt to play an improved Queen's Gambit Accepted (  }1.d4 d5 2.c4 dxc4 { ), but is likely the opposite. After   }4.e3 b5 5.a4! { , it is hard for Black to hold on to the extra pawn. White is preparing to }{ play  b2 - b3  and blow up the queenside. } )
4. Nc3( { The most logical move obviously, but also a giant burden on our opponents. After the move }4.Nc3 { , White needs to be prepared for a whole range of giant opening lines. There is the Chebanenko Slav, a very modern line connected to }4...a6 { , the infamous Semi-Slav arising after }4...e6 { , and there are plenty of smaller lines like the Schlechter Variation after }4...g6 { . Last but not least, there is our repertoire choice }4...dxc4 { , the Classical Slav. } )( { For some, this is too heavy a burden to carry, and they switch to the calmer waters of }4.e3 { , the Slow Slav. Here theory has also amassed over the years - but it's still nothing compared to }4.Nc3 { . Play is of a more strategic nature where concrete knowledge is less important. Therefore, it is a very practical choice that still gives White decent chances to fight for the advantage. That's why it is important to give this line the proper attention it deserves in this course. } )( { Other moves that we will focus on are }4.Qc2 { or }4.Qb3 { (leading to the same position after }4...dxc4 { ), and setups connected }{ to the move  g2 - g3 . The latter has seen a real surge in popularity over the last few years, and that's why we look at the move  g2 - g3  on move 2, 3, 4, and 5! } )
4. dxc4( { After mentioning all the different Slav variations in the previous note, you may wonder why nobody plays }4...Bf5 { . The answer is }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { , when Black has problems. }{ The pawn on  b7  is hanging, and }6...Qb6 7.Nxd5! { loses a pawn. } )( { That is why we play }4...dxc4 { . Since the direct }4...Bf5 { leaves the queenside too vulnerable, we take }{ on  c4  first, before developing this bishop to  f5 . } )
5. a4( { By far the most popular move, isolating our pawn on  c4 . Of the alternatives, }5.e4 { should be mentioned as it leads to a very sharp gambit play after }5...b5 { . We have an extra pawn, but White has compensation in the form of a formidable center. Obviously, other, less critical, alternatives will be looked at as well. } )
5. Bf5{ Our repertoire choice. We develop the bishop on the best square, from where it controls the important  e4 -square. As a result, it is hard for White to get the pawn to  e4 . Now that the bishop has left  c8 , we are ready to play ... e7 - e6  and develop our other bishop. }( { Another popular system is }5...e6 { , which can be considered as an addition to the repertoire I offer in this course. I would not recommend }5...Na6 { , which is named after the 7th World Champion, Vassily Smyslov. Smyslov himself scored already pretty badly with this move, and its reputation hasn't improved over the years.    Perhaps even worse is }5...Bg4 { , the Steiner Variation. After }6.Ne5 Bh5 { , White has multiple ways to get a considerable advantage. } )
6. Ne5{ This has always been considered the most critical response even from the early days of this opening. White does not necessarily intend to take back the pawn on  c4  with the knight, but, more importantly, prepares to set up a big center with  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 , in order to embarrass Black's light-squared bishop and knight on  f6 . A very ambitious plan indeed that, if carried out successfully, would give White a big advantage. }( { There are two other directions that are important to point out. One is the Bled Variation, which arises after }6.Nh4 { and leads to interesting strategic battles after }6...e6 7.Nxf5 exf5 { . } )( { Another strategic line is the Dutch Variation, which arises after }6.e3 { . It is named that way because of the contributions of Max Euwe in this line, in particular in his 1937 match against Alexander Alekhine where he employed it five times. Contrary to the main line,  6.Ne5 , this move leads to quieter, more strategic play. The main line continues }6...e6 7.Bxc4 Bb4 8.O-O O-O { , when my earlier point on bad pieces becomes clear: }{ Black has excellent development, and the  b8 -knight will also soon find a good spot on  d7 . } )
6. e6( { Given that this is a Lifetime Repertoire, which hopefully will last that long indeed, I also offer an alternative at this point in }6...Nbd7 { . I consider }6...e6 { to be the main line of our repertoire though. At first sight, this looks like an odd move, as it doesn't seem to prevent White's main idea: }{ pushing  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 . It turns out it does! } )
7. f3
7. Bb4
8. e4
8. Bxe4( { This piece sacrifice is what makes   }6...e6 { a viable option. We will have an in-depth look at the complications. } )
9. fxe4
9. Nxe4
10. Bd2
10. Qxd4
11. Nxe4
11. Qxe4+
12. Qe2
12. Bxd2+
13. Kxd2
13. Qd5+{ Up to here, play is remarkably forced, and the tree ascends in various directions. No less than four king moves have their own chapter, and rightly so! I hope that studying these chapters will give you the confidence to use them in your own practice. }( { As Black seems to be doing fine in these lines, attention has shifted to   }8.Nxc4 { recently. Now, after }8...O-O { , the incredible }9.Kf2!? { has taken the line by storm. By stepping out of the pin, White reintroduces the threat }{ of  e2 - e4 .    At first, I thought this was just one of those fashionable moves, that would disappear quickly, but at the moment of writing, it's still very much in play. So much so, that we will spend the first chapters of the course tackling this line.    I hope you enjoy this course and invite you to start the journey! } )
