[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Why this is a 1.d4 repertoire"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. c4{ Time to talk about move orders. When we build an opening repertoire, it's a good strategy to find shortcuts. Everything that brings down the burden on our memory should be considered a success. }( { In the introduction, I already mentioned this is a   }1.d4 { repertoire. But can it be used against }1.c4 { or }1.Nf3 { as well? After all, }1.c4 c6 2.d4 d5 { transposes to the Slav, and so does   }1.Nf3 d5 2.d4 { , or }2.c4 c6 3.d4 { . Indeed, these move orders work perfectly fine. The issue arises after the following moves. } )
1. c6
2. Nf3
2. d5( 2...Nf6 { can be played as well, but it doesn't change much, after }3.Nc3 d5 4.e3 { . } )
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3{ This has become a popular setup for White, with German Vincent Keymer being one of the main exponents. First of all, note that White can reach this order via both  1.Nf3  and  1.c4 . By postponing  d2 - d4 , White is making it hard right now to follow our repertoire. Let's look at the most obvious move first. }
4. Bf5{ If we can play ... e7 - e6  next move, Black is in great shape. }
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Qb3( { A theme we have seen before. With the bishop away from home on  f5 , the queenside has become particularly vulnerable. }6...Qb6 7.Nxd5 { loses a pawn and that leaves just one move. } )
6. Bc8( { While this is by no means lost for Black it doesn't attract me at all. After, for instance, }7.d4 e6 8.Ne5!? Nc6 9.f4 Be7 10.Bd3 { , White has a small but pleasant advantage.    On move 4, we could consider improving with   }4...Bg4 { . First of all, }5.cxd5 Bxf3! { is not so bad now because }6.gxf3 cxd5 7.Qb3 Qd7 { can no longer be answered with  8.Ne5!  by White.    However, after   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 { , our repertoire choice is }4...Bf5 { and not }4...Bg4 { . That means that   }5.d4 { now moveorders us into a line we don't want to play. If that wasnt bad enough, }5.Qb3 Qb6 6.Ne5! { is pretty annoying as well, and objectively best.    Other moves, like   }4...Nbd7 { , }4...e6 { , and }4...a6 { are all fine, but can be answered with }5.d4 { , after which we play a different type of Slav, once again, taking us out of book!    The harsh conclusion must be that this course is a  1.d4  repertoire and a   }1.d4 { repertoire alone. Against }1.c4 { and }1.Nf3 { , the student can not rely on the Slav Defense. } )
