8. h6( { The stem game continued }8...c5 9.dxc5 Qa5 { in Mikenas-Bogoljubow, Tallinn 1930, and here I think }10.Nxc4 Bxc3+ 11.bxc3 Qxc3+ 12.Nd2 Bc2 { ( }12...Qxc5 13.Rc1! { loses on the spot of course.)   }13.Rc1 Bxd1 14.Rxc3 Bxa4 15.Nc4 { gives White interesting compensation for the pawn. Black is surely alright, but I think the main line offers even better chances.    It should be said that   }9...Qxd1+ 10.Kxd1 Nbd7 { is an interesting alternative, as the endgame doesn't offer White much. As I mentioned though, the main line is more interesting. } )
