8. e4( { At the top level, this has largely been replaced by }8.Nxc4 { , which is explored in separate chapters! However, don't think that the current section is of less importance. }8.e4 { has an enormous history, forces Black to sacrifice a piece, and is still one of the critical tests of the variation. It may well take the central stage again someday. } )
8. Bxe4{ The point of Black's previous move. Of course, we were not planning to retreat with the bishop! The idea of this sacrifice was first mentioned by Orla Herman Krause (1867-1935) in 1926.    Krause was a doctor by profession, working in the hospital of Oringe (Denmark). His chess analysis, however, makes him known to this very day. He published his analysis in various German publications, and there are numerous discoveries that carry his name. This variation is the most famous among them.    It was in the following year that André Chéron, nowadays mostly known for his famous endgame work, published  Traite Complet d'Echecs , where he confirmed Krause's analysis. Chéron then went on to introduce the sacrifice into practice at the 1928 World Amateur Championship in The Hague. }( { Before moving on, I should briefly mention that taking on  e4  with the knight doesn't quite have the same effect: }8...Nxe4 9.fxe4 Qh4+ 10.Ke2! { ( }10.g3 Qxe4+! { is what White needs to avoid.)   }10...Bxe4 11.g3 Qh5+ 12.g4 Bd3+ 13.Kf3 { and Black is running out of steam. } )
9. fxe4
9. Nxe4
10. Qf3{ In the initial stages of this variation, this was considered to be by far the critical response. Indeed, the mating threat on  f7  and attack on the knight on  e4  pose a serious threat to the validity of Black's sacrifice. Nowadays, the move is considered to lead to a forced draw, though we will see that we can still try to keep some life in the position. }
10. Qxd4( { The only move, and a good one! Instead, }10...f5 11.Qh5+ g6 12.Nxg6 { is bad news. } )
11. Qxf7+
11. Kd8
12. Bg5+{ An important move, trying to lure away the knight from  e4 . }( 12.Qxg7?? { This horrible blunder was seen in the very first game played in the Krause Attack. Chéron reacted ruthlessly: }12...Bxc3+ 13.bxc3 Qf2+ 14.Kd1 Nxc3# { 0–1 Przepiorka-Chéron, The Hague 1928. The starting point of the entire variation! } )
12. Kc8{ Refusing the bishop on  g5 ! This king move had a dubious reputation but that is up for revision. Essentially, it leads to an endgame that was considered better for White after a model win by Georgy Borisenko back in 1951. It is amazing what impact such a game can have on a variation. There are many examples of that in chess opening history. }
13. Qxe6+
13. Nd7( 13...Kc7 14.Qf7+ Kc8 15.Qf5+ Nd7 { transposes. } )
14. Qxd7+( { Forcing the endgame I mentioned earlier. It should be noted that taking with the queen is essential. Instead, }14.Nxd7 Bxc3+ 15.bxc3 Qxc3+ 16.Ke2 Nxg5 { gives Black a winning game. After the further }17.Nb6+ Kc7 18.Nxa8+ Kb8 { , White is still a rook and bishop up, but hopelessly lost! } )
14. Qxd7
15. Nxd7
15. Nxc3
16. bxc3
16. Bxc3+
17. Kd1
17. Bxa1
18. Nc5{ After all the different captures it's time to take stock. Black has a rook and three(!) pawns for two pieces, meaning we are doing very well materially speaking. The only issue is that our army is somewhat disorganized at the moment and in need of time to get into the battle. }( { The model game Borisenko-Aronin, Lviv 1951, continued }18...b6 19.Ne6 h6?! 20.Bf4 b5 21.Be2 Kd7 22.Nc7 Rab8 23.Kc2 { and with the rook }{ coming to  d1  and fantastic overall coordination, it is clear White has a huge advantage. Aronin resigned on move 36. }{    The great Tigran Petrosian later tried to improve on this game with   }19...b5 { , but here too }20.g3!? { , planning }{ to bring the bishop to  h3 , doesn't seem entirely satisfactory. We will therefore choose an entirely different approach. } )
18. Bf6{ Offering an exchange of bishops in order to reduce the firepower of White's pieces. }
19. Bxf6( { The most obvious move. Engines also show }19.Bd2 { , but here I like the sequence }19...Rd8 20.Kc2 b5 { , when we have an improved version of the Borisenko endgame. A possible continuation is }21.Be2 Rxd2+ 22.Kxd2 Kc7 { , }{ when the engine still claims it's equal }{ (and it probably objectively is) }{ , but any human would be terrified of those queenside pawns. } )
19. gxf6
20. Bxc4
20. Re8( { An improvement over }20...b5 21.axb5 cxb5 22.Bxb5 Rb8 23.Bd3 Rb2 24.Bc2 { , which was close to equal, but not quite fully equal, in Vorobjov-Sulskis, Tallinn 2018. Moreover, I feel there is no need for us to force a draw here, as I think we can play on equal ground. } )
21. Rf1
21. b6( 21...Re5!? { is possible too. } )
22. Ne6
22. b5{ Now we see why the rook comes in handy on  e8 ! By pushing ... b6 - b5  we aim to open up the queenside so that our  a8 -rook can become active. }
23. axb5
23. cxb5
24. Bd5
24. Rb8
25. Rxf6
25. Rb6( { We are ready to push our a- and b-pawns down the board. It can no longer be said that   }10.Qf3 { is a line leading to an 'immediate draw', as both   }12...Kc8 { and }12...Nxg5 { offers Black chances of keeping the game going. } )
