14. Ke1{ This move first came to my attention when Alexander Grischuk played it against Sam Shankland in the 2015 World Team Championship. It is extremely rare, with just a handful of games played, yet engine-approved, meaning we are likely to encounter it one day. Because the king is headed for the kingside here, play is somewhat different from what we have seen thus far, where the king moved to the c-file. }
14. Qa5+{ We are going to be materialistic this time and will try to hold on to our  c4 -pawn by exchanging it on  c3 . }( { Holding on to the c-pawn in a more direct manner with }14...b5 { fails to }15.Rd1 Qc5 16.g3! { , when it's hard to come up with a good idea against the plan }{ of  Bf1 - g2  followed by  axb5 . } )( { The more standard }14...Na6 { doesn't work well here as a recent correspondence game revealed. }15.Nxc4 O-O-O { (I also had a look at }15...Rd8 { and }15...O-O { but neither appealed very much.)   }16.h4! { The rook is brought into play }{ via  h3 . }16...Nb4 ( { I think }16...Qc5 17.Rh3 Rd4 { may be a bit more tenacious, but nevertheless }18.Rc3 Qd5 19.Rd1 Nc5 20.Rxd4 Qxd4 21.Qe3 { looks pretty one-sided. } )17.Rh3 Qc5 ( 17...Qf5 18.Rc1 Qf4 19.Qe3?? Rd1+! { lead to a quick victory for Black in the Dutch encounter Piket-Ernst, the Netherlands 2003. }19.Rcc3 { is a simple improvement though, leaving White completely in control. } )18.a5 Rd4 19.Rc3 { . Over the next few moves, White will slowly disentangle and the extra piece does the rest. }19...Kb8 20.a6 Rhd8 21.Qf3 Nd5 22.Qg3+ Rf4 23.Nd2 Qd6 24.Rd3 e5 25.Rc1 { and White won a model game in Offringa-Cross, ICCF 2020. } )
15. Kf2
15. c3
16. bxc3
16. Qxc3{ One of the rare occasions in this variation where we have even four pawns for the piece, instead of three. We shall not be complaining! }
17. Rb1{ Grischuk's choice, which gave him an edge against Shankland. }
17. Nd7( { Of course, }17...b6 { would be a horrible structural weakening. } )
18. Nxd7
18. O-O-O{ The engine improvement, which prepares to recapture on  d7  with the rook and simultaneously fixes the issue on  b7 . }( { Instead, }18...Qd4+ 19.Qe3 Qxd7 20.h4 O-O 21.h5 { gave White an edge in Grischuk-Shankland, Tsaghkadzor 2015. Shankland quite comfortably held his own, and Black does have four(!) pawns for the bishop, but the proposed improvement is easier. } )
19. Qe5
19. Qc2+
20. Be2
20. Rxd7{ We have won some time compared to the Grischuk game, and it's also close to impossible for White to keep the queens on, which is why I also prefer to have our king on the queenside instead of the kingside. }
21. Rhc1{ White forces our reply, but with four pawns for the bishop, we have nothing to fear from the upcoming endgame. }
21. Qf5+( { It looks very dangerous to play }21...Qxa4 { , which makes it less surprising that a refutation like }22.Rc4! Qa6 23.Rd4 { is available. } )
22. Qxf5
22. exf5
23. a5
23. a6{ Stopping the positional threat of  a5 - a6  and a good moment to end the variation. As mentioned earlier, with four pawns for the bishop we are doing well here. Moves like ... Re8 - e5  and ... g7 - g6  come to mind, whilst Black may sometimes be able to bring the king in via  c7 - d6 - c5  as well. }
