15. Kf2
15. c3
16. bxc3
16. Qxc3{ One of the rare occasions in this variation where we have even four pawns for the piece, instead of three. We shall not be complaining! }
17. Rd1( { Not technically a novelty, as it was played in an obscure email game in 1999, but this move only got attention now, as engines started pointing it out. White rules out Black's ... Nb8 - d7  defense, which works very well against }17.Rb1 { , and plans to continue with a }{ quick  h2 - h4  and  Rh1 - h3 , to grab the initiative. } )
17. Na6( { As natural as it is to want to start with }17...O-O { in order to get the king out of the center, here it's very imprecise. The reason is that after }18.Qe4! { , we can't develop }{ our  b8 -knight (it will be taken by the bishop), and White is preparing  Bf1 - d3  with a very serious attack. Engines already scream of a winning advantage. } )
18. h4{ The only way to fight for an advantage. As so often in this line, the  h1 -rook enters the game via  h3 . }
18. Nb4( { Note that }18...Nc7 19.Rh3 Qc5+ 20.Qe3 Qxe3+ 21.Rxe3 Nd5 { transposes to  18...Nb4 . } )
19. Rh3
19. Qc5+
20. Qe3{ It looks counterintuitive to offer an exchange of queens when Black has four pawns for the piece. The upcoming endgame isn't too scary indeed. }
20. Qxe3+
21. Rxe3
21. Nd5
22. Ree1
22. Rc8{ I think this is an excellent practical solution. In order to understand why that is we have to look at the  alternatives  one by one. }
23. Rb1
23. Rc7
24. Ba6{ After any other move we would simply play ... Ke8 - e7 , with an excellent game. }
24. b6( 24...Nb6 25.a5 { doesn't help. } )
25. Rbc1{ Again very subtle, and forces us to be precise. Please note that it is extremely unlikely your opponent will be making these moves. }( 25.Rec1 { is a case of the wrong rook! Black can play }25...c5 { followed }{ by ... Ke8 - e7 , with a good game. } )
25. Nb4( { Having moved the  b1 -rook to  c1 , White has prevented the move }25...c5 { , which is now met by }26.Bc4! { with serious threats along the e-file. My engine forces me to play }26...O-O { here, but that's not where the king belongs in the endgame and is an indication that things have gone wrong. After }27.g4 { , we have another case of White totally dominating all over the board. Our queenside pawns aren't going anywhere, and on the kingside not much is happening either. White, in the meantime, can improve the position at will. } )
26. Bb5
26. Ke7{ The point of our 25th move − we are ready to give up on the pawn to get fully coordinated. }
27. Nxc6+( 27.Bxc6 Rhc8 { simply wins material. } )
27. Nxc6
28. Rxc6
28. Rxc6
29. Bxc6
29. Rc8{ The dust has cleared and what remains is a pretty clear-cut position. We have given back one pawn but have fully mobilized our remaining pieces. Despite what the engine initially proclaims, the endgame is balanced. }( { If we follow the machine's first line }30.Bb5 f5 31.Rd1 Rc7 32.Kf3 g6 33.Kf4 Kf6 { (intending to build a }{ mating net with ... Rc7 - c3  followed by ... e6 - e5  mate!), it slowly dawns on it that Black is indeed completely fine. We have no weaknesses and can simply await developments. As a final note, in all the endgames we have seen the drawing margin is usually pretty big, meaning that even if we make an error along the way, usually the position will still be holdable. } )
