6. e3( { The so-called Dutch Variation. It is named that way because of the contributions of Max Euwe in this line, in particular in his 1937 match against Alexander Alekhine where he employed the variation five times. Contrary to the other main line, }6.Ne5 { , this move leads to quieter, more strategic play. } )
6. e6
7. Bxc4
7. Bb4{ Allowing us to castle on the next move. On  b4  the bishop is better placed as it, indirectly, fights for the  e4 -square by attacking the knight on  c3 . }( { Less good is }7...Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Qe2 { , when it's easier for White to }{ get  e3 - e4  in. } )
8. O-O
8. O-O( { I prefer this move over }8...Nbd7 { , which is often used to provoke White into sacrificing a pawn. The problem is that this pawn sacrifice is actually very strong. }9.Qe2 Bg6 10.e4! Bxc3 { (Better is }10...O-O { , which transposes to one of the main lines.)   }11.bxc3 Nxe4 12.Ba3 { and White has tremendous compensation, as Black's king is stuck in the center. } )
