1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. a4( { Isolating the pawn on  c4  is the best way to go. By preventing ... b7 - b5 , White prepares to regain the  c4 -pawn. As we will see, the alternatives }5.e4 b5 { ,   }5.e3 b5 6.a4 b4 { , and   }5.g3 b5 { leave Black in excellent shape. } )
5. Bf5{ Not just developing the bishop but also preventing  e2 - e4 . Our development scheme is quite clear: in random order, we will play ... e7 - e6 , ... Bf8 - b4 , ... O-O , and ... Nb8 - d7 . Once we achieve that, we can start looking for central breaks connected to ... c6 - c5  and ... e6 - e5 . }
6. Nh4{ Statistically speaking, you will meet this move about once in every fifteen games. If we retreat our bishop, White can choose to either repeat moves by dropping back to  f3  as well, or to seize the center with  e2 - e4 . Those are scenarios we won't bother with though, as we don't retreat our bishop. }
6. e6{ I remember this move came as a bit of a surprise to me when I first saw it many years ago. We give up the bishop and our structure gets fractured in the process! Things are a bit more subtle than that though as we will see. }( { As a surprise weapon, the move }6...Bg6!? { is not too bad. After }7.Nxg6 hxg6 { , Black has a solid structure and the likes of Bareev and Gelfand have proven the validity of this position. It's important that the complications that arise following }8.e4 e5! { are OK for Black. } )
7. Nxf5
7. exf5
8. e3{ This is a good moment to take stock and think about what this position is about. White is about to take back on  c4  and there is not much we can do about that. Instead, we should think about where our pieces belong.    Our ideal scenario is to have a setup where we move our  f8 -bishop to  d6 , the  b8 -knight to  d5 , castle kingside, and bring our rooks to  d8  and  e8  and our queen, let's say, on  e6 . Once we have that, we can throw in moves like ... h7 - h5 - h4  and start harassing White's king that is likely to castle on that wing.    Note that we don't mind having doubled f-pawns. In fact, it gives us a half-open e-file and good control over the  e4 -square. On top of that, we may be able to throw in ... f5 - f4  sometimes to cause problems for White's pawn structure. }
8. Bd6( { Historically, this is not the most popular move, but I am not sure that is justified. We already said the bishop is well placed on  d6 , and therefore, I prefer to go there immediately rather than the most played move in the position, which is }8...Bb4 { . } )
9. Bxc4
9. O-O
10. Qf3{ This move is the reason why the bishop is usually placed on  b4 , from where it pins the knight and supposedly would give better chances for counterplay. The plan with  h3 - g4  was just considered too dangerous for Black here. }
10. Qd7( { This may look a bit unnatural, but I don't like the positions after }10...g6 11.h3 { , when White is }{ ready to play  g2 - g4 , even if Black plays }11...h5 { . It is quite telling that the engine indicates }11...Bb4 { as the best move here! } )( { After }10...Qd7 { , we don't weaken our king position. }{ The  b8 -knight is less happy with this move but will find a good route into the game via  a6  and  b4 . } )
11. h3
11. Na6( { In Van Wely-Chernin, Taastrup 1992, }11...c5 { was played, but I think }12.dxc5 Bxc5 13.O-O { gives White a pleasant edge. } )
12. Bd3{ This makes more sense now, compared to  move 11 , as that line ended with ... c6 - c5  with the idea to follow up with a quick ... Nb8 - c6 . Here we have already committed our knight to  a6 . }
12. g6
13. g4
13. Nb4
14. Bb1{ This looks problematic for us at first since  f5  can no longer be protected. }
14. c5{ We hit in the center again. }
15. gxf5
15. cxd4
16. exd4
16. Nc6( 16...Qc6!? { is an option as well, transposing after }17.Qxc6 bxc6 18.O-O Rab8 { to the  15.O-O variation . While this is a completely fine and playable endgame, keeping the queens on with   }16...Nc6 { is the more ambitious option. } )
17. Be3
17. Bb4{ Simply threatening to take on  d4 . }
18. fxg6
18. fxg6
19. Ba2+
19. Kg7
20. O-O-O{ White has found a sophisticated way to protect the d-pawn, but the king on  c1  now becomes a target. }
20. Bxc3
