6. b4{ Back in 1920, when Alekhine first employed this variation, it was very unclear to the masters of those times how to assess the inclusion of the moves  a2 - a4  and ... b5 - b4 .    It was thought that it may well favor White, and indeed if White manages to regain the pawn on  c4  and reroute the attacked  c3 -knight, the squares on the queenside may well be used to White's advantage.    For that though, White needs time, and the appreciation and understanding of time in chess has improved greatly over the past 100 years. To a modern grandmaster, it is quite obvious that this line doesn't promise White anything. }
7. Na2{ Attacking both  b4  and  c4 . We are ready to give back the  c4 -pawn, making sure the knight on  a2  will take a while to get back in the game. }
7. e6
8. Bxc4
8. Bb7{ A fairly normal Meran type of position has arisen, where White's knight on  a2  is somewhat misplaced. }( { The text move is the cleanest way to proceed since }8...Nbd7 { instead hands White the additional option of }9.a5 { , when obviously }9...Bb7 { would be met by the unpleasant }10.a6 { . Of course, we can take the pawn on  a5 , but after   }9...Qxa5 10.Bd2 { , }{ threatening  Na2xb4 , }10...Qb6 11.Qa4 { , Black doesn't have access to }11...a5 { because of the hanging rook on  a8 . If we follow the same variation but with the bishop on  b7  instead, }{   }11...a5 { would already yield a significant advantage for us. } )
