12. e4( { The plan }12.Bd2 a5 13.Nc1 { is possible but doesn't quite equalize. We play }13...c5!? 14.Nb3 Qb6 { , with a small edge. }{ Our  b7 -bishop does a great job restricting White. } )
12. a5( { It is interesting for the evolution of this line though, to hear what Alekhine has to say about this position. Through a transposition, we have returned back into his game with Tarrasch.    Alekhine points out 'the  a5 -pawn could become weak, but not playing }12...a5 { would run }{ into  Na2 - c1 - b3  and  a4 - a5 - a6 .' For modern standards, calling the pawn on  a5  a potential weakness is a bit abstract, and so far Tarrasch played very well. It is only after Alekhine's next move that he falters. } )
13. Bg5
