1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2{ An interesting waiting move that always had a decent following. While protecting  c4 , Black is given the move yet deprived of the natural ... Bc8 - f5  development. }( 4...g6 { is a popular move in this position yet commits to a kingside fianchetto, which may not be to everyone's liking. In choosing the move }4...dxc4 { , I also took into account that we can use this against both   }4.Qc2 { and }4.Qb3 { , saving us the trouble of having to learn two different systems. }4.Qb3 dxc4 5.Qxc4 { transposes to  4.Qc2 . } )
4. dxc4( { We react in the same way as after  4.Nc3 . White now has a choice to simply recapture, or play in gambit style with }5.e4 { . } )
5. e4{ Typical gambit play. White won't see the pawn returned any time soon but get's central control in return. This pawn sac has been played by the likes of Carlsen, Grischuk, Caruana, Andreikin, and Firouzja, just to name a few! }
5. b5{ We, of course, hang on to the pawn, otherwise White would simply recapture on  c4  while also occupying the center. }
6. b3{ Fairly typical as well, and the main direction in this line. White exchanges the  c4 -pawn for the b-pawn in order to open the a- and c-files, and the  d3 -square may also come in handy sometimes for the  f1 -bishop. }
6. cxb3( { We are forced to take, though, for players wanting to pick up this line with White, it may be useful to know the variation that starts with }6...Qa5+ 7.Bd2 cxb3 { . Now }8.axb3! { is very strong, as }( 8.Qxb3 Qa4 { , or }8...Qb6 { , also gives White fine compensation but is less clear. } )8...Qxa1 9.Bxb5! { crashes through. Black can't take that bishop due to mate in 1 and besides that, the queen }{ on  a1  is on the verge of being trapped. The engine panics into }9...Qxb1+ 10.Qxb1 cxb5 { , which is fine from a materialistic standpoint, yet the simple }11.O-O Nbd7 12.d5 { leaves Black struggling. } )
7. axb3
7. e6( { The most natural move in the position. }7...g6 { is not completely out of the question, but I am not a fan. So far though, practice has seen White struggling to prove compensation. For instance, after the most played move }8.Bd2 Bg7 9.Ba5 Qd7 { , Black is doing perfectly fine. Important is that }10.Nbd2 O-O 11.b4 { , which looks }{ pretty at first, preparing  Nd2 - b3 , and fixing the queenside, is well met with }11...e5! 12.dxe5 Ng4 { and }{ with  e5  falling, Black is for choice. } )( { I don't recommend }7...g6 { because of }8.Nc3 { , when }8...Bg7 9.e5! Bf5 10.Bd3 Bxd3 11.Qxd3 Nd5 { , at first sight, may look fine for Black, but }12.h4! { is annoying, as it starts a kingside initiative that is surprisingly hard to nip in the bud. Pushing }12...h5 { runs into }13.e6! { , for instance, as the pawn }{ on  g6  has now lost some protection. Engines also prefer White. } )( { In short, }7...g6 { can be used as a surprise weapon, as most players tend to go for }8.Bd2 { , but if White plays }8.Nc3 { instead, the position may be a bit suspicious. } )
8. Bd3( { All the top players I previously mentioned went for this move, instead of the most popular continuation, }8.Bd2 { . } )
8. a5{ We still play this move, which prepares the typical ... Nb8 - a6 - b4 . It is nice to see a sample line of how things can go terribly wrong for Black so that we know what we are trying to avoid. }( { After the natural }8...Bb7 9.O-O Be7 10.Nc3 { , Black faces issues. Castling isn't possible, as }10...O-O 11.e5! { loses the  h7 -pawn. Another natural idea is to play }{   }10...Nbd7 { , which isn't great either, as }11.e5! Nd5 12.Nxd5 { gives Black the choice }{ to give up on the  b5 -pawn or play the extremely undesirable }12...exd5 { .    Last but not least,   }10...Na6 11.Qe2 Nb4 12.Bb1 { has been seen in a recent Grischuk-Goryachkina blitz game. This looks attractive for White, as it's hard for Black to find a safe spot for the }{ king on  e8 . In general, this setup, which I will refer to as the Grischuk setup from now on, is what White should be aiming for, and we should prevent White from reaching it by bringing our knight to  b4  as soon as possible. } )
9. Nc3( { New and a very tricky attempt! White aims to meet }9...Na6 { with }10.Qe2 { and }10...Nb4 { with }11.Bb1 { , in order to get the Grischuk setup. } )( 9.Bd2 { would now transpose back to the  8.Bd2 variation , but it is White's intention to play an improved version of that line, omitting }{ the move  Bd2 . } )
9. Na6
10. Qe2
10. Bb4{ Not a very logical follow-up perhaps, as the knight is destined for  b4 , but on the other hand, White has moved the queen away from  c2  meaning the knight on  c3  lacks protection. On top of that, we have a concrete follow-up in mind. }( 10...Nb4 11.Bb1 { followed by  O-O , allows White to reach the Grischuk setup. } )
11. Bb2
11. e5{ A great push! White's mighty center is suddenly under serious pressure. }
12. O-O{ An attempt to make the most of things, though 'most' may, objectively, not mean much. We have to be on our toes here though. }( { Instead, }12.dxe5 Nh5 13.g3 O-O { followed by moves }{ like ... Bc8 - g4 , ... Na6 - c5 , and ... Qd8 - e7  gives Black a big edge. } )( 12.d5 O-O { isn't very critical either, and the engines rightly give us a small edge already. } )
12. exd4
13. Nxb5{ Trying to cause as much trouble as possible now that the king is still on  e8 . }
13. cxb5
14. Bxb5+
14. Nd7
15. Nxd4{ Not just recapturing the pawn but also preparing to bring the knight to  f5 . }
15. Nc7( 15...O-O 16.Nf5 Nf6 17.Nxg7! Kxg7 18.Rfd1 { intending  Rd3 - g3  looks tricky. Black may hold after }18...Qb6 { , but I would prefer to avoid the position after }19.Rac1! { , as the text move is less complicated. } )
16. Bc4
16. Ne5{ Yes, the position is still sharp, but we are up material and the engine is on our side. If we survive the next few moves, we should have a big advantage. That in itself is good news! }( { I find this the trickiest line within   }5.e4 { , as   }9.Nc3 { takes us out of our usual setup and forces us to play a different solution with   }10...Bb4 { followed by }11.Bb2 e5 { . } )
