5. Nc3
5. e6
6. Nh4{ Here we are faced with a major choice. Where to move our bishop? Moving it we must since  Nh4xf5  can't be allowed − it would harm our structure too much. }( { Historically, the move }6...Bg6 { has been played most, but it's still an open debate whether first }{ provoking  f2 - f3 , }{ with }6...Be4 7.f3 { before dropping back to  g6  is an improved version. On the one hand, the pawn on  f3  could just indeed be ruining the integrity of White's pawn structure, but it can also be the launching pad for a future  e3 - e4  push. The jury is still out! } )( { For this repertoire, I have chosen the solid }6...Bg6 { . I like the resulting positions, which are very straightforward in nature and understandable, whereas the lines after }6...Be4 { are often sharper. } )( { On a final note, I should mention }6...Bg4 { , which is not that popular anymore these days. That probably has to do with Veselin Topalov who, after   }4...Bg4 { , introduced the line }5.Nc3 e6 6.Qb3 Qb6 7.Nh4!? { in 2008, playing against the }{ bishop on  g4 . } )( { If we switch back to }6...Bg4 { , here }7.Qb3 Qb6 { reaches that same position but with a full extra tempo for White. That can't be good news! Jorden van Foreest made an attempt to revive this line by playing }7...dxc4 8.Qxb7 Nbd7 { , but venturing here is at your own risk! } )
6. Bg6
7. Be2{ The second most popular move in the position. White doesn't take our bishop just yet, but first castles kingside, waiting for the right moment. }
7. Nbd7
8. O-O
8. Be7( { I always thought that }8...Ne4 9.g3 Nd6 { looked very pretty, but modern engines like White after }10.c5 Nf5 11.Nxg6 hxg6 12.b4 { , when White is quite fast on the queenside, and it is not that easy for us to generate play in the center or kingside. } )( 8...Bd6 { is the other main move, and after }9.g3 { , both }9...O-O { and }9...dxc4 { lead to very playable positions. Interesting as well is the provocative }9...Qe7 { , after which it is once again a question of how }10.c5 Bc7 11.b4 { is to be assessed, as other avenues don't offer White much. This is certainly a better version than the position mentioned above after  8...Ne4 , but nevertheless, requires careful study before playing it. If Black plays inaccurately over the next few moves, White will just storm the queenside and win. } )
9. g3( 9.Nxg6 hxg6 10.g3 dxc4 { would transpose. } )
9. dxc4{ An interesting decision that essentially forces White to take on  g6 . }( { Of course, }9...O-O { isn't that bad, but }10.Nxg6 hxg6 { does give White the type of game they are after − a pair of bishops and a long stable advantage. } )
10. Nxg6( { Making sure the bishop doesn't escape to  h5 , as would be the case after }10.Bxc4 { . } )
10. hxg6
11. Bxc4
11. Qa5( { This is one of the points. The queen can often swing over to the kingside, to make something happen on the h-file. That is, for instance, the case after }12.Bd2 Qf5 { . } )
12. Bd3( { Gelfand's choice, which prevents the queen from reaching  f5 . }12.e4 { serves that same purpose but does make the center look a bit vulnerable after }12...Rd8 { (or }12...b5!? { first). } )
12. Rd8{ I like this move a lot. We still keep the king on  e8  for now, as the h-file may prove useful sometimes, but in the meantime, bringing the rook to  d8  prepares for breaks in the center connected to ... e6 - e5  and ... c6 - c5 . }
13. Bd2
13. Qc7{ Okay, so mate on the h-file is not happening, but now ... e6 - e5  is an unstoppable break. }
14. Rc1
14. e5( { Black was fine in Gelfand-Goryachkina, Riga 2021. In fact, after }15.Qf3 { , she could have seized the initiative with }15...Nc5!  )
