1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. cxd5{ The Exchange Variation − often described as boring, but I beg to differ. The resulting positions, especially when White is playing for a win, are very interesting and in fact full of life. If White wishes to make a draw, then we have to learn to be patient and seize every small opportunity we get. Taking this task seriously can truly improve your strength as a player.    Looking at the database, one sees that on all levels there are many decisive games in this variation. Humans make mistakes, and having a symmetrical pawn structure doesn't change the fact we still have a board full of pieces. Our first task is to acquaint ourselves with the necessary theoretical knowledge, so as not to get into trouble.    I often see players behind the black pieces rushing to make active moves in this variation; a completely wrong approach. Patience is key, and that means we first have to neutralize White's extra move, before thinking about taking over. }( { A few things about the move order. I believe the best move order for White is connected to }3.cxd5 cxd5 4.Bf4 { , but White can also play   }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 5.Bf4 { , which will transpose. The move order   }3.Nf3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 { is covered under   }3.cxd5 cxd5 4.Nf3 { . } )
3. cxd5
4. Bf4( { Having seen the other move orders we can now appreciate why this is considered the cleanest one. }4.Nc3 { allows }4...e5 { , while   }4.Nf3 { commits the knight to  f3  when White would prefer to stay flexible. } )
4. Nc6( 4...Nf6 5.e3 Nc6 { would  transpose . } )
5. Nc3( { This may just lead to a transposition if we play }5...Nf6 { here, but there is an interesting alternative. } )
5. e5{ Of the lines where Black throws in ... e7 - e5 , this is probably the best version, as we have already developed the  b8 -knight, and the bishop on  f4  is awkwardly placed. }
6. Bxe5{ Taking the pawn while also getting a set of minor pieces off the board is White's best bet. }
6. Nxe5
7. dxe5
7. d4
8. Ne4
8. Bb4+
9. Nd2
9. Ne7{ Our compensation lies in the fact that the  d4 -pawn somewhat hampers White's development, and the  e5 -pawn is weak and is likely to fall. On top of that, we have the pair of bishops. }
10. Ngf3
10. O-O
11. g3
11. Nd5( { The key idea. There is no fun in }11...Nc6 12.Bg2 { , when Black is either a bit worse or forced to play }12...d3 13.O-O Nxe5! 14.Nxe5 dxe2 15.Qxe2 Qxd2 16.Qxd2 Bxd2 { , where White is still a bit better, and what's worse, it's risk-free. } )
12. Nxd4( { The critical test. }12.a3 Ba5 { transposes to the  11.a3 variation . } )
12. Bg4( { After }12...Qb6 { , there follows }13.e3 { , which explains our move. }{ Pinning the pawn on  e2  makes ... Qd8 - b6  a threat, as well as ... Bb4 - c3 !? } )
13. Bg2
13. Bc3{ As strange as it sounds, this move forces a draw. }( 13...Qb6 { is a move here as well, but White has the neat tactic }14.O-O!? Qxd4 15.Nb3 { , which somewhat surprisingly wins back the piece, as }15...Qxd1 16.Rfxd1 { threatens both the knight }{ on  d5  and  Rd1 - d4 . } )
14. h3
14. Bxd4
15. hxg4
15. Bxf2+{ Without this move, it would have all been for nothing. }
16. Kxf2
16. Qb6+
17. Ke1( { A winning attempt with }17.e3 { seems very risky. Black just plays }17...Nxe3 18.Qb3 Nxg4+ 19.Kf3 Nxe5+ 20.Ke2 Qa6+ 21.Kf2 Rad8 { , keeping very serious pressure against White's open king. } )
17. Ne3
18. Be4
18. Nxd1( 18...f5 19.Nc4! { saves the day. } )
19. Bxh7+
19. Kh8{ White should repeat moves by shuffling the bishop back and forth. }( { We can conclude that while   }5...e5 { surely isn't winning by any stretch of the imagination, it is quite challenging for White. On top of that, it is not very well known, meaning I doubt most of our opponents will be ready to meet it. After all, when you prepare to play the Exchange Slav, why choose this move order over   }5.e3?  )
