7. Bb4( { In the stem game, Bogoljubov opted for }7...Be7 { , which Alekhine rightly condemned as being a bit passive. At the same time, there probably isn't that much wrong with the move either. Certainly in the game, after }8.f3 ( 8.Nxc4 { is preferable, with an approximately equal game. } )8...h6 9.e4?! { had Black played }9...hxg5 10.exf5 Nbd7 11.fxe6 fxe6 { , it wouldn't have been easy for Alekhine to prove compensation. One of the issues is that }12.Bxc4 Nxe5 13.dxe5 { allows Black to exchange queens and follow it up by plonking }{ a knight on  d5 , with a clearly better endgame. }{    Instead, Bogoljubov played   }9...Bh7?! { and after }10.Be3 { , Alekhine got a dream position and won a model game (Alekhine-Bogoljubov, Game 5, World Championship 1929). } )( 7...Bb4 { is clearly preferable }{ and  b4  is the natural square for our bishop in the Slav. The next time Bogoljubov encountered  7.Bg5 , he indeed improved on his play with this move. It was also Euwe's choice in his 1937 return match against Alekhine. } )
8. e3( { Very timid, and not in keeping with the idea behind  7.Bg5 , which is to set up a broad center. The more important }8.f3 { would  transpose  to   }7.f3 Bb4 8.Bg5 { . } )
