13. Bxa4( { An invitation we happily accept. This move entails a promising exchange sacrifice. Before, both Huebner and Torre, the latter no less than four times, had successfully defended the endgame after }13...Bh7 { . It isn't much fun though, with White enjoying a pleasant and risk-free edge. } )
14. Bxf6{ It's important to eliminate the knight before it gets to  d5 . }
14. gxf6
15. Ra1
15. Bb3( { A year earlier, GM Curt Hansen had opted for }15...Bc6 16.Nb6 Nd7 { ( }16...axb6! 17.Rxa8 bxc5 { followed }{ by ... b7 - b5  gives Black fine compensation.) }{   }17.Nxa8 Rxa8 { , after which White was a bit better and indeed went on to win in Petursson-Hansen, Reykjavik 1985.   }15...Bb3 { is a small refinement. } )
16. Nb6
16. Nc6
17. Nxa8
17. Rxa8{ A stunning concept, which Evgeny Bareev was confronted with at the URS Championship under 20, in 1986. Inspired by that game, he used it himself to defeat Beliavsky in the same year! Black has invested a full exchange but is about to pick up  c5  and has an ongoing initiative.    Engines hoover around the 0.00 mark, with a slight inclination towards Black. From a human perspective though, I would lean towards Black more than just a little. Defending a position like this is very hard in a practical game. It is for this reason the line is currently out of practice. }
18. e3
18. Bxc5
19. Kf2( 19.Be2 Bxe3 20.Bd1 Bc4 21.Be2 Bb3 22.Bd1 Bc4 23.Be2 { was agreed drawn in Brunner-Huebner, Solingen 1986, but   }19...Nb4! { would have been very awkward to face for White. } )
19. f5
20. g3{ Beliavsky's choice, with the intent to prevent ... f5 - f4 . It's too slow and gives Black the time to invade with the rook. }
20. Rd8
21. Be2
21. Rd2( { Black is clearly better. The game Beliavsky-Bareev, Kyiv 1986, continued }22.f4 Nb4 23.Kf3 Nd5 24.Rhc1 Nxe3 25.Ra5 Bd4 26.Rb5 Rxb2 27.Na4 Rc2 { and White resigned. It goes to show just in how much trouble White is already that a player of the caliber of Beliavsky lost it in a mere 6 moves. } )
