12. e4( { The critical moment. Now }12...Bg6 13.Bf4 Nc6 14.Qb5! { gives White some hope of an advantage. } )
12. Bd6{ Very strong. The attack on the  e5 -knight is very hard to meet for White. }
13. Nd3( 13.exf5 Qxe5+ { followed by taking on  f5  would be making things too easy for us! } )
13. Bg6( { Another very important move, and, in fact, a novelty! Ever since a game Pinter-Beliavsky, played in 1987, it was considered that }13...Bg3+ 14.Kd1 Bg6 { was the right course of action, giving Black a good game. However, Stockfish comes up with the new }15.Rh3! { , which seems highly unpleasant for Black. After the further }15...Be5 ( 15...Nh5 16.Ne2! { kicks the bishop away from  g3 , after which  g2 - g4  will be decisive. }{ And   }15...Qc7 16.Qxc7 Bxc7 17.Nb5 { is horrible as well. } )16.Qb5! { Black is in trouble since the endgame after }16...Qxb5 17.axb5 { is awful, while   }16...Bxc3 17.bxc3 Qxc3 18.Bb2 Qc7 19.Bxf6 gxf6 20.h5 { loses a piece. It means Black has to bail out with   }17...Nc6 { , but that endgame is not going to be much fun either. } )( 13...Bg6 { keeps the check }{ on  g3  in reserve and simply prepares ... Nb8 - c6  followed by centralizing the rooks to  c8  and  d8 . } )
14. Be3
14. Nc6
15. Be2
15. Rac8
16. Kf2( { Safer than }16.O-O { , after which }16...Nh5 { reminds White of the dark-squared }{ weaknesses on  f4  and  g3 . } )
16. a6{ It is useful to take away the  b5 -square from White's queen or knight. According to the engines, Black is to be preferred here and I can only agree. We may continue with ... Qa5 - c7  to start play on the dark squares  f4  and  g3 . }
