6. Ne5{ This has always been considered the most critical response, even from the early days of this variation. White does not necessarily intend to take back the pawn on  c4  with the knight but, more importantly, prepares to set up a big center with  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 , in order to embarrass Black's light-squared bishop and knight on  f6 . A very ambitious plan indeed that, if carried out successfully, would give White a big advantage. }
6. e6( { While, at first sight, this does not seem to counter White's intentions, it will soon become apparent that it does. The alternative }6...Nbd7 { is very reliable as well, which is why I offer both moves as part of this Lifetime Repertoire. Note that the direct }6...c5? { is met with }7.e4! { , with the idea that }7...Nxe4 8.Qf3 { leads to immediate trouble. } )
7. f3
7. Bb4
8. Bg5{ An old continuation that shouldn't cause us too much trouble, given we are aware of the details. }
8. h6( { The stem game continued }8...c5 9.dxc5 Qa5 { in Mikenas-Bogoljubow, Tallinn 1930, and here I think }10.Nxc4 Bxc3+ 11.bxc3 Qxc3+ 12.Nd2 Bc2 { ( }12...Qxc5 13.Rc1! { loses on the spot of course.)   }13.Rc1 Bxd1 14.Rxc3 Bxa4 15.Nc4 { gives White interesting compensation for the pawn. Black is surely alright, but I think the main line offers even better chances.    It should be said that   }9...Qxd1+ 10.Kxd1 Nbd7 { is an interesting alternative, as the endgame doesn't offer White much. As I mentioned though, the main line is more interesting. } )
9. Bh4
9. c5( { Initially, the engine sent me in a different direction, one that intends to hold on to the  c4 –pawn. I choose the text move though, as }9...b5!? 10.e4 Bh7 11.Be2 Qb6 { ( }11...O-O 12.O-O Qb6 { transposes.)   }12.O-O O-O 13.Bf2 { didn't look that clear to me. Certainly explore this line though, if you like the idea of defending an extra pawn. } )
10. dxc5
10. Qa5
11. Nxc4( { One of the upsides of including the moves   }8...h6 9.Bh4 { is seen in this line. } )
11. Bxc3+
12. bxc3
12. Qxc3+
13. Nd2
13. Bc2
14. Rc1{ So far exactly the same as in the note on move 8. Now we deviate. }
14. Qb4( { Making use of the fact that the bishop is now on  h4 ! }14...Bxd1 15.Rxc3 Bxa4 { is a similar endgame I mentioned in the note on }{ move 8. Black is surely fine, but not more than that. } )
15. Qxc2
15. Qxh4+
16. g3
16. Qd4{ Objectively, the position is still more or less equal, but I'd certainly take Black here. }
