8. Nxc4( { For some years now, this has replaced }8.e4 { as the main move at the top level. I am not at all sure it will remain that way, but in any case, we need to be on top of things! While }8.Nxc4 { has been played almost a hundred years ago, it is the remarkable follow-up that caused a revival in 2009. } )
8. O-O( 8...Nd5 9.Bd2! { with the idea }9...Qh4+ 10.g3 Qxd4 11.e4! Nxc3 12.bxc3 Bxc3 13.Ra2± { has been considered bad for Black ever since the game Giri-Harikrishna, Wijk aan Zee 2010. } )( { Another disaster is }8...c5 9.dxc5 Qxd1+ 10.Kxd1 Bxc5 { since after the simple }11.e4 Bg6 12.Nb5! { , Black's kingside pieces are completely out of play. } )
9. Kf2{ This is the incredible move that caused the revival of the entire variation. By stepping out of the pin, White prepares the  e2 - e4  push. Of course, casually playing the king on  f2  is an enormously far-reaching decision, and frankly, when I saw this move for the first time, I thought it must be a move that can only be played as a surprise weapon. After the surprise is gone, surely Black would be able to avoid whatever tricks there are in the position and should be doing fine. }( { It was French GM Laurent Fressinet who introduced }9.Kf2 { into practice in 2009, and I must say, despite my initial doubts, the move is still going strong! In the early stages of this variation, practice saw Black players trying to punish White for the indiscretion }{ committed on move 9. }{    The stem game Fressinet-Solak, Eforie Nord 2009, for instance, continued with }9...b5 { , which is obviously a very direct attempt. After }10.axb5 cxb5 11.Nxb5 Nc6 12.e3 { , Black's compensation is not that obvious. I also tried to make   }9...Nd5 { work, as }10.e4 Nxc3 11.bxc3 Bxc3 { is fine for Black. Stronger is   }10.Na2! { though, and now }10...b5 12.Ne5 f6 13.Ng4 Bxg4 14.e4! { is the key idea that seems to give White an advantage. This line can be explored further but I was unable to make the complications work for Black.    Initially, players moved on to   }9...c5 { under the influence of the engines of that time. This was, after all, their main recommendation in those days. In 2009 engines had trouble evaluating the position that ensues after }10.e4 Bxc3 11.bxc3 Bxe4 12.fxe4 Nxe4 13.Kg1 Nxc3 14.Qe1 cxd4 { , when Black has four pawns for the piece. It was in the world of correspondence chess that this line was explored further, and it was quickly established that }15.Ba3 { , as well as the simple }15.h4 { , }{ intending  h5  and, if allowed,  h6 , gives White a clear advantage.    Trying to improve on the above line with }{   }10...Bg6 { also doesn't cut it after }11.Na2! { going after Black's bishop. Now }11...Nc6 12.Nxb4 Nxb4 { is excellent for White, but the most natural move in the position should be avoided. }13.Be3 cxd4 14.Bxd4 Bxe4! { is great for Black because of }15.fxe4 Nxe4+ 16.Kg1 Nc2! { when trouble is looming.    Instead, both the most played move in the position,   }13.Qb3 { , as well as the move that is indicated by modern engines }13.Bd2!? { with the idea }13...Qxd4 14.Be3 { , give White a sizable advantage.    As a result, }9...c5 { is rarely seen in practice these days, though historically it's still the most played move in the position. Around this time, it also dawned on people that this line was here to stay, as there is no easy solution for Black.    Attention then moved to less direct options. One of them is }9...Bg6 { , anticipating the move }10.e4 { , after which there are a number of options. }10...Nbd7 { comes to mind, in order to remain flexible and simply develop in the meantime. Another option is }10...Nfd7 { , when the idea }{ of ... f7 - f5  is introduced in the position as well. All of the above is very reasonable, though engines give a slight preference for White. }{    It turns out we can improve on }9...Bg6 { with the move }9...h6!? { intending after }10.e4 { to bring }{ the bishop back to  h7 . This is a similarly flexible setup to  9...Bg6 , but just a bit more precise. With Black, we can aim for all three breaks in the center, ... c6 - c5 , ... e6 - e5 , and ... f7 - f5 . }{    Just when the approach to this line switched from concrete (  }9...b5 { , }9...c5 { ) to positional/long-term }{ ( }9...Bg6 { , }9...h6 { ), Fabiano Caruana introduced the stunning novelty }9...e5 { in 2020 Candidates Tournament. Despite losing that game to Ding Liren, analysis showed he was completely fine. I have added it as an  alternative  to our main line. It turns out there are indeed two valid approaches to this variation: the positional way with }9...h6 { , and the direct one with }9...e5 { − it is good to have the option of throwing out either. } )
