5. a4( { Isolating the pawn on  c4  is the best way to go. By preventing ... b7 - b5 , White prepares to regain the  c4 -pawn. As we will see, the alternatives }5.e4 b5 { ,   }5.e3 b5 6.a4 b4 { , and   }5.g3 b5 { leave Black in excellent shape. } )
5. Bf5{ Not just developing the bishop but also preventing  e2 - e4 . Our development scheme is quite clear: in random order, we will play ... e7 - e6 , ... Bf8 - b4 , ... O-O , and ... Nb8 - d7 . Once we achieve that, we can start looking for central breaks connected to ... c6 - c5  and ... e6 - e5 . }
6. Ne5{ This has always been considered the most critical response, even from the early days of this variation. White does not necessarily intend to take back the pawn on  c4  with the knight but, more importantly, prepares to set up a big center with  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 , in order to embarrass Black's light-squared bishop and knight on  f6 . A very ambitious plan indeed that, if carried out successfully, would give White a big advantage. }
6. e6( { While, at first sight, this does not seem to counter White's intentions, it will soon become apparent that it does. The alternative }6...Nbd7 { is very reliable as well, which is why I offer both moves as part of this Lifetime Repertoire. Note that the direct }6...c5? { is met with }7.e4! { , with the idea that }7...Nxe4 8.Qf3 { leads to immediate trouble. } )
7. f3
7. Bb4
8. Nxc4( { For some years now, this has replaced }8.e4 { as the main move at the top level. I am not at all sure it will remain that way, but in any case, we need to be on top of things! While }8.Nxc4 { has been played almost a hundred years ago, it is the remarkable follow-up that caused a revival in 2009. } )
8. O-O( 8...Nd5 9.Bd2! { with the idea }9...Qh4+ 10.g3 Qxd4 11.e4! Nxc3 12.bxc3 Bxc3 13.Ra2± { has been considered bad for Black ever since the game Giri-Harikrishna, Wijk aan Zee 2010. } )( { Another disaster is }8...c5 9.dxc5 Qxd1+ 10.Kxd1 Bxc5 { since after the simple }11.e4 Bg6 12.Nb5! { , Black's kingside pieces are completely out of play. } )
9. Kf2{ This is the incredible move that caused the revival of the entire variation. By stepping out of the pin, White prepares the  e2 - e4  push. For an in-depth overview of  9.Kf2 , check the  Informational . }
9. h6{ A modest-looking pawn move, that prepares for the  f5 -bishop to be tucked away on  h7 . }
10. e4
10. Bh7{ White has managed to build a broad center, which was the objective behind  9.Kf2 . It isn't the end of the story though. The king on  f2  still makes an odd impression and getting it to complete safety will take some time. On top of that, White also still needs to finish the general development.    Black, on the other hand, only has a dormant knight on  b8  but other than that is ready to start active operations. Those active operations are usually focused on attacking White's center. That can be done with ... c6 - c5 , ... e6 - e5 , or, the most common one, by preparing ... f7 - f5 . }
11. Be3
11. a5
12. g4{ This push makes more sense with the  f1 -bishop developed to  e2 , when the  c1 -bishop anyway participates in the attack on the  c1 - h6  diagonal and White has the extra option of switching the queen over to  g1 . }
12. b5( { The most forceful reply. Note that Black has plenty of alternatives at this point, like }12...Ne8 { for instance. } )
13. axb5
13. cxb5
14. Nxb5
14. Nxe4+( 14...Nxg4+ 15.fxg4 Bxe4 { transposes. } )
15. fxe4
15. Bxe4
16. Bd3{ Essentially a draw, as the following forced sequence can't be avoided by either player. }( { The desirable }16.Bg2 { loses to }16...Bxg2 17.Kxg2 Qd5+ 18.Qf3 Qxb5 { because }19.Qxa8 Nc6 { traps the queen. } )
16. Qh4+
17. Kg1
17. Bxd3
18. Qxd3
18. Qxg4+
19. Kf2
19. Qh4+{ With perpetual check. }
