12. Nfd7( 12...Na6 13.Qb3 Nd7 { was played by Anish Giri in the Rapid World Championship 2021 against Ivan Cheparinov. I prefer to start with }12...Nfd7 { , as it's not clear to me }{ that the  b8 -knight should already be committed to  a6 . } )( 12...Ne8 13.Qb3 f5 14.exf5 Bxf5 15.Rhd1 Nf6 16.Kg1 Nd5 { looked alright for Black in Yu Yangyi-Solak, Ankara 2022, and by playing   }12...Nfd7 { , we try to slightly improve over this game. I feel the knight is better }{ on  d7  than  e8 . } )
13. Re1{ Preparing an artificial way of castling. }
13. Nb6( { Simply exchanging a pair of knights. }13...f5!? { is possible as well. As a general rule, }{ when the king is on  f2 , this move is good because after }14.e5 f4 { , }{ the bishop needs the  f2 -square. } )
14. Nxb6
14. Qxb6
15. Qb3( { Using the discovered attack on the queen with }15.d5 { only backfires after }15...Bc5!  )
15. Nd7{ Black is fine. Note that it's much easier to deal with White's extra space when pieces get exchanged. I like to play the flexible ... Kg8 - h8  next, getting out of the  a2 - g8  diagonal. That gives options like ... Bh7 - g8!?  but also ... f7 - f5 , as the e-pawn won't be hanging with a check anymore. }
