11. Na2{ This is the idea. Suddenly both our bishops are hanging! Fortunately, it's not the end of the world. }
11. b5{ You probably guessed by now, this line is sharp! Instead of removing one of the attacked bishops, we raise the stakes. }( { Less convincing is }11...Bc5 { , when }12.exf5 b5! { is not clear at all, but   }12.b4 { is stronger, attacking the dark-squared bishop once again. Now }12...b5 13.bxc5 bxc4 14.Bxc4! { (and not }14.exf5 d3! { with unclear complications), is unpleasant for Black. } )
12. axb5( { We don't particularly mind this exchange, as it gives our  b8 -knight access to  c6 . After }12.exf5 { , Black transposes to the  12.axb5 line  with }12...Bc5! 13.axb5 cxb5 { . } )
12. Bc5
13. exf5
13. cxb5
14. Na3( { Already an only move. Less good is }14.b4 bxc4 15.bxc5 d3! { , when White's position is very much cramped. } )
14. d3+{ Just before White blockades the pawn with  Bf1 - d3 , we open the diagonal. }
15. Be3{ The most obvious reply, but also simply a losing move. }
15. Bxe3+
16. Kxe3
16. Nd5+{ Other moves win as well, but this is the most precise. }
17. Kd2( { After }17.Kxd3 Re8 { , it's hard for White to come up with anything }{ against ... Nd5 - e3 +. } )
17. Qg5+
18. Kxd3
18. Nc6{ I think we will even be able to mate Stockfish here! White's king has wandered too far into the open field. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Krause Attack 9.Kf2 e5 [Alternative]"]
[Black "Krause Attack 9.Kf2 e5 [Alternative] − 10.e4 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. a4( { Isolating the pawn on  c4  is the best way to go. By preventing ... b7 - b5 , White prepares to regain the  c4 -pawn. As we will see, the alternatives }5.e4 b5 { ,   }5.e3 b5 6.a4 b4 { , and   }5.g3 b5 { leave Black in excellent shape. } )
5. Bf5{ Not just developing the bishop but also preventing  e2 - e4 . Our development scheme is quite clear: in random order, we will play ... e7 - e6 , ... Bf8 - b4 , ... O-O , and ... Nb8 - d7 . Once we achieve that, we can start looking for central breaks connected to ... c6 - c5  and ... e6 - e5 . }
6. Ne5{ This has always been considered the most critical response, even from the early days of this variation. White does not necessarily intend to take back the pawn on  c4  with the knight but, more importantly, prepares to set up a big center with  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 , in order to embarrass Black's light-squared bishop and knight on  f6 . A very ambitious plan indeed that, if carried out successfully, would give White a big advantage. }
6. e6( { While, at first sight, this does not seem to counter White's intentions, it will soon become apparent that it does. The alternative }6...Nbd7 { is very reliable as well, which is why I offer both moves as part of this Lifetime Repertoire. Note that the direct }6...c5? { is met with }7.e4! { , with the idea that }7...Nxe4 8.Qf3 { leads to immediate trouble. } )
7. f3
7. Bb4
8. Nxc4( { For some years now, this has replaced }8.e4 { as the main move at the top level. I am not at all sure it will remain that way, but in any case, we need to be on top of things! While }8.Nxc4 { has been played almost a hundred years ago, it is the remarkable follow-up that caused a revival in 2009. } )
8. O-O( 8...Nd5 9.Bd2! { with the idea }9...Qh4+ 10.g3 Qxd4 11.e4! Nxc3 12.bxc3 Bxc3 13.Ra2± { has been considered bad for Black ever since the game Giri-Harikrishna, Wijk aan Zee 2010. } )( { Another disaster is }8...c5 9.dxc5 Qxd1+ 10.Kxd1 Bxc5 { since after the simple }11.e4 Bg6 12.Nb5! { , Black's kingside pieces are completely out of play. } )
9. Kf2{ This is the incredible move that caused the revival of the entire variation. By stepping out of the pin, White prepares the  e2 - e4  push. For an in-depth overview of  9.Kf2 , check the  Informational . }
9. e5{ An absolute shocker of a novelty by Fabiano Caruana. Black seems completely unprepared for this central break, yet he makes it happen! Going back to what we spoke about before, this is a very direct approach to the position and possibly the most challenging reply to  9.Kf2 . }
10. e4{ A new move, but one that gets praise by the engines. That makes it only a matter of time before it will get introduced into practice. I consider it a very serious test of Caruana's novelty. }
10. exd4( { We have to bite, as }10...Bg6 11.Nxe5 { is just lost. } )
11. Na2{ This is the idea. Suddenly both our bishops are hanging! Fortunately, it's not the end of the world. }
11. b5{ You probably guessed by now, this line is sharp! Instead of removing one of the attacked bishops, we raise the stakes. }( { Less convincing is }11...Bc5 { , when }12.exf5 b5! { is not clear at all, but   }12.b4 { is stronger, attacking the dark-squared bishop once again. Now }12...b5 13.bxc5 bxc4 14.Bxc4! { (and not }14.exf5 d3! { with unclear complications), is unpleasant for Black. } )
12. axb5( { We don't particularly mind this exchange, as it gives our  b8 -knight access to  c6 . After }12.exf5 { , Black transposes to the  12.axb5 line  with }12...Bc5! 13.axb5 cxb5 { . } )
12. Bc5
13. exf5
13. cxb5
14. Na3( { Already an only move. Less good is }14.b4 bxc4 15.bxc5 d3! { , when White's position is very much cramped. } )
14. d3+{ Just before White blockades the pawn with  Bf1 - d3 , we open the diagonal. }
15. Kg3{ The only way to avoid getting mated. }
15. Nc6{ Perhaps somewhat surprisingly, we just develop normally. }
16. Bxd3
16. Qb6{ We have the famous 0.00 on the engine's scoreboard, yet White is a piece up. That last fact means the equal score indicates clear compensation for Black. And that is easy to see as well.    Next, our rook coming to  d8  could already prove very disturbing, and the king on  g3  isn't exactly safe yet either, and vulnerable, potentially to checks on  f2 . A likely scenario is White having to shed (some of) the extra material to get the position back in order. }
