6. Ne5{ This has always been considered the most critical response, even from the early days of this variation. White does not necessarily intend to take back the pawn on  c4  with the knight but, more importantly, prepares to set up a big center with  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 , in order to embarrass Black's light-squared bishop and knight on  f6 . A very ambitious plan indeed that, if carried out successfully, would give White a big advantage. }
6. e6( { While, at first sight, this does not seem to counter White's intentions, it will soon become apparent that it does. The alternative }6...Nbd7 { is very reliable as well, which is why I offer both moves as part of this Lifetime Repertoire. Note that the direct }6...c5? { is met with }7.e4! { , with the idea that }7...Nxe4 8.Qf3 { leads to immediate trouble. } )
7. f3
7. Bb4
8. Nxc4( { For some years now, this has replaced }8.e4 { as the main move at the top level. I am not at all sure it will remain that way, but in any case, we need to be on top of things! While }8.Nxc4 { has been played almost a hundred years ago, it is the remarkable follow-up that caused a revival in 2009. } )
8. O-O( 8...Nd5 9.Bd2! { with the idea }9...Qh4+ 10.g3 Qxd4 11.e4! Nxc3 12.bxc3 Bxc3 13.Ra2± { has been considered bad for Black ever since the game Giri-Harikrishna, Wijk aan Zee 2010. } )( { Another disaster is }8...c5 9.dxc5 Qxd1+ 10.Kxd1 Bxc5 { since after the simple }11.e4 Bg6 12.Nb5! { , Black's kingside pieces are completely out of play. } )
9. Kf2{ This is the incredible move that caused the revival of the entire variation. By stepping out of the pin, White prepares the  e2 - e4  push. For an in-depth overview of  9.Kf2 , check the  Informational . }
9. e5{ An absolute shocker of a novelty by Fabiano Caruana. Black seems completely unprepared for this central break, yet he makes it happen! Going back to what we spoke about before, this is a very direct approach to the position and possibly the most challenging reply to  9.Kf2 . }
10. Nxe5{ After Ding-Caruana, the move  9...e5  appeared in a handful of other games as well. So far, everyone has replied with the text move. }
10. Bc2( { The first point is tactical in nature. This bishop can't be taken since }11.Qxc2 Qxd4+ { followed by taking on  e5  makes life easy for us. } )
11. Qd2
11. c5{ Giving White no time to catch their breath. White's center is being challenged. }
12. e3{ Not the most principled reply, but certainly a logical one. White simply protects the pawn on  d4  and prepares for the  f1 -bishop to be developed. }
12. Bg6{ We safely drop back to  g6 , trusting that our superior coordination and better king position will compensate for the pawn deficit. }( { Less good is }12...Bb3 13.Nd3! { and Black has issues with the bishop }{ on  b4 . } )
13. Bc4{ Focusing on development, but not really making life hard for us. }
13. cxd4
14. Qxd4( 14.exd4 Nc6! 15.Nxc6 bxc6 { gives great compensation, and the next moves }{ are very easy: ... Qa5 , ... Rf8 - d8 , ... Ra8 - b8 , etc. The engine already prefers Black here. } )
14. Qa5{ Threatening ... Rf8 - d8 , which makes White's next move forced. }
15. Rd1
15. Nc6( { Again this move! Now }16.Nxc6 bxc6 { gives Black great play. We are fully mobilized and our rooks have plenty of open files to enjoy. White will find it hard to disentangle. } )
