13. d5( { In combination with the previous move, this looks odd, but White did avoid the move ... Bc2 - b3 , which is our answer after   }12.d5 { . } )
13. Nbd7( { Simple development! }13...Be4 { is a good joke, but as long as White doesn't take that bishop, it doesn't do particularly much. The simple }14.Nd3 { gives White the advantage. } )
14. Nc4
14. Nb6( 14...a6!? { is an interesting alternative when, for instance, }15.Be2 Be4 16.d6 { ( }16.Qd1 Bxc3 17.bxc3 Bxd5 18.e4 Bxe4! 19.fxe4 Nxe4+ { followed by ... Nxc3  looks attractive for Black.) }{   }16...Bc6 { looks very unclear and playable. } )( { The immediate }14...Be4 { I like less after }15.Qd1 Bxc3 16.bxc3 Bxd5 17.e4 { , when White may be able to claim an edge, as }17...Bxe4 18.fxe4 Nxe4+ 19.Kg1 { doesn't have the same venom to it with the bishop on  f1 . }{ Now }19...Nxc3 20.Qc2 { looks fantastic for White. } )
15. Nxb6( 15.d6 Bf5! { intends to bring the bishop over }{ to  e6  and dislodge the knight from  c4 . } )
15. axb6{ Recapturing with the pawn ensures that we keep an eye on the  d5 -pawn and open the a-file as well. I left this position accidentally running on the computer for an entire weekend, which at least gave me the confirmation that Black is doing fine here.    That being said, the position obviously remains sharp and somewhat irrational. I like that we have a safe king and are fully developed, meaning we can start causing havoc. In general ... Bg6 - e4  is one of the main ideas. Last, but not least, there is one move that we should be aware of: }
16. Bc4
16. Ne8{ Creating the threat of a check on  h4  while rerouting the knight to  d6 . }
17. g3
17. Nd6
18. Qe2( 18.Be2 b5! { highlights the various pins. } )
18. Bxc3
19. bxc3
