16. Nf8{ Intending to embarrass the queen on  f4 . }( { It is tempting to make a forceful move like }16...Bxc4 17.Bxc4 Ne5 18.Be2 Bd6 { , but White has a convincing way to parry these threats. Following }19.Qf5 Nc4 20.Bxc4 Re5 21.Qh3 Rh5 22.Qxh5! Nxh5 23.g3 { , White is doing excellent }{ with a rook, bishop, and big central pawns for the queen. } )
17. Bd4{ Very sensible. White vacates the  e3 -square so that the queen may potentially fall back, while the knight on  c4  may also be able to use the freed square. }
17. Rc8( { It's important to start with this move. Caruana mixed up with }17...Ng6 { , after which }18.Qc1 { would have been more or less winning. Ding played }18.Qf5 { , which is less clear, but won anyway. Truly a pity for Caruana to have spoiled his fantastic novelty in this way. } )
18. Ne3
18. Ng6{ I am sure this is the position that Caruana had prepared with his team. During the game he simply mixed up and played ... Nf8 - g6  one move too early. Now that the knight has been forced to  e3 , White no longer has the retreat square  c1  for the queen. }( { It should be mentioned that }18...Nh5 { may be playable as well. The engine line }19.Qg4 Ne6 20.dxe6 Qxd4 21.Rd1 Qc5 22.exf7+ Bxf7 { isn't that clear. } )( { I prefer to play }18...Ng6 { though. First of all, }19.Bxf6 gxf6 { now transposes to a line we saw earlier, and }19.Qg5 Bxc3! { followed by the discovery ... Nf6xe4 + wins on the spot. That leaves White with two reasonable queen moves. } )
19. Qf5{ A seemingly safe spot for the queen. }
19. Bc5{ Challenging White's strongest minor piece. Removing it means the queen on  f5  is in danger again because of a potential ... Re8 - e5  threat. }
20. Bxc5( 20.Bxf6 gxf6 { is already losing for White. The problem is }{ that ... Re5  followed by ... f6 - f5  is coming, blasting open the position. } )
20. Rxc5
21. Ra3{ Reminding us that our bishop doesn't have many squares, or does it? }
21. Bc2( { Very elegant! Black makes use of the fact that }22.Nxc2 Qb6! { works tactically − more on that later. For now, let's note that we want to avoid   }21...Re5 22.Rxb3! Rxf5 23.Nxf5 { , which is a queen sacrifice White happily makes. The rook, bishop, and two pawns certainly outweigh the queen. } )( { What is playable though, is }21...Qb6 22.Bb5 Rxc3! { , which seems to offer ample compensation for the exchange. The line continues }23.bxc3 Nxd5 24.Re1 Nxe3 25.Rxe3 Be6 26.Qg5 Rd8 27.Be2 Rd2 28.Qb5 Qd6 { , with clear compensation for the exchange. Worth checking out as well! } )
22. Nxc2{ After other moves, we play  22... Qb6 !  with great counterplay on  b2  and the  g1 - a7  diagonal. }
22. Qb6{ An amazing position! We are a bishop and two pawns down, but the threats are obvious. First and foremost the discovered check on the king is threatened. Secondly, the queen on  f5  is still in dire straits, with ... Re8 - e5  being a constant threat. }
23. Ke1( 23.Ke2 Nxd5! { neatly rips open the position. } )
23. Re5
24. b4{ Trying to get off the hook by giving up the queen. }
24. Rxc3
25. Rxc3
25. Rxf5
26. Rc8+
26. Nf8
27. a5( { Two important intermediate moves by White. Instead, }27.exf5 Nxd5 28.a5 { gives Black the extra option of going }28...Qh6! { , }{ which threatens a nasty check on  c1 . } )
27. Qd6
28. exf5
28. Nxd5{ Materially speaking, White is up, but the lack of coordination and development speaks volumes. We are bound to pick up a couple of other pawns as well ( f5 ,  b4 ,  a5 ) and are definitely on the better side. }( { Note that }28...Qf4 { is strong as well. White probably does best replying }29.d6 { in that case, to answer }29...Qxd6 { with }30.Kf2 { , in an attempt to get organized. The immediate   }29.Kf2? { loses to }29...Ne4+ { . } )
