9. fxe4
9. Nxe4
10. Ra3( { I saw this move being played in a weekend tournament some twenty years ago and was shocked! Could such a move really be possible? At first sight, I was not sure at all how to assess the position after }10...Bxa3 11.Nxe4 { and this is indeed not clear at all. The engine indicates an entirely different route though. } )
10. Qh4+
11. g3
11. Nxg3{ Simple and strong. We just ignore White's little queenside demonstration and pick up an exchange on the other side of the board. }
12. hxg3( 12.Nf3 Qe4+! { is another neat point. } )
12. Qxh1{ Even if lose  c4 , we still have a rook and three pawns for two pieces. Black should be winning. }
