11. Qxf7+
11. Kd8
12. Bg5+{ An important move, trying to lure away the knight from  e4 . }( 12.Qxg7?? { This horrible blunder was seen in the very first game played in the Krause Attack. Chéron reacted ruthlessly: }12...Bxc3+ 13.bxc3 Qf2+ 14.Kd1 Nxc3# { 0–1 Przepiorka-Chéron, The Hague 1928. The starting point of the entire variation! } )
12. Nxg5
13. Qxg7{ Without the knight on  e4 , it is now possible to take on  g7 . The threat is to bring the rook over to  d1 . Black now usually forced a draw, though that is by no means necessary. }
13. Qe3+{ The way to keep the game going. Alekhine was the first to give this check, and it took over 50 years before someone repeated it. }
14. Kd1
14. Rf8{ One of those multipurpose moves. The rook was attacked and needed to be moved. From  f8  it can enter on  f2  when needed, but it also protects against the tactic of  Qg7xg5  followed by  Ne5 - f7 +. }
15. Nxc4
15. Qc5{ It took 63 years to come up with this improvement! The move prepares for one of White's main threats: taking on  b7 . }( { The stem game continued }15...Qf4? 16.Qxb7 Bxc3 17.bxc3 Ne4 18.Qxa8 { , when White was completely winning in Euwe-Alekhine, Amsterdam 1936. The fact that the game ended in a draw on move 22 after some further adventures, I believe had to do with the fact that this was an exhibition game with 'living pieces' on a giant board. Perhaps the players felt a draw was the correct result in this setting. } )
16. h4{ The only move to keep the balance. At this point, it is good to point out that White generally plays this line in order to force a draw. Getting into complicated positions like the one before us is generally not part of that game plan! }( 16.Qxb7 { − contrary to the Euwe-Alekhine game, now this is a bad capture. }16...Nd7! { With the queen }{ on  c5 , Black is ready to trap the queen. }17.Qxa8+ Kc7 18.Qxf8 Qxf8 { and the two rooks are no match for the queen. Black is completely winning, as White's king is an easy target. } )
16. Nf7( 16...Bxc3 { is very possible, but given that this is the line where we attempt to keep the game going, I think it's hard to recommend it. After all, it's going to be difficult to make something out of }17.Qxg5+ Qxg5 18.hxg5 { , }{ when  h7  is a weakness and White shouldn't have any trouble steering the game to safe havens. The text move does not allow any simplifications. } )
17. Kc2
17. Nd7
18. Be2( 18.Rd1 Kc7 19.Qxh7?! Bxc3 20.bxc3 Nb6! { gave Black the initiative in Wicklund Hansen-Savu, ICCF 2006, as }21.Nxb6 axb6 { opens up the a-file. } )
18. Kc7{ We transposed to the  17.Be2 move order . }
