8. e4( { At the top level, this has largely been replaced by }8.Nxc4 { , which is explored in separate chapters! However, don't think that the current section is of less importance. }8.e4 { has an enormous history, forces Black to sacrifice a piece, and is still one of the critical tests of the variation. It may well take the central stage again someday. } )
8. Bxe4{ The point of Black's previous move. Of course, we were not planning to retreat with the bishop! The idea of this sacrifice was first mentioned by Orla Herman Krause (1867-1935) in 1926.    Krause was a doctor by profession, working in the hospital of Oringe (Denmark). His chess analysis, however, makes him known to this very day. He published his analysis in various German publications, and there are numerous discoveries that carry his name. This variation is the most famous among them.    It was in the following year that André Chéron, nowadays mostly known for his famous endgame work, published  Traite Complet d'Echecs , where he confirmed Krause's analysis. Chéron then went on to introduce the sacrifice into practice at the 1928 World Amateur Championship in The Hague. }( { Before moving on, I should briefly mention that taking on  e4  with the knight doesn't quite have the same effect: }8...Nxe4 9.fxe4 Qh4+ 10.Ke2! { ( }10.g3 Qxe4+! { is what White needs to avoid.)   }10...Bxe4 11.g3 Qh5+ 12.g4 Bd3+ 13.Kf3 { and Black is running out of steam. } )
9. fxe4
9. Nxe4
10. Bd2( { These days an automatic move, but that was not at all the case in the initial development of this variation. }10.Qf3 { was considered to be the critical response, and it was assumed that giving up another pawn with the text move can't possibly give White chances to fight for an advantage.    It was Vladimir Kramnik who did a great job in the nineties proving that it is possible to do just that, and nowadays it's the absolute main move in the position. White does give up yet another pawn but exchanges a lot of Black pieces in the process. } )
10. Qxd4( { The only viable option, as the greedy }10...Qh4+ 11.g3 Nxg3 12.hxg3 Qxh1 { leaves Black too far behind in development. After the energetic }13.Qg4 { , White has a murderous initiative. } )
11. Nxe4
11. Qxe4+( { The stem game continued }11...Bxd2+ 12.Qxd2 Qxe5 13.Qe2 O-O 14.Nc3 Nd7 { and was eventually drawn in Enevoldsen-Piazzini, Buenos Aires 1939. It was only years later that it was discovered that the simple   }13.O-O-O! { gives White a near-winning advantage, effectively moving  11...Bxd2+  to oblivion. } )
12. Qe2
12. Bxd2+
13. Kxd2
13. Qd5+{ After the check on  d5 , we are at a major crossroads. I dare say there is hardly any top player in the '90s that hasn't either played games from this position or, at the very least, extensively analyzed it. It was all the rage!    Today,  attention has shifted more towards the Semi-Slav and solid Queen's Gambit, but that's just fashion and may change at any moment. For now, we have four pawns for the bishop, meaning we are doing fine materially speaking. Our pawn on  c4  is weak though and will likely drop off.    It is hard to speak in broad general terms about the position, as it is so unbalanced. What we can say is that White has a small lead in development, but the king on  d2  is awkwardly placed and may easily become a target.     How is a potential endgame? Take the queens off, and White will be doing very well in the current position. The pawn on  c4  will fall, and while Black has three pawns, they aren't that easy to move forward. However, take the queens off by exchanging them on  d5 , giving Black the option of recapturing with the c-pawn, and suddenly Black has a mobile central pawn mass, which should give plenty of play for the piece. There is more to say about the endgame, as the placement of pieces is a major factor as well.    Is Black's king nicely centralized on  e7  or tucked away in the corner, having castled kingside? The main question you may have at this point, though, is why all this talk about a potential endgame when we have a board full of pieces?    The above comments do seem a bit abstract for now, but White intends to play  Ne5xc4  followed by  Qe2 - e5  next, in order to bring the  f1 -bishop into the game. In that situation, the tension between the queens on  e5  and  d5  often leads to one side 'blinking' and exchanging queens. We then get to see the scenarios described unfold. It is therefore essential to get a feel for these Slav Endgames, as that will surely bring dividends.    As we navigate our way through this variation, it is my intention to carefully explain the various subtle differences between the endgames that can arise. As you have probably guessed, the position is very hard to play for both sides. Good thing we came prepared! There are no less than four king moves that are all fairly critical, and we will look at them in great detail. Most of the king moves ask for a different approach from us as if things weren't complicated enough yet! }( { A final thing to note is that the best check is indeed on  d5 . That is shown in the variation }13...Qd4+ 14.Kc2 Na6 15.Rd1 { , when it would be great to be able to swing the queen }{ over to  a5 , creating immediate counterplay. With the queen on  d4 , however, that is not allowed. } )
