14. Kc1( { Extremely rare, yet a king move to take seriously. Somewhat surprisingly, Black's best reply leads to a transposition to }14.Kc3 { . } )
14. b5( { Keeping the  c4 -pawn for now. It's important to note that }14...Na6 15.Ra3! { is one of the points of having the king }{ on  c1  instead of  c3 . } )( { The other typical move, }14...O-O { , is also better for White after }15.Nxc4 Na6 16.Ra3 { . } )
15. Ra3( { While the rook should eventually get into the game this way, the timing is definitely off here. White can also start with }15.axb5 { and after }15...cxb5 16.Qe3 Nd7 17.Nxd7 Qxd7 18.Be2 O-O { , we transposed to the  15.Qe3 variation . } )
15. O-O
16. Rg3{ Way too optimistic. }
16. Rd8{ We already have a clear advantage. While White has wasted two moves on the rook, we have brought our king to safety and taken the d-file. }
