5. Bf5{ Not just developing the bishop but also preventing  e2 - e4 . Our development scheme is quite clear: in random order, we will play ... e7 - e6 , ... Bf8 - b4 , ... O-O , and ... Nb8 - d7 . Once we achieve that, we can start looking for central breaks connected to ... c6 - c5  and ... e6 - e5 . }
6. Ne5{ This has always been considered the most critical response, even from the early days of this variation. White does not necessarily intend to take back the pawn on  c4  with the knight but, more importantly, prepares to set up a big center with  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 , in order to embarrass Black's light-squared bishop and knight on  f6 . A very ambitious plan indeed that, if carried out successfully, would give White a big advantage. }
6. e6( { While, at first sight, this does not seem to counter White's intentions, it will soon become apparent that it does. The alternative }6...Nbd7 { is very reliable as well, which is why I offer both moves as part of this Lifetime Repertoire. Note that the direct }6...c5? { is met with }7.e4! { , with the idea that }7...Nxe4 8.Qf3 { leads to immediate trouble. } )
7. f3
7. Bb4( { Vladimir Kramnik defended Black's position in the endgame after }7...c5 8.e4 Bg6 9.Be3 cxd4 10.Qxd4 Qxd4 11.Bxd4 { in a couple of games, including his 2006 WC match against Veselin Topalov, and so did Vishy Anand in his 2010 match against the same player. Nowadays, the endgame has the reputation of being pretty lousy − besides being completely one-sided. That's why we choose the much more ambitious text move. } )
8. e4( { At the top level, this has largely been replaced by }8.Nxc4 { , which is explored in separate chapters! However, don't think that the current section is of less importance. }8.e4 { has an enormous history, forces Black to sacrifice a piece, and is still one of the critical tests of the variation. It may well take the central stage again someday. } )
8. Bxe4{ The point of Black's previous move. Of course, we were not planning to retreat with the bishop! The idea of this sacrifice was first mentioned by Orla Herman Krause (1867-1935) in 1926.    Krause was a doctor by profession, working in the hospital of Oringe (Denmark). His chess analysis, however, makes him known to this very day. He published his analysis in various German publications, and there are numerous discoveries that carry his name. This variation is the most famous among them.    It was in the following year that André Chéron, nowadays mostly known for his famous endgame work, published  Traite Complet d'Echecs , where he confirmed Krause's analysis. Chéron then went on to introduce the sacrifice into practice at the 1928 World Amateur Championship in The Hague. }( { Before moving on, I should briefly mention that taking on  e4  with the knight doesn't quite have the same effect: }8...Nxe4 9.fxe4 Qh4+ 10.Ke2! { ( }10.g3 Qxe4+! { is what White needs to avoid.)   }10...Bxe4 11.g3 Qh5+ 12.g4 Bd3+ 13.Kf3 { and Black is running out of steam. } )
9. fxe4
9. Nxe4
10. Bd2( { These days an automatic move, but that was not at all the case in the initial development of this variation. }10.Qf3 { was considered to be the critical response, and it was assumed that giving up another pawn with the text move can't possibly give White chances to fight for an advantage.    It was Vladimir Kramnik who did a great job in the nineties proving that it is possible to do just that, and nowadays it's the absolute main move in the position. White does give up yet another pawn but exchanges a lot of Black pieces in the process. } )
10. Qxd4( { The only viable option, as the greedy }10...Qh4+ 11.g3 Nxg3 12.hxg3 Qxh1 { leaves Black too far behind in development. After the energetic }13.Qg4 { , White has a murderous initiative. } )
11. Nxe4
11. Qxe4+( { The stem game continued }11...Bxd2+ 12.Qxd2 Qxe5 13.Qe2 O-O 14.Nc3 Nd7 { and was eventually drawn in Enevoldsen-Piazzini, Buenos Aires 1939. It was only years later that it was discovered that the simple   }13.O-O-O! { gives White a near-winning advantage, effectively moving  11...Bxd2+  to oblivion. } )
12. Qe2
12. Bxd2+
13. Kxd2
13. Qd5+{ For the moment, we have four pawns for the bishop, meaning we are doing fine materially speaking. Our pawn on  c4  is weak though and will likely drop off. It is hard to speak in broad general terms about the position, as it is so unbalanced, but you do have access to an extensive overview in the corresponding  Informational . }( { An important thing to note is that the best check is indeed on  d5 . That is shown in the variation }13...Qd4+ 14.Kc2 Na6 15.Rd1 { , when it would be great to be able to swing the queen over }{ to  a5 , creating immediate counterplay. With the queen on  d4 , however, that is not allowed. } )
14. Kc1( { Extremely rare, yet a king move to take seriously. Somewhat surprisingly, Black's best reply leads to a transposition to }14.Kc3 { . } )
14. b5( { Keeping the  c4 -pawn for now. It's important to note that }14...Na6 15.Ra3! { is one of the points of having the king }{ on  c1  instead of  c3 . } )( { The other typical move, }14...O-O { , is also better for White after }15.Nxc4 Na6 16.Ra3 { . } )
15. Qe3( { Preparing  Bf1 - e2 - f3 . White can also start with }15.axb5 { and after }15...cxb5 16.Qe3 Nd7 17.Nxd7 Qxd7 18.Be2 O-O { , we transpose to  15.Qe3 . } )
15. O-O( { We can also start with }15...Nd7 { , which will transpose to  15...O-O  after }16.Nxd7 Qxd7 17.Be2 O-O { . } )
16. Be2
16. Nd7
17. Nxd7
17. Qxd7{ The critical position for the assessment of  14.Kc1 . We have four pawns for the bishop and our king is very safe on  g8 . Still, we have to take care as our queenside is vulnerable. If White gets to play  Be2 - f3 ,  Qe3 - c5 ,  Rh1 - d1 , etc, it's clear our position may just collapse. }
18. h4{ The most challenging reply. We will see a lot of  h2 - h4 s in this course, as it's White's standard way of softening up our kingside. Once the pawn reaches  h5 , we will be faced with the question of allowing to pawn to run to  h6  or slightly weaken our kingside by pushing ... h7 - h6  ourselves. }
18. a6{ Keeping our queenside together. }
19. h5
19. h6( { The pawn can't be allowed any further. See the sample line }19...Rfd8 20.h6 g6 21.Rd1 { followed by moves like  Kc1 - c2  and  Qe3 - e5  when, besides queenside pressure, White can combine that with threats on our weakened king. } )
20. Rd1
20. Qc7
21. Bf3
21. Rad8( { It's important to seek counterplay along the d-file, instead of passively defending the queenside, with, for instance, }21...Rac8 { , after which }22.Qc5 { gives White a dominating position. } )
22. Qc5{ The first move to look at it, but we are prepared for it! }
22. Qf4+
23. Kc2
23. Rd3{ This is the point behind our 21st move; without it, White would slowly gobble up our queenside unhindered. }
24. Qxc6{ In a practical game, I think it's easy to miss our next move. }
24. Qd4{ Suddenly the threat of ... Qf2 + is hard to counter. }
25. Qe4
25. Qf2+
26. Kb1( 26.Qe2 { looks safe but is quite the opposite! }26...Rxf3! { , winning a piece in broad daylight. } )
26. c3{ Opening up a way to the king. }
27. bxc3
27. Rxc3
28. Ra2
28. Qc5{ Black is doing well here, as the king on  b1  is permanently weak. }
