[White "6) Krause  Attack 8.e4 − 14.Kc3"]
[Black "Krause Attack 14.Kc3 O-O 15.a5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. a4( { Isolating the pawn on  c4  is the best way to go. By preventing ... b7 - b5 , White prepares to regain the  c4 -pawn. As we will see, the alternatives }5.e4 b5 { ,   }5.e3 b5 6.a4 b4 { , and   }5.g3 b5 { leave Black in excellent shape. } )
5. Bf5{ Not just developing the bishop but also preventing  e2 - e4 . Our development scheme is quite clear: in random order, we will play ... e7 - e6 , ... Bf8 - b4 , ... O-O , and ... Nb8 - d7 . Once we achieve that, we can start looking for central breaks connected to ... c6 - c5  and ... e6 - e5 . }
6. Ne5{ This has always been considered the most critical response, even from the early days of this variation. White does not necessarily intend to take back the pawn on  c4  with the knight but, more importantly, prepares to set up a big center with  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 , in order to embarrass Black's light-squared bishop and knight on  f6 . A very ambitious plan indeed that, if carried out successfully, would give White a big advantage. }
6. e6( { While, at first sight, this does not seem to counter White's intentions, it will soon become apparent that it does. The alternative }6...Nbd7 { is very reliable as well, which is why I offer both moves as part of this Lifetime Repertoire. Note that the direct }6...c5? { is met with }7.e4! { , with the idea that }7...Nxe4 8.Qf3 { leads to immediate trouble. } )
7. f3
7. Bb4( { Vladimir Kramnik defended Black's position in the endgame after }7...c5 8.e4 Bg6 9.Be3 cxd4 10.Qxd4 Qxd4 11.Bxd4 { in a couple of games, including his 2006 WC match against Veselin Topalov, and so did Vishy Anand in his 2010 match against the same player. Nowadays, the endgame has the reputation of being pretty lousy − besides being completely one-sided. That's why we choose the much more ambitious text move. } )
8. e4( { At the top level, this has largely been replaced by }8.Nxc4 { , which is explored in separate chapters! However, don't think that the current section is of less importance. }8.e4 { has an enormous history, forces Black to sacrifice a piece, and is still one of the critical tests of the variation. It may well take the central stage again someday. } )
