17. Qxd7
18. Qc5( 18.Bf3 Rab8! { shows the vulnerability of }{ the king on  c3 . } )
18. Qd8{ One to remember! From  d8 , the queen is ready to generate counterplay on  f6  or  a5 . Of course, it is important that White can't take on  c6 . }
19. Qxc6
19. b4+{ The nasty tactical point. }
20. Kc2( { Obviously, }20.Kxc4 Rc8! { loses the queen, and   }20.Kxb4 Rb8+ 21.Kc3 Qf6+ { isn't much better. } )
20. b3+
21. Kb1( { Instead, }21.Kc3 Qa5+ { gives White good reasons to resign. } )
21. Rc8{ Black is winning, as White's king is in serious danger. }
