14. Qa5+{ We are going to be materialistic this time and will try to hold on to our  c4 -pawn by exchanging it on  c3 . }( { Holding on to the c-pawn in a more direct manner with }14...b5 { fails to }15.Rd1 Qc5 16.g3! { , when it's hard to come up with a good idea against the plan }{ of  Bf1 - g2  followed by  axb5 . } )( { The more standard }14...Na6 { doesn't work well here as a recent correspondence game revealed. }15.Nxc4 O-O-O { (I also had a look at }15...Rd8 { and }15...O-O { but neither appealed very much.)   }16.h4! { The rook is brought into play }{ via  h3 . }16...Nb4 ( { I think }16...Qc5 17.Rh3 Rd4 { may be a bit more tenacious, but nevertheless }18.Rc3 Qd5 19.Rd1 Nc5 20.Rxd4 Qxd4 21.Qe3 { looks pretty one-sided. } )17.Rh3 Qc5 ( 17...Qf5 18.Rc1 Qf4 19.Qe3?? Rd1+! { lead to a quick victory for Black in the Dutch encounter Piket-Ernst, the Netherlands 2003. }19.Rcc3 { is a simple improvement though, leaving White completely in control. } )18.a5 Rd4 19.Rc3 { . Over the next few moves, White will slowly disentangle and the extra piece does the rest. }19...Kb8 20.a6 Rhd8 21.Qf3 Nd5 22.Qg3+ Rf4 23.Nd2 Qd6 24.Rd3 e5 25.Rc1 { and White won a model game in Offringa-Cross, ICCF 2020. } )
15. Kf2
15. c3
16. bxc3
16. Qxc3{ One of the rare occasions in this variation where we have even four pawns for the piece, instead of three. We shall not be complaining! }
17. Rd1( { Not technically a novelty, as it was played in an obscure email game in 1999, but this move only got attention now, as engines started pointing it out. White rules out Black's ... Nb8 - d7  defense, which works very well against }17.Rb1 { , and plans to continue with a }{ quick  h2 - h4  and  Rh1 - h3 , to grab the initiative. } )
17. Na6( { As natural as it is to want to start with }17...O-O { in order to get the king out of the center, here it's very imprecise. The reason is that after }18.Qe4! { , we can't develop }{ our  b8 -knight (it will be taken by the bishop), and White is preparing  Bf1 - d3  with a very serious attack. Engines already scream of a winning advantage. } )
18. h4{ The only way to fight for an advantage. As so often in this line, the  h1 -rook enters the game via  h3 . }
18. Nb4( { Note that }18...Nc7 19.Rh3 Qc5+ 20.Qe3 Qxe3+ 21.Rxe3 Nd5 { transposes to  18...Nb4 . } )
19. Rh3
19. Qc5+
20. Qe3{ It looks counterintuitive to offer an exchange of queens when Black has four pawns for the piece. The upcoming endgame isn't too scary indeed. }
20. Qxe3+
21. Rxe3
21. Nd5
22. Ree1
22. f6{ As I have stated before, we generally prefer to avoid weakening our structure with ... f6 . }( { The most obvious move is }22...Ke7 { , which connects the rooks. However, White has a strong reply in }23.Rb1 Rab8 24.Ba6! { and suddenly Black is in huge trouble. } )( { Another natural-looking move is }22...a5 { securing a square for the }{ knight on  b4 . As solid as that looks, it's quite the opposite after }23.Rb1 Nb4 24.Red1! f6 25.Nc4! { , }{ when both  Nc4 - d6 + and  Nc4xa5 (!) are big threats. } )
23. Nc4
23. Kd7{ Black still has four pawns for the piece and seems to have stabilized the position. Here too, things are not what they seem! Very instructive I think is the following sample line that is by no means forced: }
24. h5
24. Rhe8
25. a5
25. Rad8{ And now a move to remember: }
26. Bd3{ Forcing the weakening ... h6 . }
26. h6{ Our kingside pawns are now effectively stopped. We won't be able to push them forward. The same happened on the queenside where  a4 - a5  hampers our play. Black's position is by no means lost here, but it seems we simply have to sit and wait for White to further strengthen the position. White can do so by pushing  g2 - g4 , perhaps bringing the bishop to  g6 / e4 , shuffling the rooks to the b-file, etc. }( { In short, this is not a scenario I am very happy with. Seeing the above lines will hopefully clarify my choice for   }22...Rc8 { . I want to protect the queenside by placing the rook }{ on  c7 , and don't want to weaken our kingside with ... f7 - f6 . } )
