15. Rd1{ This is known to be inaccurate but does, in fact, pose a serious question to Black. }
15. Qa5
16. Kb1{ We have just one good move now. }
16. c3( { Keeping the pawn alive for now. }16...Qxa4 17.Qf3! O-O 18.Bxc4 { is just crushing. For instance, }18...Nb4 19.Bb3 Qa5 20.Nd7 Rfe8 21.Rhf1 Re7 22.Bxe6! { and either recapture }{ on  e6  will lead to mate. } )
17. Nxc6( { Again, }17.Nc4 Qxa4 18.Nd6+ Ke7 19.Nf5+ Kf8 { is simply great for Black. } )
17. Qxa4( { The justification behind White's move lies in }17...bxc6 18.Qxa6 Qxa6 19.Bxa6 Rb8 20.b3! { , when }20...Rxb3+ 21.Kc2 { is technically winning for White. True, after }21...Rb2+ 22.Kxc3 Rxg2 { , Black has four pawns already, but }23.Rb1! { followed }{ by  Rb7  is very grim for Black. White's a-pawn is a huge asset, while our pawns are far from queening. } )
18. Ne5
18. O-O{ It is a great relief to get the king out of dodge. }
19. Qc2{ If not for this queen move, White would simply be in big trouble. }
19. Qxc2+{ Forced, since White also threatened to capture the pawn on  c3  with the queen. }
20. Kxc2
20. cxb2
21. Bxa6( { Before recapturing on  b2 , it's important to eliminate the knight and ruin Black's structure. }21.Kxb2 Nc5 { is slightly better for Black according to the engines, but probably more than that in a practical game. } )
21. bxa6
22. Kxb2
22. Rab8+
23. Ka3
23. Rb5{ The endgame is approximately equal. With the king offside on  a3  and a lot of pawns on the board, I'd perhaps rather play with Black though. We simply intend to push the kingside forward. }
