15. Re1( { I haven't found any games with this move, but the idea is pretty straightforward. The knight on  e5  gets overprotected so that White can recapture on  c4  with the queen. Add to that, that }15...b5 16.g4! { is dangerous for Black, and we already realize we have to take this move seriously. } )
15. c3{ Not the first, nor the last time we will see this sneaky pawn push. }( { Also possible is }15...Nb4+ 16.Kb1 Rd8 { , but I am not sure I am eager to recommend the endgame after }17.Qxc4 Qd1+ 18.Rxd1 Rxd1+ 19.Qc1 Rxc1+ 20.Kxc1 Ke7 { . Black is certainly not in a very bad way, but our pawn structure makes it hard for us to make the three pawns count. I'm afraid this could easily turn one-sided after a continuation like }21.Bc4 Rd8 22.Nf3 { followed by moves such as  a4 - a5 ,  Rh1 - e1 ,  h2 - h4 ,  g2 - g4 , etc. Black is probably completely fine, but if anyone is better, it is probably White. } )( 15...O-O? 16.Qxc4 { illustrates what White has in mind. }{ Taking on  c4  with the queen leaves White's position in a much more harmonious state, and the advantage here is already of a near-winning nature. } )
16. Qe3{ Preparing both  Bf1xa6  and the capture on  c3 . }
16. Nc5{ Simple enough. }
17. Qxc3
17. Nxa4( { Grabbing a fourth pawn and, depending on where the queen goes, we can also consider exchanging queens on  c5  on the next move (for example, both }18.Qa3 { and }18.Qb4 { are well met by }18...Qc5+ { ) }{ . We should be doing fine here. } )
