19. Kb1
19. O-O{ It's no wonder that it has not yet been seen in practice. In a practical game, it's very hard to play with a king on  b1  and most of your pieces in their initial positions. Black already has three pawns and, with the rooks coming to  d8  and  c8 , has very easy play against the white king. }
20. g4( { White could also push the g-pawn one more square, but as the following line shows, }20.g3 { is stronger. } )
20. Nc6
21. Nc2{ Preventing our knight from reaching the key square on  d4 . }
21. Rad8( { The difference between placing the  a8 -rook on  d8  instead of the one from  f8  is very subtle. If we follow the line }21...Rfd8 22.Qxb5 Rd1+ 23.Ka2 Rxa1+ 24.Nxa1 Nb4+ 25.Kb1 Qd4 { , now White has time for }26.Bg2 { , which attacks }{ the rook on  a8 . With the rook on  f8 , Black could simply grab the pawn on  g4  now. } )
22. Qxb5
22. Rd1+{ The start of a long and forced sequence. }
23. Ka2
23. Rxa1+
24. Nxa1
24. Nb4+
25. Kb1
25. Qd4
26. Bg2{ With the pawn on  g3 , this is excellent for White. }
26. Qxg4{ As it is, this position is excellent for Black. }
