20. g3
20. Rad8( { We are planning to simply double on the d-file. As mentioned, with the pawn on  g3 , the line }20...Nc6 { is now disadvantageous. In the same line: }21.Nc2 Rad8 22.Qxb5 Rd1+ 23.Ka2 Rxa1+ 24.Nxa1 Nb4+ 25.Kb1 Qd4 26.Bg2 { there is no longer the possibility to grab a }{ pawn on  g4 , and that means White can slowly disentangle with moves like  Na1 - b3  and  Rh1 - c1 , with a winning game. } )( { Also not very effective is }20...Rac8 21.Bg2 Rfd8 22.Ra3! { , when it's not easy to see how Black can up the pressure. } )
21. Ra3
21. Rd6{ As announced! }
22. Bg2
22. Rfd8
23. Rc1
23. Qb6
24. Bf1
24. a6{ I like our position here. We have, as usual, three pawns for the piece and active play. Control of the d-file and our strong knight on  b4  make it hard for White to move around freely.    My engine initially liked White, but while I was making a cup of tea, it dropped all the way to equality. That's indeed what I think is a fair evaluation of the position − dynamic equality. Practically speaking, I'd take Black, as our king is safer and our play is more straightforward. }
