18. Qc5+( { I wasn't 100% happy with }18...Rc8+ 19.Kb1 Qe4+ 20.Nc2 Qxe2 ( 20...Qxc2+ 21.Qxc2 Rxc2 { ( }21...Nxc2?! 22.Bxb5+ Ke7 23.Rxa7+ Kf6 24.Rf1+ { is unpleasant for Black.)   }22.Bxb5+ Ke7 { transposes  20...Qxe2 . } )21.Bxe2 Rxc2 22.Bxb5+ Ke7 23.Rxa7+ Kd6 24.Rd1+ Kc5 25.Ba4 Kb6 26.Rdd7 Rcc8 { which, somewhat surprisingly, is more or less forced. It looks scary and if we continue the line a few more moves, }27.Rdb7+ Kc5 28.Ra5+ Kc4 29.Rxf7 Rhf8 30.Bb5+ Kd4 31.Rxg7 { , we still have some work to do to hold the game. The text move keeps the queens on, which makes sense with that exposed }{ king on  c1 . } )
19. Kb1
19. O-O{ It's no wonder that it has not yet been seen in practice. In a practical game, it's very hard to play with a king on  b1  and most of your pieces in their initial positions. Black already has three pawns and, with the rooks coming to  d8  and  c8 , has very easy play against the white king. }
20. g3
20. Rad8( { We are planning to simply double on the d-file. As mentioned, with the pawn on  g3 , the line }20...Nc6 { is now disadvantageous. In the same line: }21.Nc2 Rad8 22.Qxb5 Rd1+ 23.Ka2 Rxa1+ 24.Nxa1 Nb4+ 25.Kb1 Qd4 26.Bg2 { there is no longer the possibility to grab a }{ pawn on  g4 , and that means White can slowly disentangle with moves like  Na1 - b3  and  Rh1 - c1 , with a winning game. } )( { Also not very effective is }20...Rac8 21.Bg2 Rfd8 22.Ra3! { , when it's not easy to see how Black can up the pressure. } )
21. Bg2
21. Rd6
22. Rc1( 22.Ra3 { transposes to the  21.Ra3 line . } )
22. Qb6
23. Bf1
23. a6{ The same setup we have seen before. We are planning ... Rf8 - d8  next. }
24. Nc2
24. Nd3{ Keeping knights on the board for now! }
25. Rd1
25. Rfd8
26. Qe3
26. Nb4{ Cocky! Due to back-rank issues, White can't take the queen or knight. }
27. Rxd6
27. Rxd6( { White can still not touch our queen on  b6 , while we have nothing to complain about in the endgame that arises after }28.Be2 Qxe3 { , as our kingside pawns can start their march next. } )
