26. Qd4( { ½-½ Topalov-Anand, Dos Hermanas 1997. In a later round, Salov showed that   }20.Kd2 { is more precise, and he won a good technical game after the further moves }20...O-O 21.Qe5 Rac8 22.Be2 Rfd8 23.Rc1 Nb6 24.Ke1 { etc. Salov-Illescas Cordoba, Dos Hermanas 1997.    Despite the queen sacrifice not being entirely correct, you have to admire Vishy's creativity. Confronted with a new idea, he improvised a very ingenious way to play, which may not have been entirely correct but yielded him an easy draw.    Interestingly, the previous year in Dos Hermanas, Anand had made a similar queen sacrifice against Topalov in an Open Spanish and made a draw as well! There too, Topalov could have won, but it proved too hard to find in a practical game.    Returning back to the Slav, after Salov proved the sacrifice to be incorrect, players' attention shifted to   }18...Qc5 { . } )
