27. Rc6( { Surely not }27...Rxb4?? 28.Nxd5+ { . } )
28. Ra1
28. Kd6( 28...d4 29.Nd5+ Kd6 30.Ra5! { gives White some hope, though the engine indicates }30...f5! { still holds }{ ( }31.Bxf5 Rb5 32.Rxb5 axb5 { being the idea, }{ when the  d5 -knight is in trouble). We can hardly move a muscle though after, for instance, }31.h4 { , and I think the text move is more convenient. } )
29. Ra4{ Preparing  Bd3xa6 . }( 29.Ra5? Rxb4 30.Rxd5+ Ke7 { is fantastic for Black. At the risk of repeating myself, it is essential for White to keep hold of the b-pawn. Here Black has a very promising passed a-pawn as well as a workable majority on the kingside. } )
29. Ke5{ An important move. Not only are we activating the king }{ (an important endgame rule) }{ , but we also prepare counterplay over the 6th rank for the rook. }( { Instead, }29...Rbb6 { allows }30.Ne2 Ke5 { , and now the very pretty move }31.Ng1! { , }{ when the knight will reach  d4  via  f3  and all of White's pieces will have found excellent squares. }{    Less good is the natural looking }31.Ke3 { because }31...f5! { prevents  Ne2 - d4 , which would run into  f5 - f4 +!, while }32.Ng1 { is no longer the same. Black gets counterplay with }32...Rg6 33.Nf3+ Kd6 34.g3 Rg4 35.Nd4 Ke5 { and White likely has nothing better but to drop the knight }{ back to  f3 . } )
30. Bxa6{ Our previous move anticipated this capture. }( 30.Ne2 Rcb6 31.Kc3 Rc6+ 32.Kb3 Rbb6 { is a much better version compared to the previous note on  29...Rbb6 . Here, the knight will never }{ reach  d4 , making it hard for White to do something constructive. In the meantime, Black can consider pushing the kingside forward or activating the  c6 -rook on that side of the board. } )
30. Rg6{ It's all about activity. }
31. Bf1( 31.g3 Rh6 { further weakens the kingside. A sample line is }32.h4 Rg6 33.Ne2 Rg4 34.Kc3 { , and while White has managed to hold on to the b-pawn, the pieces are completely tied up. We can simply push our kingside with }34...f5 35.Bd3 g6 { , }{ preparing ... h7 - h6  and ... g6 - g5 . The position is drawish. } )
31. Rf6( { First luring the king to  e1 . The direct }31...Rg4 32.b5 Rxa4 33.Nxa4 { is a slightly worse version of what we are about to see, as the white king is }{ on  d2  instead of  e1 . } )
32. Ke1( { It is possible to play }32.Be2 { , but it entails a pawn sacrifice. }32...Rf2 33.Nd1 Rxg2 34.Ne3 Rg1 { , time to take stock. Yes, White has a passed b-pawn, but it is under control for now. }{ In the meantime, having won the pawn on  g2 , we can focus on bringing the kingside forward. I'd take Black here, though the engine, probably rightly so, insists on the evaluation of 0.00. } )
32. Rf4
33. b5
33. Rxa4
34. Nxa4{ At first, this felt dangerous to me, but Black's next few moves changed my mind completely. White is not better at all! }
34. Ra8
35. Nc3
35. Ra1+
36. Nd1
36. Kd4{ We can end the line here. Black is very active, easily controls the b-pawn, and can focus, as usual, on bringing the d- and kingside-pawns forward. }
