18. Rd1( { Introduced by Topalov, and an improvement over }18.Nb6 Qc5+ 19.Kb3 Nc6 { ( }19...Qxb6 20.Qxb5+! { wins on the spot.)   }20.Qxb5 Qe3+ 21.Kc2 Qf2+ { ( }21...O-O 22.Qxc6 Qf2+ 23.Kc3 Rab8 24.Ra6! { )   }22.Kc3 Qd4+ { , when White couldn't avoid the perpetual in Shirov-Khalifman, Ter Apel 1997. } )( 18.Kxb4 { transposes to the  17.Kb3 line . } )
18. Qc5( { Anand played }18...bxc4 { instead, with the idea to build a fortress against Topalov. For more details, see the  Informational  dedicated to this amazing queen sacrifice. } )
19. Qe5
19. Nd5+
20. Rxd5{ The point behind White's play, and undoubtedly what Topalov had prepared for his game with Anand. }
20. Qxd5
21. Nd6+
21. Kf8
22. Qxd5
22. exd5( { The difference with  the lines  we saw after   }20...b4 { is the discrepancy in coordination between White's forces. As we will see, Black is doing fine in this version of the endgame. } )
23. Bd3
23. a6( { Instead of }23...Ke7 { , Black can also opt for the text move. } )
24. Kd4( 24.Ra1 h5 { followed by ... Rh8 - h6  is fine for us. Note that White isn't threatening anything, as }25.Nxb5 Rc8+! { loses a piece. } )
24. h5{ Forcing White to show some real precision. For now, White's compensation lies in the fact that Black is not yet mobilized − the moment that changes, so will the evaluation. }( { After }24...Ke7 25.Kc5 Rhd8 26.Re1+ Kf8 27.Kc6! g6 28.Kc7 { , we get to see what Hein Donner meant when he wrote that in the endgame the king, when broken through enemy lines, has the firepower of no less than a rook! }28...f5 29.Re6 { , }{ White is dominating and wants  Bd3 - e2 - f3  next. As usual, when it goes wrong for Black in this endgame, it is because White gets the chance to activate/coordinate in an optimal fashion. } )
25. Rf1
25. Ra7
26. Rc1{ White wants to force ... g7 - g6 , and it will soon be clear just why that is. }
26. g6
27. Ra1
27. Ra8( { With the pawn on  g7 , Black would happily play }27...Rh6 28.Nxb5 Rb7 { here, but now that fails to }29.Rxa6 { . } )
28. Nxb5( { It is exactly this move that Black's last move anticipated. Only }28.Kxd5 { and }28.Kc5 { offers some chances for an advantage, though I believe Black should be OK. } )
28. Kg7
29. Nc3
29. Rhb8{ Immediately using the open b-file to attack the pawn on  b2 . Without it, White has zero winning chances. }
30. Ra2
30. Rb4+
31. Kxd5
31. Rab8{ The  b2 -pawn will drop. }
