[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) Krause  Attack 8.e4 − 14.Kc2"]
[Black "Krause Attack 14.Kc2 Na6 15.Nxc4 #23 | Conclusion 15...b5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

( { This is the modern way of equalizing against   }14.Kc2 { . In the next chapter, I will present you the older way of playing, }15...O-O { , which is offered as an  alternative , but before I do so, let me reiterate some key points about the endgame we have just seen.    ♟ Given that the material is unbalanced, the key factor is the  activity of the pieces . Both sides constantly strive to find the optimal coordination of their pieces. We have seen moments where White's pieces reach their ideal positions and Black is struggling. On the other hand, Black's rook in some lines also performs miracles when activated. Note how in the last variation we also optimized the position of our king, all the way to }d4! {    ♟ We analyzed the endgame very thoroughly, perhaps even a bit too thoroughly, and the likelihood of all these lines appearing in your games, honestly, is rather small. I do feel that playing through these lines will give you a  good understanding  of what to aim for, which is maybe just as important, as your opponent is likely to deviate.    ♟ Last but not least, I like the endgame from a  practical viewpoint . At the start of the endgame, we still have three pawns and a rook for two pieces, and we are already }{ on move 22. White, therefore, has to be very much on top of things. In the training games I played online, that was very rarely the case! } )1. --
