18. Qe3( { With the king on  b3 , }18.Be2 b5! { is very dangerous − frankly, just lost. We can illustrate it with a sample line: }19.axb5 cxb5 20.Na5 Qc2+ 21.Kxb4 Qxb2+ 22.Nb3 ( 22.Kc5 Rac8+ 23.Nc6 Rxc6+! 24.Qxc6 { ( }24.Kxc6 Qd4! { shuts the door for the king. Mate is coming.)   }24...Qc3+ 25.Kd6 { . Sometimes the king can heroically walk into enemy lines and end up victorious. This is not such a case. }25...Qd4+ 26.Kc7 Qd8+ 27.Kb7 Qa8+ { , winning the queen and the game. } )22...a5+! 23.Rxa5 Rxa5 24.Kxa5 Qa3+ 25.Kb6 { ( }25.Kxb5 Rb8+ { doesn't end well either.)   }25...Rb8+ 26.Kc7 Qa7+ 27.Kd6 Rd8+ 28.Ke5 Rd5+ 29.Kf4 { ( }29.Qxd5 Qe3+ 30.Qe4 f6+! { also wins the queen.)   }29...Rf5+! { winning the queen! } )
18. Qe7{ A positional approach. We keep the queens on, as the knight will jump to  d5  next and the king may prove vulnerable on  b3 . }( 18...Qxe3+ 19.Nxe3 { is not the type of endgame we are striving for. Structurally, it's hard to make much of our pawns, and White is generally well-positioned. } )
