16. Qe5{ The overwhelming main move, and for good reason! From  e5  the queen controls important squares in the center and keeps an eye on the queen on  d5 , meaning White can always choose to play an endgame. On top of that, moving the queen from  e2  allows the  f1 -bishop, and with it the  h1 -rook, to get into the game. }
16. Rfd8( { A logical move, though strictly speaking, it doesn't do much to prepare for the upcoming exchange on  d5 . After }17.Qxd5 cxd5 18.Na5 { , the pawn }{ on  b7  is hanging, but it turns out that energetic play with }18...Rac8+ 19.Kd1 Nb4! 20.Nxb7 Rd7 21.Na5 e5 { guarantees enough play for the piece. The combination of a fantastic }{ horse on  b4  and the central pawns that will start running is enough to convince even the materialistic engine. }{ White should therefore start with the developing move   }17.Be2 { . } )
17. Be2
17. f6{ Only after this move does White oblige. }
18. Qxd5( 18.Qe3?! b5! { is one of those cases where Black is just in time with counterplay. The line }19.axb5 Nb4+ 20.Kc3 cxb5 21.Kxb4 ( 21.Nb6! { may be a better shot, but Black is anyway for choice. } )21...bxc4 22.Bxc4 Rab8+ 23.Kc3 Rdc8 24.Ra4 { looks like it allows White to escape until you see }24...Qb5! 25.Qxe6+ Kh8 { and the king is highly }{ uncomfortable on  c3 ! } )
18. cxd5{ The only serious recapture. At the risk of repeating myself, we need the three connected central passers for the endgame to be viable. }
19. Na5{ I was about to end the line here, thinking that the rook is misplaced on  d8  and Black has to lose additional time worrying about the  b7 -pawn, and then an old Kramnik game caught my attention. First, a few more general thoughts about this position.    We are of course happy to get three connected passers in the center, and it's the structure we should always be striving for. Place the  d5 -pawn back on  c6 , and suddenly our potential to promote becomes very limited. White, on the other hand, generally tries to get play on the queenside going, as we see here.    It is very hard, in the long run, for White to stop our central pawns, so the queenside is where the focus should be. The knight on  a5  does an annoying job attacking  b7 , while the knight on  a6  is vulnerable to the bishop on  e2  as well. Very often, White swiftly brings in the rook via  a1 - a3 - b3  to add more pressure on the queenside.    In the meantime, Black has to do two things: try to keep White's initiative on the queenside within acceptable terms and... push those central pawns!    Very often it comes down to some sort of a race; is White faster on the queenside, or do our central pawns provide enough counterplay? Needless to say, the assessment very often hangs on the smallest of details, as so often in sharp positions. }
19. Rdc8+
20. Kb1
20. Nb4{ Sacrificing the  b7 -pawn is something we have seen before and will see more often. Here it is close to giving Black full compensation − just not quite. }( { Plain bad is }20...Nc5 21.Rc1 b6 { and here both }22.b4 { or the elegant }22.Ra3! bxa5 23.Rac3 { gives White a winning game. } )
21. Nxb7( { The engine is also fond of }21.Ra3 b6 22.Nb7 { initially, but I like that there is still some justice in chess. Placing the knight }{ on  b7  looks ugly, and some deeper analysis also convinces the machine that the complications after }22...e5 { are not bad for Black. } )
21. Rc2( { A logical move, and an improvement over the Kramnik game I mentioned earlier. That game continued }21...Rab8 22.Na5 Rc2 23.Re1 Rd2 24.Ra3 Nc2 25.Kc1 { ( }25.Rb3!? { would have gotten the job done as well.)   }25...Rxe2 26.Rxe2 Nxa3 27.bxa3 { and Black resigned on move 35 in Kramnik-Haba, Germany 1993. } )
22. Re1
22. a5{ I like this concept, and I am showing it in order to illustrate just how close this is to fully working for Black. }
23. Bf1( { A novelty that is quickly pointed out by modern engines. It is an improvement over }23.Nd6 Rd8 24.Nb5 e5 25.Nc3 Rd2 26.Rd1 Rxd1+ 27.Bxd1 Kf7 28.Na2 { as seen in Ress-Willmann, email 2012. Now }28...Nc6! { allows Black to stay very much in the game, an opportunity that was missed. } )( { White needs to go to  f1 , as it's important to control the  d3 -square. See for instance }23.Bf3 Rf2 24.Rc1 Nd3!  )
23. Rf2{ Threatening ... Nb4 - c2  and pinning the  e1 -rook to the defense of the bishop. }
24. Rc1
24. Rb8
25. Nc5( { Once again the  d3 -square is important, which means }25.Nxa5 { is not the best because of }25...Nd3!  )
25. e5
26. Ra3
26. e4( { As strange as it sounds, this may be the critical position for the assessment of   }16...Rfd8 { . } )
27. Nb3( { This looks clumsy, but starting with }27.Rac3 Kf7 { and only now }28.Nb3 { runs into }28...d4! 29.Nxd4 Nd3 { , when Black gets counterplay }{ on  b2 . } )
27. Ra8{ Also not ideal, but Black needs to protect  a5 . }
28. Nd4
28. f5
29. Rac3( { Given that I don't recommend playing   }16...Rfd8 { , I will end our analysis here. As I said already, the line intrigued me, and that's why I analyzed it a lot further. It gave me the impression that any correspondence game would end in a draw from here. } )
29. Kf7{ But most of you want to play the Slav over the board, and there I am a lot less certain about the outcome! White is in control, and there are just two results that the game is headed for. That is enough for us to dismiss it as part of our repertoire. Nevertheless, I think it is an interesting piece of analysis that further shapes our understanding of the endgame.    As a final note, do appreciate how carefully White had to play in order to get the advantage. I dare say nobody would find this sequence over the board. }
