16. f6{ The most direct way of playing, forcing an exchange of queens. Black's alternatives here all have the same idea: preparing for the upcoming endgame. I have come to the conclusion though, that each of these preparatory moves has some disadvantage, hence I decided on the move that immediately forces the endgame. }( { I think it's important that we have a look at some of the alternatives first, as they provide an inside into my decision-making and give us great insights into how to handle the various endgames in general. We've seen the  16...Rfd8 option  as well as the  16...Rab8 idea , each presented in a separate informational.    Let's continue with }16...Rac8 { , which isn't a very convincing idea. }{ While it is true that the move prevents White from exchanging on  d5  }{ (the pin after ... cxd5  would cost a knight) }{ , the rook is, in itself, badly placed on  c8 . After the simple }17.Be2 f6 18.Qe3 b5 19.Rad1 Qf5+ 20.Bd3 { , White was already winning in Novikov-Rosiz, Tuzla 1989. The problem is that }20...Nb4+ 21.Kb1 Nxd3 { loses to }22.Nd6!  )( { Also not very convincing is }16...Nb4+ 17.Kc3 b5 18.axb5 cxb5 19.Kxb4 bxc4 20.Qxd5 exd5 { and now, instead of }21.Kc5?! { as in Ftacnik-Conquest, Prague 1989, better is }21.Be2! { , with a technically winning endgame. } )
17. Qxd5
17. cxd5
18. Nd2{ Not a particularly threatening retreat. On  d2 , the knight is a long way from the main battleground. }
18. Rac8+
19. Kb1( { It's not easy to find a good square for the king, and  b1  may be relatively best. }19.Kd3 Nb4+ { is disturbing, and so is   }19.Kd1 Nb4 { . } )( { Last, but not least }19.Kb3 Nc5+ 20.Ka2 e5! { secures a nice }{ square on  e6  for the knight, which can be occupied after }21.b4 Ne6 { , when Black is already for choice. The center will start storming forward. } )
19. e5( { It makes a lot of sense to start pushing the center, but there is nothing wrong with }19...Nc5 20.b4 Ne4 { either. After }21.Nxe4 dxe4 { , }{ we follow up with ... f6 - f5 , ... Kg8 - f7 - f6 , and start pushing the kingside forward. I would stress though, that this is still a very sharp endgame, with all three results possible. } )
20. Bxa6{ Preventing the strong maneuver ... Na6 - c5 / c7 - e6 . }
20. bxa6
21. Ra3
21. Kf7{ It's time for the king to support the pawns. We can end the line here, as it's clear Black is doing fine. White is a long way from getting counterplay on the queenside, while our center will soon be ready to go. }( { Let me give a sample line for illustrative purposes. }22.Rc1 Rxc1+ 23.Kxc1 Ke6 { and now both }( { I don't much like }23...Rc8+ 24.Rc3 Rxc3+ 25.bxc3 { , as the newly formed c-pawn is an effective defender and turns out the three-pawn advantage to a two-pawn advantage. } )24.Rb3 Rf7 { and   }24.Rc3 Kd6 { prevent the white rook from doing any damage, while we are now set to }{ push ... f6 - f5 , ... e5 - e4 , etc. Note how we first carefully prevent any counterplay instead of rushing our pawns forward. 'Don't rush' is an important endgame rule! } )
