17. Qxd5
17. cxd5
18. Nd6( { Without a doubt the most testing option, and the reason this endgame is considered dangerous for Black. White attacks the pawn on }b7 { but in a more effective way than the }18.Na5 { we saw earlier. The most important difference is that }{ from  d6  the knight also prevents our rook from entering the c-file. } )
18. Rab8{ Not the most active of defenses, but we are planning to play ... Na6 - b4 - c6  and ... Rf8 - d8  next, which expels the active knight from  d6 . After that, the  b8 -rook will find a better purpose. }( { Note that }19.Nxb7 { does not win a pawn because of the intermediate }19...Nb4+ { , }{ before recapturing on  b7 . } )( { In the line with  18.Nd2 , I proposed }18...Nc5 { as a decent alternative to the main recommendation, but I wouldn't do so here. As I have stressed earlier, this endgame often comes down to a race between our central pawns and White's initiative on the queenside. Now }19.b4 Ne4 20.Nxe4 dxe4 21.a5! { already gives White a winning }{ advantage.  a5 - a6  is a threat, and White can quickly follow up with  Bf1 - c4 ,  Kc2 - b3 , centralizing the rooks, etc.    Do compare the position to the one we saw in the  18.Nd2 line  to appreciate the differences! White had the king on  b1  there and was not to move. Those two tempi change the evaluation of the position. } )
19. Kb3{ It's unlikely anyone would voluntarily move their king into a check, but since it's one of the engine's suggestions, I thought I would be remiss not to include it. }
19. Nc5+
20. Ka3{ White now wants to quickly play  Ra1 - c1 ,  b2 - b4 , and get the usual queenside play going. }
20. f5{ Black has other options, but I am really fond of this one! }
21. Rc1
21. Ne4
22. Nxe4
22. fxe4{ Now that's a center! We plan to bring in the king (... Kg8 - f7 - f6 - e5 ) and get those pawns rolling. I'd not feel comfortable with White here, though the engine obviously suggests it's all 0.00. }
