1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. a4( { Isolating the pawn on  c4  is the best way to go. By preventing ... b7 - b5 , White prepares to regain the  c4 -pawn. As we will see, the alternatives }5.e4 b5 { ,   }5.e3 b5 6.a4 b4 { , and   }5.g3 b5 { leave Black in excellent shape. } )
5. Bf5{ Not just developing the bishop but also preventing  e2 - e4 . Our development scheme is quite clear: in random order, we will play ... e7 - e6 , ... Bf8 - b4 , ... O-O , and ... Nb8 - d7 . Once we achieve that, we can start looking for central breaks connected to ... c6 - c5  and ... e6 - e5 . }
6. Ne5{ This has always been considered the most critical response, even from the early days of this variation. White does not necessarily intend to take back the pawn on  c4  with the knight but, more importantly, prepares to set up a big center with  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 , in order to embarrass Black's light-squared bishop and knight on  f6 . A very ambitious plan indeed that, if carried out successfully, would give White a big advantage. }
6. e6( { While, at first sight, this does not seem to counter White's intentions, it will soon become apparent that it does. The alternative }6...Nbd7 { is very reliable as well, which is why I offer both moves as part of this Lifetime Repertoire. Note that the direct }6...c5? { is met with }7.e4! { , with the idea that }7...Nxe4 8.Qf3 { leads to immediate trouble. } )
7. f3
7. Bb4( { Vladimir Kramnik defended Black's position in the endgame after }7...c5 8.e4 Bg6 9.Be3 cxd4 10.Qxd4 Qxd4 11.Bxd4 { in a couple of games, including his 2006 WC match against Veselin Topalov, and so did Vishy Anand in his 2010 match against the same player. Nowadays, the endgame has the reputation of being pretty lousy − besides being completely one-sided. That's why we choose the much more ambitious text move. } )
8. e4( { At the top level, this has largely been replaced by }8.Nxc4 { , which is explored in separate chapters! However, don't think that the current section is of less importance. }8.e4 { has an enormous history, forces Black to sacrifice a piece, and is still one of the critical tests of the variation. It may well take the central stage again someday. } )
8. Bxe4{ The point of Black's previous move. Of course, we were not planning to retreat with the bishop! The idea of this sacrifice was first mentioned by Orla Herman Krause (1867-1935) in 1926.    Krause was a doctor by profession, working in the hospital of Oringe (Denmark). His chess analysis, however, makes him known to this very day. He published his analysis in various German publications, and there are numerous discoveries that carry his name. This variation is the most famous among them.    It was in the following year that André Chéron, nowadays mostly known for his famous endgame work, published  Traite Complet d'Echecs , where he confirmed Krause's analysis. Chéron then went on to introduce the sacrifice into practice at the 1928 World Amateur Championship in The Hague. }( { Before moving on, I should briefly mention that taking on  e4  with the knight doesn't quite have the same effect: }8...Nxe4 9.fxe4 Qh4+ 10.Ke2! { ( }10.g3 Qxe4+! { is what White needs to avoid.)   }10...Bxe4 11.g3 Qh5+ 12.g4 Bd3+ 13.Kf3 { and Black is running out of steam. } )
9. fxe4
9. Nxe4
10. Bd2( { These days an automatic move, but that was not at all the case in the initial development of this variation. }10.Qf3 { was considered to be the critical response, and it was assumed that giving up another pawn with the text move can't possibly give White chances to fight for an advantage.    It was Vladimir Kramnik who did a great job in the nineties proving that it is possible to do just that, and nowadays it's the absolute main move in the position. White does give up yet another pawn but exchanges a lot of Black pieces in the process. } )
10. Qxd4( { The only viable option, as the greedy }10...Qh4+ 11.g3 Nxg3 12.hxg3 Qxh1 { leaves Black too far behind in development. After the energetic }13.Qg4 { , White has a murderous initiative. } )
11. Nxe4
11. Qxe4+( { The stem game continued }11...Bxd2+ 12.Qxd2 Qxe5 13.Qe2 O-O 14.Nc3 Nd7 { and was eventually drawn in Enevoldsen-Piazzini, Buenos Aires 1939. It was only years later that it was discovered that the simple   }13.O-O-O! { gives White a near-winning advantage, effectively moving  11...Bxd2+  to oblivion. } )
12. Qe2
12. Bxd2+
13. Kxd2
13. Qd5+{ For the moment, we have four pawns for the bishop, meaning we are doing fine materially speaking. Our pawn on  c4  is weak though and will likely drop off. It is hard to speak in broad general terms about the position, as it is so unbalanced, but you do have access to an extensive overview in the corresponding  Informational . }( { An important thing to note is that the best check is indeed on  d5 . That is shown in the variation }13...Qd4+ 14.Kc2 Na6 15.Rd1 { , when it would be great to be able to swing the queen over }{ to  a5 , creating immediate counterplay. With the queen on  d4 , however, that is not allowed. } )
14. Kc2{ In terms of games played, this is the absolute main line. }
14. Na6{ On  a6  the knight is well placed, as it can jump into the weakened square  b4  at any moment. }( { We are forced to give up the  c4 -pawn, as }14...b5 15.Rd1 Qc5 16.axb5 { is very strong. Now }16...cxb5 17.g4! { , as proposed by Vigorito, is very strong and leaves White with a winning advantage. }{ The simple  Bf1 - g2  is being prepared. }{ Less clear is }17.Qf3 Qxe5 18.Qxa8 O-O { , when Black is still kicking, though }19.Qf3 { should still preserve an advantage. } )( { Another inaccuracy is }14...O-O { , which is refuted by }15.Qe3! { preparing  Bf1xc4 . An additional issue is that }15...b5 16.Rd1! { traps the queen. } )
15. Nxc4{ Not only taking a pawn but also handing the  e5 -square to the queen. }
15. O-O( { Though I suspect this move will be overtaken by }15...b5 { in terms of popularity, a quick search in the database will show you that this is by some margin the most played move in the position. }{ The king is very safe on  g8 , but the downside is also obvious.    We already know  Qe2 - e5  is White's main option, and after an exchange of queens, we would prefer to have our king a bit closer to the center. Lately, the move has gotten under a bit of pressure, and indeed, the line will require a lot of resourcefulness. Nevertheless, I think it's very playable. } )
16. Qe5{ The overwhelming main move, and for good reason! From  e5  the queen controls important squares in the center and keeps an eye on the queen on  d5 , meaning White can always choose to play an endgame. On top of that, moving the queen from  e2  allows the  f1 -bishop, and with it the  h1 -rook, to get into the game. }
16. f6{ The most direct way of playing, forcing an exchange of queens. Black's alternatives here all have the same idea: preparing for the upcoming endgame. I have come to the conclusion though, that each of these preparatory moves has some disadvantage, hence I decided on the move that immediately forces the endgame. }( { I think it's important that we have a look at some of the alternatives first, as they provide an inside into my decision-making and give us great insights into how to handle the various endgames in general. We've seen the  16...Rfd8 option  as well as the  16...Rab8 idea , each presented in a separate informational.    Let's continue with }16...Rac8 { , which isn't a very convincing idea. }{ While it is true that the move prevents White from exchanging on  d5  }{ (the pin after ... cxd5  would cost a knight) }{ , the rook is, in itself, badly placed on  c8 . After the simple }17.Be2 f6 18.Qe3 b5 19.Rad1 Qf5+ 20.Bd3 { , White was already winning in Novikov-Rosiz, Tuzla 1989. The problem is that }20...Nb4+ 21.Kb1 Nxd3 { loses to }22.Nd6!  )( { Also not very convincing is }16...Nb4+ 17.Kc3 b5 18.axb5 cxb5 19.Kxb4 bxc4 20.Qxd5 exd5 { and now, instead of }21.Kc5?! { as in Ftacnik-Conquest, Prague 1989, better is }21.Be2! { , with a technically winning endgame. } )
17. Qxd5
17. cxd5
18. Nd6( { Without a doubt the most testing option, and the reason this endgame is considered dangerous for Black. White attacks the pawn on }b7 { but in a more effective way than the }18.Na5 { we saw earlier. The most important difference is that }{ from  d6  the knight also prevents our rook from entering the c-file. } )
18. Rab8{ Not the most active of defenses, but we are planning to play ... Na6 - b4 - c6  and ... Rf8 - d8  next, which expels the active knight from  d6 . After that, the  b8 -rook will find a better purpose. }( { Note that }19.Nxb7 { does not win a pawn because of the intermediate }19...Nb4+ { , }{ before recapturing on  b7 . } )( { In the line with  18.Nd2 , I proposed }18...Nc5 { as a decent alternative to the main recommendation, but I wouldn't do so here. As I have stressed earlier, this endgame often comes down to a race between our central pawns and White's initiative on the queenside. Now }19.b4 Ne4 20.Nxe4 dxe4 21.a5! { already gives White a winning }{ advantage.  a5 - a6  is a threat, and White can quickly follow up with  Bf1 - c4 ,  Kc2 - b3 , centralizing the rooks, etc.    Do compare the position to the one we saw in the  18.Nd2 line  to appreciate the differences! White had the king on  b1  there and was not to move. Those two tempi change the evaluation of the position. } )
19. Be2{ Having seen the various alternatives for White in this position, some more serious than others, it will become clear that this is the real test of this endgame. White simply develops the bishop and prepares to bring the  h1 -rook into the game. }
19. Nb4+( 19...Rfd8 20.Nb5 Nb4+ 21.Kd2 { transposes to  19...Nb4+ . In this case, I see no difference between the two moves, though we know there often is! } )
20. Kd2{ The best square for the king, keeping the c-file open for the rooks. There is no need to attack the  b4 -knight, as we will likely be retreating it to  c6  rather sooner than later anyway. }
20. Rfd8( 20...a6? 21.Ra3 Rfd8 22.Rb3! { gave White a big advantage in Babula-Rausis, Elista 1998. } )( { It would also be a mistake to bring the knight back to  c6  too soon. After }20...Nc6 21.Rhc1! { , with the idea }21...Rfd8 22.Nxb7! { , Black is just lost following }22...Rxb7 23.Rxc6 Rxb2+ 24.Kd1 { , when White will win on the queenside. } )
21. Nb5
21. Nc6{ Only now do we drop back the knight, after White's knight is no longer on  d6  and  Rhc1  no longer carries the threat of  Nxb7 . }( { The position on the board, I believe, is crucial for the assessment of the move   }16...f6 { . Initially, engines do not approve of what we are doing, but further analysis proves Black is holding. In terms of what both sides are aiming for here, there is nothing new to say: White tries to make headway on the queenside, and we try to simultaneously slow White down in doing so, while gently trying to make the most of our central pawn mass.    Some words of warning: we will be studying this endgame in excruciating detail, and some of the lines we will be seeing are very long. I feel we have to go through this process though, as many of the lines have a surprisingly forcing nature, and cutting them short is difficult. } )( { Two lines to avoid are }21...a6 { , which is strongly met with }22.Kc3! { and   }21...a5 { − a move that I don't like on general grounds, as it weakens the queenside. }22.Rhc1 Nc6 23.Ra3 { , }{ with the idea of  Ra3 - b3  followed by  Nb5 - a3 , so that ... Nc6 - b4  can be met with  Na3 - c2 , removing the blockading knight. } )
22. Rhc1{ The move that engines are most fond of, which also sets a nasty trap. }
22. Kf7( { Instead, }22...f5 23.a5! { is the trap I was referring to. In order to prevent White from breaking through on the queenside, we should now play }23...a6 { , but }24.Nc7 { threatens to take }{ both  e6  and  a6 , leaving our position in ruins. } )
23. b4( { Now }23.a5 a6 { leads nowhere, and after }24.Nc3 f5 { , we start our typical play in the center. } )
23. a6
24. Na3( 24.Nc3 { would allow }24...Nxb4 { which, after the text move, is met with a check }{ on  c7 . } )
24. Ke7( { Not only further centralizing the king but also dealing with White's main threat: }25.Bxa6 { . } )
25. Rab1
25. Ra8{ Sometimes we have to simply make an ugly move when the position demands it. We have now stopped all ideas connected to sacrifices on  a6  and are always ready for the  b4 - b5  break. }
26. Bd1{ By protecting  a4 , White prepares the  b4 - b5  push and can now recapture with the rook on  b5 . }
26. f5( { We push the f-pawn, as }26...e5 { leaves our center too loose. That immediately shows in the line }27.b5 axb5 28.Rxb5 Rd7 29.Bg4! { , when Black }{ loses either  b7  or  d5 . } )
27. b5
27. axb5
28. Rxb5
28. Rd7{ Time to take stock! Engines give White an edge in this position, but I do not understand why as to me, it looks like Black has done a reasonable job preventing being overrun on the queenside, while it's clear that our central pawns will have their say at some point in time. I decided to let the engines figure it out for themselves and let them play training games from this position; all of them ended up drawn! }( { I will quote one of those games here, which I think gives a reasonable insight into the position. }29.h4 g6 { (as usual, we avoid the positional mistake }29...h6? 30.h5! { )   }30.Rb6 h6 { , }{ preparing to expand with  g6 - g5 . }{ (Worse is }30...e5?! 31.Rc5 e4 32.Ke3! { , when our center is vulnerable.)   }31.Rcb1 Nd8 { looks passive but does a great job }{ protecting  b7  and  e6 . }( { Another game took a sharper course with }31...Ra7 32.Nb5 Ra6 33.Rxa6 bxa6 34.Na3 Na5 35.Be2 Rd6 36.Nc2 { , when Black is forced to give up the a-pawn but the central counterplay comes in time: }36...e5 37.Nb4 e4 38.Bxa6 d4 39.Bb5 Kf6 40.Na6 Ke5 { and this was eventually drawn. I am a bit hesitant to enter such lines though, as giving up the a-pawn greatly sharpens play and suddenly forces us to be very precise. } )32.Nb5 Rc8 33.Nd4 Rc4 34.R6b4 Rxb4 35.Rxb4 g5 36.h5 g4 37.g3 Kf6 38.Be2 Nf7 ( 38...Rg7 39.Rb6 Rg5 40.a5! { sets the beautiful trap: }40...Rxh5? 41.Rxb7! Nxb7 42.a6! { , when the a-pawn becomes the hero. The line continues quite beautifully with }42...Rg5 43.axb7 Rg8 { and now }44.Nc6? f4! { actually holds, but the careful }44.Ke1 { decides the issue. } )39.Rb6 Nd6 40.Bb5 { ( }40.Ke3 Ke5 41.a5 Rg7!? { preparing ... Rg5  is fine }{ for Black too.)   }40...Rd8 41.Bd3 Ke5 42.Ne2 Ne4+ 43.Bxe4 dxe4+ 44.Ke1 Rd3 45.Rxb7 Ra3 46.Rb5+ Kf6 47.a5 e5 { and neither side could make any progress. } )
