25. d4
26. Bc4+( { It makes sense to give a check first before moving the knight, as }26.Na4 { allows the cheeky }26...d3! { followed by ... e5 - e4 . } )
26. Kf8
27. Nd5{ Another advantage of starting with a check is that this square has now become available as well. }
27. e4{ Not only pushing the pawn but also freeing up a great square for our knight. }
28. Ba2{ Prophylaxis against ... Nc6 - e5  and clearing the c-file for a rook. }
28. Ne5
29. Rc1
29. Rbc8
30. Nc7( 30.h4 g6 31.Nf4 Ke7 32.Bd5 { transposes to the  28.Nf4 line . } )( 30.Nf4 Ke7 31.Ne6 { transposes to  30.Nc7 . } )
30. Ke7
31. Ne6{ Another very forced line that we have to be well aware of. }
31. Rxc1
32. Rxc1
32. Rd7
33. Nc5
33. Rd6( { Of course, a passive move like }33...Rc7 { simply won't do after }34.Bd5 { and the queenside collapses. } )
34. Rf1{ The only move that keeps the balance! }
34. Rg6
35. g3{ White allows us to stabilize the center. }
35. Nf3+
36. Kc2
36. b6( { An excellent follow-up, and White is under serious pressure now. A sample line is }37.axb6 Rxb6 38.g4 Rg6! { , when }39.gxf5 Rg2+ { is already winning for Black; the king doesn't have a good square. } )
