8. e6( { I did some investigating in the line after }8...Bg6 9.a5 Nbd5 10.a6!? { and didn't like what I was seeing. White has an annoying initiative on the queenside. } )( 8...e6 { is fine though, and no longer very surprising to us I assume. We have seen this type of solution more often throughout the course. } )
9. Nxf5( { Here, }9.a5 Nbd5 10.a6 Bb4!? { immediately shows the difference with   }8...Bg6 { . We are getting mobilized and ready to fight for the initiative. } )
9. exf5
10. g3( { Again, }10.a5 Nbd5 11.a6 Bb4 { doesn't lead anywhere for White. } )
10. a5{ Stopping White from playing  a4 - a5  indefinitely, and fixing the  b4 -square for our bishop or knight. }
11. Bh3( { This is the only serious try. After the casual }11.Bg2 Bb4 12.O-O O-O { , we have nothing to worry about. } )
11. g6
12. O-O( { Now it becomes apparent why White played   }11.Bh3 { , provoking }11...g6 { . }{ Our desired setup of placing the bishop on  b4  and castling kingside is no longer available, }{ as }12.O-O Bb4 { runs into }13.Bh6! { , }{ when our king is stuck on  e8 . } )
12. Bg7{ Moving the bishop to  g7  has been played exclusively here, with the main purpose of getting the king to  g8 . The bishop itself isn't very effective on  g7 , staring at the pawn on  d4 . }
13. Bg2( 13.Bg5 O-O 14.Bg2 { transposes to  13.Bg2 . } )
13. O-O
14. Bg5( { White should indeed get rid of this bishop. After, for instance, }14.e3 Re8 { , }{ the bishop on  c1  has little potential, while Black's knights control the key squares  e4  and  d5 . } )
14. Qd6
15. Bxf6
15. Bxf6
16. e3{ White's advantage is not huge here, obviously, yet it's there and of a structural nature, and that's always tricky. }( { In Kollars-Rosner, Magdeburg 2022, Black drifted into a worse position after }16...Rfe8 17.Qb3 Qb4 18.Qc2 Rad8 19.Ra3 Nc4 20.Rb3 Qe7 21.Ne2 { , when the knight starts a route }{ towards  d3 . White had serious pressure and won a good game. We have to take this game into account when choosing our next moves. } )
16. h5( { The first small deviation, creating some tension on the kingside. Now }17.Qb3 Qb4 18.Qc2 h4! { is a bit annoying for White, as there is no way to get rid of the h-pawn. } )
17. h4{ Stopping any further expansion. }
17. Rfd8{ Note how we place the  f8 -rook on  d8 , and not  e8 , as in the Kollars game. We are aiming for ... c6 - c5  sometimes, and the rook will be much better placed on  d8  in those cases. }
18. Qb3( 18.Ne2 c5! { is an improved version of   }17.Ne2 c5 { . } )
18. Qb4
19. Qc2
19. Qc4( 19...c5 { more or less works here as well, but I am not thrilled to recommend it, given the line }20.Na2 Qc4 21.Qxc4 Nxc4 22.Rac1 Nxb2 23.Rxc5 Nxa4 24.Rb5 { , which looks very scary for Black, despite what the engine says. } )
20. Rfc1
20. Be7( { Bringing the bishop to the desired diagonal. Again, }20...c5?! { isn't ideal. This time because of }21.Nd5! Qxc2 22.Nxf6+ { . } )
21. Ne2
21. Qxc2
22. Rxc2{ The differences with the Kollars game are clear. Without queens, there isn't much happening in this endgame. }
22. Nd7( { An instructive mistake would be }22...Nd5 { . The position after }23.Bxd5! Rxd5 24.Nf4 Rdd8 25.Nd3 { isn’t lost, but White’s knight is surely superior to the bishop, and some prolonged suffering in a slightly worse endgame may be ahead. } )
23. Rc3{ Trying to bring the rook over to  b3 . }
23. Bb4
24. Rb3
24. c5{ Suddenly ... c5 - c4  is a big threat. }
