10. f3{ With the obvious intention of pushing the e-pawn one step as well. }
10. Bg6( { The obvious }10...O-O 11.e4 { hits the bishop }{ on  e4  and gives White just enough time to meet }11...Bg6 { with }12.Be3 { , }{ covering the  d4 -pawn. That's why we play }{   }10...Bg6 { , }{ so that  d4  will be hanging after  e3 - e4 . } )
11. a5
11. Nbd7{ This is a new move, but it's not very surprising, as it's one of the engine's top choices. }( { Practice had only seen }11...Nxc4 12.Bxc4 Rb8 13.O-O b5 14.axb6 axb6 15.Rd1 { and White had a pleasant edge in Sarana-Fedoseev, Cheliabinsk rapid 2020.      }12...O-O { is an improvement over that game, but nevertheless }13.O-O { gives White something to work with. The break }13...b5 { leads to an endgame that, after }14.axb6 axb6 15.Rxa8 Qxa8 16.Qxb6 Rb8 17.Qa6 Qxa6 18.Bxa6 c5 { , is doable according to the engine, but after counting the pawns, I don't see where the fun is here. } )
