6. Ne5{ This has always been considered the most critical response, even from the early days of this variation. White does not necessarily intend to take back the pawn on  c4  with the knight but, more importantly, prepares to set up a big center with  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 , in order to embarrass Black's light-squared bishop and knight on  f6 . A very ambitious plan indeed that, if carried out successfully, would give White a big advantage. }
6. Nbd7( { I felt that next to the long theoretical line that arises after }6...e6 7.f3 Bb4 { , I should provide a solid alternative that is easier on the memory and very reliable. } )
7. Nxc4
7. Nb6( { And this is that alternative. It's a relatively new invention in the world of the Slav Defense. It says enough that in his 1988 book  The Slav for the Tournament Player , Glenn Flear mentioned that }7...Nb6 { 'has been tried, but }8.Ne5 e6 9.f3 Nfd7 10.a5! Nxe5 11.axb6 Nd7 12.e4 Bg6 13.Rxa7! {   gives insufficient play for the pawn.'    That is very true, but it is the move   }8...a5! { which would, some years after the book was published, spring new life into the variation. White is prevented }{ from playing  a4 - a5  and we take up a very sturdy position. } )( { The move }7...Nb6 { , in combination with  8...a5 , was only developed in the '90s, under the leadership of players like Nigel Short and Ivan Sokolov. In the decades before, people had almost exclusively played }7...Qc7 { followed by ... e7 - e5  to which the Alekine-Euwe matches in the 30's certainly contributed. } )( { Note that }7...e6 8.f3 Bb4 9.e4 Nxe4 10.fxe4 Qh4+ 11.Kd2! { , doesn't quite work here, as was already established in Stoltz-Mieses, Swinemuende 1932. } )
8. e3{ Not with the idea to outright refute the variation, but rather aimed at gaining a small advantage. White simply protects the knight on  c4  so that after a potential exchange, the  f1 -bishop gets developed. }
8. e6
9. Qb3{ Adding more pressure on our queenside and preparing to expand in the center with  f2 - f3  and  e3 - e4 . }( { The immediate }9.f3 { is less good because of }9...Bb4! { and now }10.e4 Nxe4! { is already winning. That's why the queen first controls }{ the  b4 -square. } )
9. Be7( 9...Nxc4 10.Bxc4 Qb6 { was held to a draw by Viktor Laznicka against Veselin Topalov, but after some prolonged suffering. Indeed, }11.f3 { ( }11.Ke2!? { preventing }{ the later ... Bf5 - d3  may }{ be smart!)   }11...Qxb3 12.Bxb3 Bd3 13.e4 a5?! 14.Be3 Bb4 15.Kf2 Ba6 16.Rhd1 O-O 17.Rac1 Rfd8 18.g4! { was excellent for White. } )
10. a5{ Also a logical follow-up, and one that requires us to be precise. }
10. Nxc4
11. Bxc4
11. O-O( { A new and strong idea by the engine. Previously, everyone had protected their pawn with }11...Qc7 { , but }12.f3 O-O 13.e4 Bg6 14.Be3 { is quite unpleasant. White has central control and pressure on the queenside as well. } )
12. Qxb7{ The principled response. Now we are forced to prove compensation. }
12. Bd6( { The most straightforward. }12...Qd6!? { also gives adequate compensation but feels less clear after }13.O-O { ( }13.Qb3 e5! { )   }13...Ng4! 14.f4 Nf6 { , when it's not easy for me to explain how we should go about proving our compensation after, say, }15.Be2 { . }{ The engine's evaluation of 0.06 surely means Black has a fine game, but I like things to be a bit more clear-cut. We are still a pawn down after all. } )
13. Qxc6{ Quite greedy! }
13. Rc8
14. Qa4
14. Ne4( { Black has excellent compensation. We are fully mobilized and White's king is a bit stuck for now, as }15.O-O Qc7! { drops the  h2 -pawn. } )
