13. hxg3{ We have reached the exact same position as in the note on move 11 but with the bishop on  c2 . This gives us more active possibilities, connected, among other things, to the pawn on  a4 . }
13. e6
14. f3
14. Bb4
15. Kf2
15. O-O
16. e4
16. c5( { Black was completely fine in Nikolov-Solak, Golden Sands 2014. What's more, after }17.Nb5? cxd4 18.Nxd4 Bxe4! { , Black was already winning, as }19.fxe4 Bc5 20.Be3 Ng4+ { wins back the piece with interest. } )( { White's best continuation is }17.d5 { , but after }17...exd5 18.Nxd5 Nxd5 19.exd5 Nf6 20.d6 Rad8 { , the passed pawn won't present any danger. For instance, supporting it further with }21.Bf4 { is easily met by }21...Nd5 { , while   }21.Bg5 Bb3 22.Bxf6 gxf6 { will liquidate into a 0.00 endgame following ... Bb3xc4  and the d-pawn falls. } )
