9. g3{ I always saw this move as an invitation to let theory be theory and just play chess. White fianchettoes the light-squared bishop, castles kingside, and the game will start. Even in this seemingly non-theoretical line though, theory has developed over the years. }
9. e6
10. Bg2
10. Bb4
11. O-O
11. O-O( { There isn't much to comment on for now. Both sides have made all the logical moves, and since }12.e4 Bxc3! { loses a pawn, White needs to prepare this push in a more modest way. } )
12. e3
12. h6
13. Qe2( { An interesting moment. White's plan is to play  Rf1 - d1  followed by  e3 - e4  and for many years, the standard reply here was }13...Bh7 { . Over a hundred games continued }14.Rd1 Nfd7 15.Nd3 Qe7 16.e4 e5 { , which was considered acceptable for Black.    However, the simple }17.dxe5 { , introduced by Boris Gelfand's long-time trainer and friend, Alexander Huzman, gives White a serious edge. Following }17...Nxe5 18.Nxe5 Qxe5 19.Be3 { , there is annoying pressure, and }19...Bc5 20.Rac1! Bxe3 21.Qxe3 { doesn't help much.    Slowly but surely, players have come to realize  13...Bh7  may not be the best way to go, as it allows White too much freedom. } )
13. Nfd7
14. Nd3{ The obvious move, but it's exactly what we are hoping for! Some strong players fell for this trap. }
14. e5{ After this power move, it's immediately obvious Black has a great game. }( 15.Nxe5? Nxe5 16.dxe5 Bd3 { loses the exchange and   }15.dxe5 Bxd3 16.Qxd3 Nxe5 17.Qc2 Qd3! { offers the exchange of queens into an endgame that is very pleasant for Black. } )
