3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. a4( { Isolating the pawn on  c4  is the best way to go. By preventing ... b7 - b5 , White prepares to regain the  c4 -pawn. As we will see, the alternatives }5.e4 b5 { ,   }5.e3 b5 6.a4 b4 { , and   }5.g3 b5 { leave Black in excellent shape. } )
5. Bf5{ Not just developing the bishop but also preventing  e2 - e4 . Our development scheme is quite clear: in random order, we will play ... e7 - e6 , ... Bf8 - b4 , ... O-O , and ... Nb8 - d7 . Once we achieve that, we can start looking for central breaks connected to ... c6 - c5  and ... e6 - e5 . }
6. Ne5{ This has always been considered the most critical response, even from the early days of this variation. White does not necessarily intend to take back the pawn on  c4  with the knight but, more importantly, prepares to set up a big center with  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 , in order to embarrass Black's light-squared bishop and knight on  f6 . A very ambitious plan indeed that, if carried out successfully, would give White a big advantage. }
6. Nbd7( { I felt that next to the long theoretical line that arises after }6...e6 7.f3 Bb4 { , I should provide a solid alternative that is easier on the memory and very reliable. } )
7. Nxc4
7. Nb6( { And this is that alternative. It's a relatively new invention in the world of the Slav Defense. It says enough that in his 1988 book  The Slav for the Tournament Player , Glenn Flear mentioned that }7...Nb6 { 'has been tried, but }8.Ne5 e6 9.f3 Nfd7 10.a5! Nxe5 11.axb6 Nd7 12.e4 Bg6 13.Rxa7! {   gives insufficient play for the pawn.'    That is very true, but it is the move   }8...a5! { which would, some years after the book was published, spring new life into the variation. White is prevented }{ from playing  a4 - a5  and we take up a very sturdy position. } )( { The move }7...Nb6 { , in combination with  8...a5 , was only developed in the '90s, under the leadership of players like Nigel Short and Ivan Sokolov. In the decades before, people had almost exclusively played }7...Qc7 { followed by ... e7 - e5  to which the Alekine-Euwe matches in the 30's certainly contributed. } )( { Note that }7...e6 8.f3 Bb4 9.e4 Nxe4 10.fxe4 Qh4+ 11.Kd2! { , doesn't quite work here, as was already established in Stoltz-Mieses, Swinemuende 1932. } )
8. Ne5
8. a5{ The key move that sprung new life into this variation in the '90s. White is prevented from pushing the a-pawn any further, and we have secured the  b4 -square for the future. }( { Jan Timman once tried }8...Nbd7 { , with the idea }9.Qb3 Nxe5 10.dxe5 Ng4 { . His opponent, none other than Garry Kasparov himself, outright refuted this way of playing with }11.Qxb7 Nxe5 12.f4!? Ng6 13.e4 Bd7 14.f5 Ne5 15.Bf4 { and White was already winning. It is hard to find clear improvements for Black in this line. } )
9. Bg5{ A bit of a Boris Gelfand specialty. He used it four times in 2005. White simply develops harmoniously, and before playing  e2 - e3 , first brings the bishop out. }
9. Ne4( { Extremely rare, and certainly not forced. Over the years, the main move has become }9...g6 { , preparing to fianchetto the bishop and castle kingside. After }10.e3 Bg7 11.Bd3 Be6! { , play is approximately equal. } )( { In preparing for this course, I suddenly discovered the sharp }9...Ne4 { is possible as well. I think it's very likely we will catch our opponents off-guard with this move. } )
10. g4{ The most aggressive response and an attempt to outright refute Black's previous move. }
10. Nxc3
11. bxc3
11. Bc8( { The first new move. A 2015 correspondence game continued }11...Be6 { , but I dislike the sequence }12.Bh4 f6 13.Nd3 Bd5 14.f3 { since the engine now tries to force the moves }14...e5 15.e4 Bc4 16.Nxe5 Bxf1 17.Rxf1 g5 { upon us. I feel this gives White great compensation after }18.Bg3 fxe5 19.Bxe5 Rg8 20.Qb3 Rg6 21.f4!  )
12. Bh4
12. f6
13. Nd3
13. Qd5{ An important follow-up, forcing some concession out of White. }
14. Rg1
14. g5( { We play this move first since }14...e5 15.g5! { gives White some initiative. } )
15. Bg3
15. e5
16. dxe5
16. Qc4
17. Qc2
17. f5( { Black has great compensation for the pawn. For instance }18.gxf5 Bxf5 19.f3 Nd5 { when }20.e4? { is well met with }20...Ne3 { . } )
