6. Ne5{ This has always been considered the most critical response, even from the early days of this variation. White does not necessarily intend to take back the pawn on  c4  with the knight but, more importantly, prepares to set up a big center with  f2 - f3  and  e2 - e4 , in order to embarrass Black's light-squared bishop and knight on  f6 . A very ambitious plan indeed that, if carried out successfully, would give White a big advantage. }
6. Nbd7( { I felt that next to the long theoretical line that arises after }6...e6 7.f3 Bb4 { , I should provide a solid alternative that is easier on the memory and very reliable. } )
7. Nxc4
7. Nb6( { And this is that alternative. It's a relatively new invention in the world of the Slav Defense. It says enough that in his 1988 book  The Slav for the Tournament Player , Glenn Flear mentioned that }7...Nb6 { 'has been tried, but }8.Ne5 e6 9.f3 Nfd7 10.a5! Nxe5 11.axb6 Nd7 12.e4 Bg6 13.Rxa7! {   gives insufficient play for the pawn.'    That is very true, but it is the move   }8...a5! { which would, some years after the book was published, spring new life into the variation. White is prevented }{ from playing  a4 - a5  and we take up a very sturdy position. } )( { The move }7...Nb6 { , in combination with  8...a5 , was only developed in the '90s, under the leadership of players like Nigel Short and Ivan Sokolov. In the decades before, people had almost exclusively played }7...Qc7 { followed by ... e7 - e5  to which the Alekine-Euwe matches in the 30's certainly contributed. } )( { Note that }7...e6 8.f3 Bb4 9.e4 Nxe4 10.fxe4 Qh4+ 11.Kd2! { , doesn't quite work here, as was already established in Stoltz-Mieses, Swinemuende 1932. } )
8. Ne5
8. a5{ The key move that sprung new life into this variation in the '90s. White is prevented from pushing the a-pawn any further, and we have secured the  b4 -square for the future. }( { Jan Timman once tried }8...Nbd7 { , with the idea }9.Qb3 Nxe5 10.dxe5 Ng4 { . His opponent, none other than Garry Kasparov himself, outright refuted this way of playing with }11.Qxb7 Nxe5 12.f4!? Ng6 13.e4 Bd7 14.f5 Ne5 15.Bf4 { and White was already winning. It is hard to find clear improvements for Black in this line. } )
9. h4( { Modern chess! There is a very neat point behind this move. If, like in  9.f3 , we reply with }9...Nfd7 { , suddenly }10.e4 Nxe5 11.exf5! Ned7 12.h5! { is a hugely favorable version for White. } )( 9...Nbd7 { is a better attempt and an improved version of the aforementioned Kasparov-Timman game. Nevertheless, }10.Qb3 Nxe5 11.dxe5 Nd7 12.e4 { looks pleasant for White. } )( { A blitz game between Aronian and Anand, Leuven 2016, saw }9...g6 10.h5! { being played, which poses some serious questions to Black. That leaves just two moves   }9...e6 { and }9...h6 { , which are likely to transpose. } )
9. e6( 9...h6 10.f3 e6 { transposes, but it feels more logical to me to start with   }9...e6 { , waiting for }10.f3 { before safeguarding out bishop. } )
10. f3( { Here again, it's nice to compare variations. After   }9.f3 { , we play }9...Nfd7 { , but here that would lead to }{ our bishop on  f5  getting trapped. Another smart point behind  9.h4 . } )
10. h6
11. e4
11. Bh7
12. Be3{ A truly mesmerizing position. White has a center that we are unable to take down any time soon, but there is a pawn on  h4 , which slightly weakens White's position. In order to understand the differences, I moved the pawn from  h4  to  h2  and asked the engine to evaluate the position. This minor difference seems to be quite serious! As we will see, our counterplay here is largely based on the weakened dark squares on the kingside. }
12. Nfd7
13. Nd3{ Of course, White needs to keep pieces on the board. With every exchange, White's space advantage will become less and less relevant. }
13. Bd6
14. Ne2{ I would not have added this move if it had not been played in a recent correspondence game. I think the chances of encountering it in a practical game are close to zero. White prevents the check on  g3  but in an extremely artificial way. }
14. Nc4( { Giving the  e3 -bishop a push and preparing ... b7 - b5 . White's setup would work quite well after, for instance, }14...O-O 15.Qb3 Qe7 16.Nef4 { followed by  g2 - g4 . } )
15. Bg1
15. O-O
16. Rc1
16. b5( { An interesting pawn sacrifice but by no means forced. }16...Ncb6 { intending ... f7 - f5 !? is perfectly playable as well. } )
17. b3
17. Na3
18. Rxc6
18. Qb8( { We have excellent compensation for the pawn. The correspondence game Mezera-Tropf, ICCF 2023, continued }19.Qc1 bxa4 20.bxa4 Rc8 21.Rxc8+ Qxc8 22.Qxc8 Rxc8 23.Nc5 { and the draw offer was accepted. } )
