11. dxe5
11. Qxd1+
12. Kxd1{ This used to be played more or less exclusively. The king will find a safe spot on  c2 . }
12. Be6
13. Kc2{ White's plan is very straightforward: play  Ra1 - b1  and  b2 - b4 . Since our kingside is largely undeveloped it is remarkably hard to meet this plan. }( { The old main move used to be }13...f6 { , and now Veselin Topalov won a model game against Wang Yue in Sofia 2009. That game continued }14.Rb1 Nd7 15.b4 Nxe5 16.bxa5 Bc8 17.a6 bxa6 18.a5 Nd7 19.Na4 e5 20.Bc4 { and White was dominating.    It is possible that   }14...fxe5 { , as already played by Kasparov in 2003 is a better try, intending to meet }15.b4 { with }15...Nc4 16.Bxc4 Bxc4 17.bxa5 O-O-O { . Kasparov held this endgame quite comfortably against Vallejo Pons, but it is rather one-sided nevertheless and gives Black nothing to hope for but to salvage a draw.    It should also be mentioned that White has the interesting option of playing   }15.b3!? { to prevent a piece from }{ reaching  c4  and simply intend to play  Bc1 - e3  next. If the knight moves from  b6 , both  b3 - b4  (still!) or  Bf1 - c4  are options. For the reasons above, attention has switched to a new approach on move 13. } )
13. Nd7{ This move is the reason why taking on  d1  has largely disappeared from practice. }
14. Rb1{ It is interesting to see what happens if White follows the usual plan. }
14. Nxe5
15. f4{ White is forcing us to pick the right square, but that's not a very tough decision to make, as all other squares lose a piece. }( { Having spent no time on the move  13...f6 , it is clear that the plan connected to }15.b4 { now leads nowhere after }15...axb4 16.Rxb4 Bc8 { and Black has a healthy extra pawn. } )
15. Ng4( { Black is just better. }16.b4 { can still be met calmly with }16...axb4 17.Rxb4 Bc8 { . } )
