14. g6{ Another key move, preparing for ... f7 - f6  but stopping the threat of  f4 - f5 . }
15. Rb1( { As we are about to see, this doesn't quite cut it, but }15.Ne2 Nc5 { or   }15.Be2 f6 { are also very satisfactory for Black. } )
15. f6{ Sharp students may have already noticed that we have the exact same position now as in the aforementioned game of Topalov against Wang Yue but with the moves  f3 - f4  and ... g7 - g6  included. That is very favorable for Black, as taking on  e5  now immediately challenges the  f4 -pawn and our  f8 -bishop can quickly get into the game via  g7 . }
16. b4( { It is instructive just how bad White's position is after }16.exf6 exf6 { , when Black follows }{ up with ... O-O-O , ... Bf8 - b4 , ... Rh8 - e8 , ... Nd7 - c5 , etc, with huge pressure. The engine already gives an advantage of nearly -1. } )
16. fxe5
17. bxa5
17. Rxa5
18. Rxb7
18. Nc5( 18...exf4 { isn't bad either. } )
19. Rb8+
19. Kd7( { The text move is more precise than }19...Kf7 { since }19...Kd7 { introduces the ... Kd7 - c7  idea in some variations. Now  a4  is hanging, and ... Bf8 - g7  is coming. Black is better. } )
