7. Nb6( { And this is that alternative. It's a relatively new invention in the world of the Slav Defense. It says enough that in his 1988 book  The Slav for the Tournament Player , Glenn Flear mentioned that }7...Nb6 { 'has been tried, but }8.Ne5 e6 9.f3 Nfd7 10.a5! Nxe5 11.axb6 Nd7 12.e4 Bg6 13.Rxa7! {   gives insufficient play for the pawn.'    That is very true, but it is the move   }8...a5! { which would, some years after the book was published, spring new life into the variation. White is prevented }{ from playing  a4 - a5  and we take up a very sturdy position. } )( { The move }7...Nb6 { , in combination with  8...a5 , was only developed in the '90s, under the leadership of players like Nigel Short and Ivan Sokolov. In the decades before, people had almost exclusively played }7...Qc7 { followed by ... e7 - e5  to which the Alekine-Euwe matches in the 30's certainly contributed. } )( { Note that }7...e6 8.f3 Bb4 9.e4 Nxe4 10.fxe4 Qh4+ 11.Kd2! { , doesn't quite work here, as was already established in Stoltz-Mieses, Swinemuende 1932. } )
8. Ne5
8. a5{ The key move that sprung new life into this variation in the '90s. White is prevented from pushing the a-pawn any further, and we have secured the  b4 -square for the future. }( { Jan Timman once tried }8...Nbd7 { , with the idea }9.Qb3 Nxe5 10.dxe5 Ng4 { . His opponent, none other than Garry Kasparov himself, outright refuted this way of playing with }11.Qxb7 Nxe5 12.f4!? Ng6 13.e4 Bd7 14.f5 Ne5 15.Bf4 { and White was already winning. It is hard to find clear improvements for Black in this line. } )
9. f3{ The most obvious move in the position and, unsurprisingly, also the most popular one. White intends to play  e2 - e4  in one go. }
9. Nfd7( { A bit of an only move, challenging the knight on  e5 . After the tame }9...e6? 10.e4 Bg6 11.Be3 { , White would have a large advantage. } )
10. e4{ When I first started playing the Slav around 2000, this move led to very interesting and unexplored positions. Nowadays, it has largely gone out of fashion − and for good reason.    Simply put: after we capture on  e5 , White is forced to take back on either  e5  or  f5 , in both cases ruining the central structure. As it turns out, Black has nothing to fear in the remaining complications. As usual, modern engines have helped tremendously in coming to this conclusion. }
10. Nxe5{ A major crossroads. Taking on  e5  now leads to an endgame that used to be considered dangerous for Black, but not anymore. Taking on  f5  keeps the queens on, but the structural damage to White's pawn structure is obviously quite serious here. }
11. dxe5
11. Qxd1+
12. Nxd1{ A specialty of the Serbian GM Alexey Sarana. It is likely White's best fighting chance and in practice, Sarana has done extremely well with it. }
12. Be6{ The most obvious square. On  g6  the bishop is an unhappy piece. }
13. Nf2{ Quite a different position compared to the one where White recaptures on  d1  with the king. Here,  b2 - b4  is not at all the (short-term) plan, and White just wants to bring the knight to  d3  and prepare to expand on the kingside with  f3 - f4 , etc. }( { It is not at all easy to remember these differences, even for the strongest players in the world. Anish Giri played }13...Nd7 14.f4 g6 { in an online rapid game against Sarana. This is the right solution when White recaptures }{ on  d1  with the king, and it is also quite close to the right solution in this case, just not quite! }{ After }15.g4! { , instead of }15.h4 { as Sarana played, Anish would have been in big trouble. } )( { Another logical-looking move is }13...Bc4 { , in order to }{ prepare ... e7 - e6 . However, after the simple }14.Bxc4 Nxc4 15.Nd3 e6 16.g4!? { , White has a beautiful position. } )( { Last but not least, the move }13...f6 { is an important question. Now White plays }14.Nd3 { and after }14...Nd7 15.Nf4! { , Black is in trouble. The issue is that }15...Bg8 16.e6 Nc5 17.Bc4 { keeps the  e6 -pawn alive, as }17...g5 18.Be3! { is just in time. } )
13. g6( { And that's how, after some soul-searching, we arrive at this move. We try to play the way Anish did, but using the right move order! }14.f4?! f6! { is now fine for Black, so White has to play differently. } )
14. Nd3( 14.f4 f6!  )
14. Nd7( { Threatening ... Be6 - c4  and forcing White's next. Black can also start with }14...Bc4 { , but }15.Nc5 { may give White some hope for an advantage. } )( { Practice has so far only seen }14...Bg7 15.f4 Nd7 { , but I think White is a bit better after }16.Be2 { . Essentially, our bishop }{ is misplaced on  g7 , staring at the  e5 -pawn. It's best to keep the bishop on  f8  for now. } )
15. f4{ This move lacks punch now, and we just make our usual jab at the center. }
15. f6( { Black is already better. White has to take on  f6 , as otherwise, }16.-- fxe5 { will come, leaving White with two weak pawns on the e-file. } )
*
