14. Nd7( { Threatening ... Be6 - c4  and forcing White's next. Black can also start with }14...Bc4 { , but }15.Nc5 { may give White some hope for an advantage. } )( { Practice has so far only seen }14...Bg7 15.f4 Nd7 { , but I think White is a bit better after }16.Be2 { . Essentially, our bishop }{ is misplaced on  g7 , staring at the  e5 -pawn. It's best to keep the bishop on  f8  for now. } )
15. Nf4{ The critical response. We have to act with care now, as White's move carries a major positional threat. }
15. Nxe5
16. Nxe6
16. fxe6
17. f4( 17.h4 { is similar, and we would reply }17...Nd7! { to prevent being hemmed }{ in with  f3 - f4  and  e4 - e5 . } )
17. Nd7
18. e5{ This is an important moment! If White gets just one more move,  h2 - h4 , our  f8 -bishop will be locked forever and we will just be lost. Not worse, but just lost. Our next move is therefore of the utmost importance. Any other move would not suffice. }
18. g5( { An only move, but a good one! We make sure White won't be able to set up that bind on the kingside. An example of the point I am trying to make is seen in the sample line }18...Nb6 19.h4 Nd5 20.Bd3 Kf7 21.Bd2 h5 22.g3 { , when }{ the  f8 -bishop is forever locked in and White can just prepare actions on the queenside. This is a scenario that should be avoided at all costs and an instructive positional idea to keep in your toolbox. } )
19. g3{ An attempt to hold the structure together. We will now set our sights on the  f4 -pawn. }
19. gxf4
20. gxf4
20. Bh6{ With ... Nd7 - f8 - g6  coming, our bishop on  h6  is very much alive and kicking! }
