11. e4
11. Bg6
12. d5{ This has been played by some pretty strong players but isn't very critical. After we play ... e7 - e5 , White intends to take en passant and force us to recapture with the f-pawn. This is not a major weakening of our position though, and also allows us a slight lead in development. }
12. e5( 12...Qb6 { , as played by Ivan Sokolov once, is playable as well, but I believe }12...e5 { to be more clear-cut. } )
13. dxe6{ Any other move would make White's previous decision pointless. }
13. fxe6
14. Bc4
14. Qb6( { Impressive was Tukmakov's victory over Beliavsky in Bled 2001, where Vladimir Borisovich continued with this move. Black has options at this point as well though since }14...Bf7 { and }14...Qh4+!? { are fine as well. } )
15. Bxe6( { It is very dangerous to take the pawn. White should play the safer }15.Qe2 { , though it doesn't pose Black any problems after }15...Ne5 { . } )
15. Ne5
16. Qe2
16. Rd8
17. Be3( { Better is }17.f4 { , but obviously Black has phenomenal compensation after }17...Nd3+ { . } )
17. Bc5
18. Bxc5
18. Qxc5( { White is in deep trouble. Following }19.Ba2 Rd3! 20.Kf1 Rf8 21.Nd1 Bh5! { , White was already forced to resign, as Black is crashing through }{ on  f3 . } )
