10. Nxg6
10. hxg6( { Play can now  transpose  to  9.Qe2  after }11.Qe2 Nbd7 { . }{ The difference with  9.Qe2  lies in the fact that White hasn't yet committed the queen to  e2 , and our knight is still on  b8 . There are advantages to this for both sides. The queen can sometimes be better placed on  b3  or  c2 , and our knight, after ... c6 - c5 , can sometimes be better placed on  b8 , from where it can choose between  a6 ,  c6 , and  d7 . } )
11. Qb3{ The most direct approach, recently used by Le Quang Liem against Jorden van Foreest. }
11. Qe7{ The most natural square, defending both the bishop and  b7 -pawn. That last detail can be important after a future ... c6 - c5 . Often White responds to this move with  Nc3 - a2 , which can now be answered with ... Bb4 - a5  since  b7  isn't hanging. }( 11...Qb6!? { is possible as well, with the important point that }12.Rd1 c5 13.Na2 { can be met with }13...Nc6 14.Nxb4 Na5! { and Black seems to be alright. The line continues }15.Qd3 cxb4 ( 15...Nxc4!? 16.Qxc4 Qxb4 17.Qxb4 cxb4 { is a slightly worse endgame, though also not more than that. } )16.Ba2 { , trying to keep the bishop pair, }16...b3 17.Bb1 e5! { and Black had an active game in Hoeppenstein-Flatz, correspondence 2016. Note that }18.dxe5 Rfd8 19.Qe2 Rxd1+ 20.Qxd1 Rd8 { is already quite tricky. Of course, this line isn't forced, and White has solid alternatives such as   }12.Bd2 { . } )
12. Rd1{ I feel  11.Qb3  is more in accordance with active play, and this move feels slow. }
12. Rd8{ We are preparing the ... c6 - c5  break. }
13. Bd2( 13.a5 c5! { is also OK for Black, and }14.dxc5 Nc6! { perhaps already more than OK! } )
13. c5
14. dxc5
14. Nc6{ We have comfortably equalized. The key to this position is the pawn on  a4 . If it were on  a2 , White would have a very pleasant advantage after, say,  15.Be2 , because of the bishop pair. As it is, Black has some very nice squares on the queenside, and that changes the entire evaluation. }
