7. Bb4{ Allowing us to castle on the next move. On  b4  the bishop is better placed as it, indirectly, fights for the  e4 -square by attacking the knight on  c3 . }( { Less good is }7...Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Qe2 { , when it's easier for White to }{ get  e3 - e4  in. } )
8. O-O
8. O-O( { I prefer this move over }8...Nbd7 { , which is often used to provoke White into sacrificing a pawn. The problem is that this pawn sacrifice is actually very strong. }9.Qe2 Bg6 10.e4! Bxc3 { (Better is }10...O-O { , which transposes to one of the main lines.)   }11.bxc3 Nxe4 12.Ba3 { and White has tremendous compensation, as Black's king is stuck in the center. } )
9. Nh4( { This line is of course closely related to   }6.Nh4 { , but in that variation, after }6...e6 7.Nxf5 exf5 8.e3 { , we choose to develop the bishop }{ to  d6  with }8...Bd6 { . } )( { Here, the bishop is already on  b4 , so we don't play }9...Nbd7 { , which takes us out of book after }10.Nxf5 exf5 { . Instead, we play  9...Bg6 , which leads to structures closely related to the main line with   }9.Qe2 Bg6 10.Ne5 Nbd7 11.Nxg6 hxg6 { . } )
9. Bg6
10. Nxg6
10. hxg6( { Play can now  transpose  to  9.Qe2  after }11.Qe2 Nbd7 { . }{ The difference with  9.Qe2  lies in the fact that White hasn't yet committed the queen to  e2 , and our knight is still on  b8 . There are advantages to this for both sides. The queen can sometimes be better placed on  b3  or  c2 , and our knight, after ... c6 - c5 , can sometimes be better placed on  b8 , from where it can choose between  a6 ,  c6 , and  d7 . } )
11. Qc2{ This is the most obvious response. White aims to get an improved version of the aforementioned main line. The queen on  c2  does a good job preventing ... e6 - e5  since the pawn on  g6  will be hanging after that push. The downside is that the queen is vulnerable on the c-file if we go for that other push: ... c6 - c5 . }
11. Nbd7( 11...c5 { doesn't quite work here after }12.d5! { , and now both }12...Bxc3 13.dxe6 Bb4 14.exf7+ { and   }12...exd5 13.Nxd5! Nxd5 14.Rd1 { are better for White. } )
12. Rd1
12. Qe7{ The most natural square for the queen, from where it helps Black prepare a break in the center and connects the rooks. }( { Note that a move like }12...a5 { shows why it's important to move the queen from the d-file when a rook }{ appears on  d1 . Now }13.e4 { can't be met }{ with ... e6 - e5 , which is the case when the queen is on  e7 . } )
13. a5{ Preventing ... a7 - a5 . }( { Smyslov-Unzicker, Graz 1984, continued with }13.Bd2 { , after which }13...a5 { , }{ preparing to centralize the rooks to  d8  and  c8 , and, eventually push the c- or e-pawn, }{ gives Black an easy game. It's hard to come up with a plan for White. }14.e4 { , for instance, isn't effective after }14...e5 15.d5 Nb6 { . } )
13. c5( { Immediately hitting White in the center. Of course, }13...e5 14.Qxg6! { still isn't possible, but   }13...Rac8 { is okay as well, simply awaiting developments. Black's position is rock solid and this is not the type of position where you can lose in 5 moves because of forgotten home analysis. } )
14. d5
14. exd5
15. Nxd5
15. Nxd5
16. Bxd5{ This position would be better for White, if given a few extra moves. As it is, White lacks some development to be able to claim an advantage. }
16. Nf6
17. Bf3
17. Rad8{ Challenging White's supremacy on the d-file. }
18. Bd2( { In a way, an admission that White has no advantage. It is hard to play something else though, and a sample is }18.b3 Rxd1+ 19.Qxd1 Rd8 20.Qc2 Ne4!? { , when Black is very active. } )
18. Bxd2
19. Rxd2
19. Rxd2
20. Qxd2
20. b5( { The game is approximately even. After, for instance, }21.axb6 axb6 22.Rd1 g5 { , Black has decent counterplay. Note that starting with   }20...Rd8 { , or }20...g5!? { is possible as well. } )
