[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) Dutch Variation 6.e3"]
[Black "Dutch Variation 6.e3 − 9.Qe2 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. a4( { Isolating the pawn on  c4  is the best way to go. By preventing ... b7 - b5 , White prepares to regain the  c4 -pawn. As we will see, the alternatives }5.e4 b5 { ,   }5.e3 b5 6.a4 b4 { , and   }5.g3 b5 { leave Black in excellent shape. } )
5. Bf5{ Not just developing the bishop but also preventing  e2 - e4 . Our development scheme is quite clear: in random order, we will play ... e7 - e6 , ... Bf8 - b4 , ... O-O , and ... Nb8 - d7 . Once we achieve that, we can start looking for central breaks connected to ... c6 - c5  and ... e6 - e5 . }
6. e3( { The so-called Dutch Variation. It is named that way because of the contributions of Max Euwe in this line, in particular in his 1937 match against Alexander Alekhine where he employed the variation five times. Contrary to the other main line, }6.Ne5 { , this move leads to quieter, more strategic play. } )
6. e6
7. Bxc4
7. Bb4{ Allowing us to castle on the next move. On  b4  the bishop is better placed as it, indirectly, fights for the  e4 -square by attacking the knight on  c3 . }( { Less good is }7...Be7 8.O-O O-O 9.Qe2 { , when it's easier for White to }{ get  e3 - e4  in. } )
8. O-O
8. O-O( { I prefer this move over }8...Nbd7 { , which is often used to provoke White into sacrificing a pawn. The problem is that this pawn sacrifice is actually very strong. }9.Qe2 Bg6 10.e4! Bxc3 { (Better is }10...O-O { , which transposes to one of the main lines.)   }11.bxc3 Nxe4 12.Ba3 { and White has tremendous compensation, as Black's king is stuck in the center. } )
9. Qe2
9. Bg6{ This move has taken center stage again, after going through a bit of a crisis at the start of this millennium. A few positions in this variation have recently received a reappraisal, making the line alive and kicking again. The main point is to prevent White from pushing  e3 - e4 . }
10. Ne5( { The only downside to our previous move is that White can go after our bishop. Note that the reason White can't play }10.e4 { is }10...Bxc3 11.bxc3 Nxe4 { , when we are a pawn up. } )
10. Nbd7
11. Nxg6
11. hxg6
12. Rd1{ The critical position, seen in dozens of high-level outings. Black's position is rock solid and without any weaknesses. White's last move prevents any ... c6 - c5  and ... e6 - e5  breaks and prepares  e3 - e4 . We start by taking action against that. }
12. Qe7( { Not the most common move in the position, but to my mind, the easiest. In our alternative line }12...Qa5 { , the variations are a bit more complicated while here everything is clear. A third queen move, }12...Qc7 { , has been seen as well but is slightly less convenient. } )
13. f4{ Played once by MVL, with the idea to stop ... e6 - e5  indefinitely. While that certainly works with this move, the other break, ... c6 - c5 , will gain in force now. }
13. Rfd8
14. e4
14. c5{ Black is already better. We will continue the line a bit longer cause the following moves are forced. }
15. e5
15. cxd4
16. exf6
16. Qc5{ The point −  c3  is still hanging, and ... d4 - d3  becomes a threat. }
17. Ne4
17. d3+
18. Nxc5
18. dxe2
19. Bxe2
19. Bxc5+{ And with ... Nd7xf6  coming next, Black is a solid pawn up. }
