14. Nb6{ Hitting the bishop on  c4  and preparing the capture on  d5 . }( { A scenario to avoid is }14...cxd5 15.Nxd5 Nxd5 16.Bxd5 { , }{ when the bishop on  d5  is a monster, }{ and }16...Nf6 17.Bg5 { doesn't help much. } )
15. Bb3
15. cxd5{ Now that we have two pieces aimed at  d5 , the time is right to take. }
16. a5{ This looks strong − if the knight moves, then White manages to establish a piece on  d5 . }
16. d4{ The key move. }
17. axb6
17. dxc3
18. bxc3
18. Bc5( 18...Bxc3 19.Rxa7 Rad8 { is fine as well, and the way the cool correspondence guys do it! } )
19. Rxa7
19. Rxa7
20. bxa7
20. Bxa7{ The game is approximately equal. }
