13. Qxa4( { We should grab the pawn, as }13...Be7 14.Bd2 Qh5 15.b4 { , which was seen in Yu Yangyi-Bu Xiangzhi, Danzhou Rapid 2021, gives White an easy game and a nice advantage. } )
14. e4
14. e5{ A major update, preventing  e4 - e5  in the most primitive way possible! }( { A look in the database will reveal that }14...Qa5 { is more or less universally played, but }15.e5 Nd5 16.h4 { feels incredibly dangerous. }{ White wants to play  h4 - h5  and start a quick attack on the king. Engines also have a preference for White here. } )
15. dxe5{ The most obvious move. After we recapture, White will try to use the momentum by attacking our knight on  e5 . }
15. Nxe5
16. Bf4
16. Nxc4( { Even }16...Bd6!? { works, }{ as the bishop on  c4  is now hanging as well, and }17.b3 Qa3 { narrowly holds on to the bishop }{ on  d6 . There is no need for such desperation though, and at the least, White can repeat moves with }18.Bc1 Qc5 19.Be3 { . } )
17. Qxc4
17. Rfd8( { Using White's back-rank issues. Previously }17...c5 { was seen in practice, but }18.b3 Qc6 19.e5 { gives White good chances to fight for an advantage. } )
18. Bd6{ Moving the rook from  d1  would give Black a much better version of the previous note after ... c6 - c5 . }
18. a5{ Contrary to how it looks, this move does not lose a piece! }
19. Nxb4
19. Rxd6{ Using the back rank to regain the piece. }
20. Rdc1
20. Qb5
21. Qxb5
21. cxb5{ Unfortunately, at the end of the line White gets away with a draw in the upcoming rook endgame. That's the drawing margin of chess in action! }
22. e5
22. Rdd8
23. exf6
23. axb4{ We are a pawn up, but it isn't exactly the prettiest of pawns − meaning it's equal. }
