13. Nd5{ The last few moves were all forced, and also the next few moves have a rather forcing character. }
14. Ba3( 14.Rb1 b6 15.Ba3 Re8 { transposes. } )
14. Re8
15. Rab1
15. b6( { We'd rather not weaken our queenside, but }15...Qc7 16.Ng5! { is tricky since }16...f5 17.e4! { is undesirable, and   }16...Nf6 17.e4 h6 18.e5! { is tricky as well. } )
16. Rfc1( { The critical position. Alekhine played }16...a5 { here, but was under pressure after }17.Ne5 Nb4 18.Bxb4 { (White has other promising options as well) }18...axb4 { .    Later, attention shifted to }17...Qc7 { , which Euwe has indicated as a stronger continuation. Here too practice has shown }18.Qb3 { gives White fine compensation for the pawn in the form of strong queenside pressure. The new move }18.Qe4!? { also deserves attention. That's why these days  16...a5  has been largely abandoned. } )
16. Nf6{ Threatening ... e6 - e5 . }
17. Ne5( { Other moves don't promise White anything. For instance, }17.Qb3 Qc7 18.Ne5 Nfd7! { , showing another good reason for retreating the knight }{ from  d5  to  f6 . }19.Nc4 c5 { and Black is in fine shape. } )
17. Qd5( { Threatening ... c6 - c5 . }17...Nfd7 { is the type of tricky move that can easily backfire. Sure, }18.Nxc6 Nxc6 19.Rxc6 Ne5! { is a nice trick, but   }18.Nc4 { looks very awkward for Black. } )
18. Qc3( { Less good is }18.Qc4 c5! { , }{ when the knight is not protected on  e5  so that }19.dxc5 { isn't possible. Exchanging queens first with }19.Qxd5 exd5! { also doesn't lead to the desired result since now }{ the  e8 -rook is looking at the knight. } )
18. Ne4( 18...Rc8 { is an interesting novelty, simply giving support }{ to the  c6 -pawn, which should make a future ... c6 - c5  easier to realize. } )
19. Qb2
19. f6
20. Nc4
20. Rd8( { The stem game, Keres-Petrovs, Tallinn 1978, continued }20...Ng5 { , but that gives White some interesting options. One is }21.Nd6 Rd8 22.a5!? { with the idea that }22...Rxd6 23.Bxd6 Qxd6 24.axb6 axb6 25.Qxb6 { forces Black to give up the c- and the e-pawns. After }25...Nd7 26.Rxc6 Nxb6 27.Rxd6 Nd5 28.h4 Ne4 29.Rxe6 Ndc3 30.Rb2 { , the endgame may be tenable for Black, but tricky nonetheless. } )( { With }20...Rd8 { we first secure }{ the  d6 –square, before retreating the knight. } )
21. f3
21. Ng5{ The knight will find a good spot on  f7 . Our position is rock solid. }
