10. g4{ I hear you think... is this the latest engine twist in this position? Not at all! The rematch between title holder Max Euwe and Alexander Alekhine in 1937 was decided after 25 games, when Alekhine was leading with a +6 score, with 5 games to go. Nevertheless, the players continued with 5 exhibition games, which would be unthinkable in our time.    In game 1 of these exhibition games, Alekhine uncorked this bold move. It must not have come as a complete surprise to Euwe, as Alekhine had already faced this move earlier in the year, against Friedrich Sämisch. Despite having been played just 7 times, it's definitely a very critical test of the  9...Ne4  system. }
10. Bg6
11. Ne5
11. Nxc3( { Presumably caught by surprise, Jon Ludvig Hammer once played }11...Nd6 { against Gabriel Sargissian in Wijk aan Zee 2011, but this move doesn't meet the demands of the position. After }12.Ba2 Nd7 13.Nxg6 hxg6 14.e4 { , White had a huge initiative. I can imagine the Norwegian trying to jump out of his opponent's preparation though. }{ Taking on  c3  unprepared does look very scary indeed! } )
12. bxc3
12. Bxc3
13. Ra3{ An interesting new idea, deviating from the aforementioned Alekhine-Euwe game. White wants to play  e3 - e4  in the foreseeable future and swing the rook over to the kingside. }
13. Bb4
14. Rb3
14. a5
15. e4
15. b5( 15...Qxd4!? 16.Bb2 Qxe4 17.Re3 { may be possible after }17...Qf4 { or }17...Qc2 { , but I am trying to get a better version of this. }{ I like to open up the queenside first and lure the  c4 -bishop to a less favorable spot. } )
16. axb5
16. cxb5
17. Bxb5
17. Qxd4{ Going for it, under slightly better circumstances. }
18. Bb2
18. Qxe4
19. Re3
19. Qc2{ With the queens off, there isn't much to fear anymore. }
20. h4
20. Qxe2
21. Rxe2
21. f6{ We are two pawns up but will have to give one back. The threat of  h4 - h5  had to be met. }
22. Nxg6
22. hxg6
23. Rxe6
23. Rd8{ We are ready to push ... a5 - a4 - a3 , and the bishop can always cover the kingside with ... Bb4 - f8  if need be. }
