10. Ne5{ Out of 539 games I found in the database, only 17 times this move was used. I still consider it the main line though, as it's no doubt the move that poses Black the most questions. The immediate threat is  g2 - g4 , but moving the knight away from  f3  has the additional advantage that the center can now be put in motion, with a future  f2 - f3  followed by  e3 - e4 . }( { Note that }10...Nxc3? 11.bxc3 Bxc3 12.Ra3! Bb4 13.Rb3 a5 14.e4 Bg6 15.h4! { is extremely dangerous for Black, as I was able to demonstrate myself against Quinten Durcamon in Maastricht 2014. } )( { Playing }10...Bxc3 { isn't much of an improvement, as }11.bxc3 Nxc3 12.Qb2! { leaves  b7  hanging. } )
10. Nd7{ This is the way to go. We ignore the possibility of taking on  c3  and simply offer an exchange of knights. }
11. Nxd7
11. Qxd7{ Now we are threatening to take on  c3 , hence White's next move. }
12. Na2
12. Be7( 12...Ba5 { has been played as well, but after }13.f3 Nd6 14.Bb3 Bg6 15.Rd1 { , we prefer to have this bishop }{ on  e7 . More on that later! } )
13. f3
13. Nd6( 13...Nf6?! 14.e4 Bg6 15.Be3 { was fantastic for White in Topalov-Bu Xiangzhi. }{ The knight belongs to  d6  since we need to have ... f7 - f5  as a resource to fight against White's center. As it is, both the bishop on  g6  and the knight on  f6  are in a pitiful state. } )
14. Bb3
14. Bg6
15. e4{ I failed to understand the position when first confronted with it in my game against Evgeny Bareev. This push looks logical, but Black is in fact fully prepared for it. }
15. Kh8{ Preparing the ... f7 - f5  push. }
16. Be3
16. f5
17. e5
17. Ne8{ Rerouting the knight to  d5  via  c7 . Black has comfortably equalized and the game l'Ami-Bareev, Amsterdam 2008, was soon agreed draw. }
