6. e6{ I remember this move came as a bit of a surprise to me when I first saw it many years ago. We give up the bishop and our structure gets fractured in the process! Things are a bit more subtle than that though as we will see. }( { As a surprise weapon, the move }6...Bg6!? { is not too bad. After }7.Nxg6 hxg6 { , Black has a solid structure and the likes of Bareev and Gelfand have proven the validity of this position. It's important that the complications that arise following }8.e4 e5! { are OK for Black. } )
7. Nxf5
7. exf5
8. e3{ This is a good moment to take stock and think about what this position is about. White is about to take back on  c4  and there is not much we can do about that. Instead, we should think about where our pieces belong.    Our ideal scenario is to have a setup where we move our  f8 -bishop to  d6 , the  b8 -knight to  d5 , castle kingside, and bring our rooks to  d8  and  e8  and our queen, let's say, on  e6 . Once we have that, we can throw in moves like ... h7 - h5 - h4  and start harassing White's king that is likely to castle on that wing.    Note that we don't mind having doubled f-pawns. In fact, it gives us a half-open e-file and good control over the  e4 -square. On top of that, we may be able to throw in ... f5 - f4  sometimes to cause problems for White's pawn structure. }
8. Bd6( { Historically, this is not the most popular move, but I am not sure that is justified. We already said the bishop is well placed on  d6 , and therefore, I prefer to go there immediately rather than the most played move in the position, which is }8...Bb4 { . } )
9. Bxc4
9. O-O
10. O-O{ Obviously a very natural move, but it may not be very critical. The most dangerous plan to fight for an advantage is to go for the  g2 - g4  break, and castling kingside certainly doesn't help with that plan. }
10. Nbd7( 10...Na6!? { may be possible as well, to aim for }{ the  b4 -square. There is no need to fear }11.Bxa6 bxa6 { , }{ as the b-file will give us great play. Here White would love to have the pawn back on  a2  so that the b-pawn can be supported after a subsequent  b2 - b3 . As it is, the b-pawn is an annoying weakness. } )
11. f3
11. Rc8{ Preparing to play ... c6 - c5  more or less regardless of what White plays next. }( { We don't push }11...c5 { immediately since after }12.Nb5 { , we would like to be able to retreat }{ to  b8 , staying on the strong  h2 - b8  diagonal. That's why we first move the rook to  c8 , so as not to incarcerate it there. } )( { A small trap is }11...Qc7 12.g3 Bxg3?! { and now, instead of taking the piece and agreeing to a draw, White has }13.Qc2! Bd6 14.Qxf5 { , when }14...Bxh2+ 15.Kh1 { gives great compensation for the pawn. } )
12. e4( { We are all set for this central break. After a move like }12.Qd3 { , we can just ignore the threat }{ to  f5  and play }12...c5 { , though }12...g6 { is fine as well, intending to meet }13.e4 { with }13...c5!  )
12. c5( { White already has to be careful, as }13.e5 cxd4! { works for us, and   }13.d5 { is not desirable either, as after }13...fxe4 14.fxe4 { , Black gets a great blockade on the dark squares. } )
