[White "16) Slav − 5th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "Slav 5.e3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. e3{ The Alekhine Variation. Alexander Alekhine used it, amongst other games, in game 23 of his 1935 World Championship match against Max Euwe. }
5. b5
6. a4
6. b4{ Back in 1920, when Alekhine first employed this variation, it was very unclear to the masters of those times how to assess the inclusion of the moves  a2 - a4  and ... b5 - b4 .    It was thought that it may well favor White, and indeed if White manages to regain the pawn on  c4  and reroute the attacked  c3 -knight, the squares on the queenside may well be used to White's advantage.    For that though, White needs time, and the appreciation and understanding of time in chess has improved greatly over the past 100 years. To a modern grandmaster, it is quite obvious that this line doesn't promise White anything. }
7. Nb1( { Contrary to }7.Na2 { , this move doesn't guarantee that White wins back the pawn. }{ Indeed, Alekhine himself considered this move imprecise for this very reason, as he indicated in the notes to his game (a model game!) against Tarrasch, in Hastings 1922. The engine is not convinced, and true, from  b1  it is much easier for White to get the knight back into the game than via  a2 . } )
7. Ba6
8. Ne5
8. e6( { Here Alekhine went wrong though, considering }8...Qd5 { to be best, and concluding that Black is better after }9.f3 c5 { . That is indeed so, but White has the stronger }9.Nd2 { , when }9...c3 10.bxc3 bxc3 { ( }10...Bxf1 11.Kxf1 bxc3 12.Nb1 { transposes)   }11.Nb1 Bxf1 12.Kxf1 { allows White to }{ recapture on  c3  next move, with a slightly better game. } )( 8...e6 { is much better, simply continuing development while White still needs to regain the pawn. } )
9. Nxc4( { Artificial, but }9.Bxc4 { loses a pawn after }9...Bxc4 10.Nxc4 Qd5 { , and although }11.Nbd2 Qxg2 12.Qf3 Qxf3 13.Nxf3 { may not even be that bad for White, we obviously can't complain here with an extra pawn. } )
9. Be7
10. Nbd2
10. O-O{ Having finished development, we are now ready to start preparing the ... c6 - c5  break. Black is already for choice, as White still needs some moves to develop. }
