4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. e3{ The Alekhine Variation. Alexander Alekhine used it, amongst other games, in game 23 of his 1935 World Championship match against Max Euwe. }
5. b5
6. a4
6. b4{ Back in 1920, when Alekhine first employed this variation, it was very unclear to the masters of those times how to assess the inclusion of the moves  a2 - a4  and ... b5 - b4 .    It was thought that it may well favor White, and indeed if White manages to regain the pawn on  c4  and reroute the attacked  c3 -knight, the squares on the queenside may well be used to White's advantage.    For that though, White needs time, and the appreciation and understanding of time in chess has improved greatly over the past 100 years. To a modern grandmaster, it is quite obvious that this line doesn't promise White anything. }
7. Ne2{ A modern twist on this variation. It makes sense to reroute the knight to the kingside, given that on  a2 / b1 , it is often out of the game for a prolonged period of time. }
7. a5{ White's knights can jump anywhere,  e5 ,  f4 ,  g3 , and we will react accordingly. In the meantime, we make a useful move on the queenside. }
8. Ng3
8. Ba6{ Hanging on to the pawn. }
9. Ne5
9. Qd5( { It's very hard to up the pressure on the c-pawn for White. }10.Bd2 { , }{ preparing  Ra1 - c1 , }{ is too slow because of }10...Nbd7! { , }{ removing the knight from  e5 . } )( 10.Qc2 b3! { also doesn't quite work, as }11.Qc3 e6 { threatening ... Bf8 - b4  is annoying. } )
10. Be2( { In order to meet }10...Nbd7 { with }11.Bf3 { , }{ winning  c6 . } )
10. Qxg2{ Not just grabbing a pawn but also making it hard for White to get the king out of the center. }
11. Bf3
11. Qh3
12. Nxc6
12. e6
13. Nxa5
13. Ra7{ Black is clearly better. There is no harmony in White's position, while we simply intend to play ... Bf8 - e7  and ... O-O . }
