13. c5( { The game saw }13...Re8 { , }{ which is logical, as Black protects the bishop on  e7 , thereby freeing the queen on  d8 , yet it gave White the time for }14.Nc1 { , when }14...Qb6 15.Nb3 h6 16.Be3 { gave White a clear advantage. The pawn on  e4  can't be captured because of  d4 - d5 . } )( 13...c5! { is a typical modern concrete solution, which works wonders. } )
14. dxc5
14. Qc7( { The point! Less good is }14...Nxe4 15.Rxd7 Qxd7 16.Bb5 Qc7 17.Bxe7 Qxe7 18.c6 { , which gives White some advantage following }18...Nd6 19.cxb7 Qxb7 20.Bd3 { . The two pieces should outweigh the rook and pawn. } )
15. c6
15. Bxc6
16. Rxd7
16. Qxd7( { This transposes to the  15.Rxd7 move order , but gives the extra option of }16...Bxd7 17.e5 Bxa4 18.exf6 Bxf6 19.Bxf6 gxf6 { , where the engines like Black. } )
