1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. e3{ The Alekhine Variation. Alexander Alekhine used it, amongst other games, in game 23 of his 1935 World Championship match against Max Euwe. }
5. b5
6. a4
6. b4{ Back in 1920, when Alekhine first employed this variation, it was very unclear to the masters of those times how to assess the inclusion of the moves  a2 - a4  and ... b5 - b4 .    It was thought that it may well favor White, and indeed if White manages to regain the pawn on  c4  and reroute the attacked  c3 -knight, the squares on the queenside may well be used to White's advantage.    For that though, White needs time, and the appreciation and understanding of time in chess has improved greatly over the past 100 years. To a modern grandmaster, it is quite obvious that this line doesn't promise White anything. }
7. Na2{ Attacking both  b4  and  c4 . We are ready to give back the  c4 -pawn, making sure the knight on  a2  will take a while to get back in the game. }
7. e6
8. Bxc4
8. Bb7{ A fairly normal Meran type of position has arisen, where White's knight on  a2  is somewhat misplaced. }( { The text move is the cleanest way to proceed since }8...Nbd7 { instead hands White the additional option of }9.a5 { , when obviously }9...Bb7 { would be met by the unpleasant }10.a6 { . Of course, we can take the pawn on  a5 , but after   }9...Qxa5 10.Bd2 { , }{ threatening  Na2xb4 , }10...Qb6 11.Qa4 { , Black doesn't have access to }11...a5 { because of the hanging rook on  a8 . If we follow the same variation but with the bishop on  b7  instead, }{   }11...a5 { would already yield a significant advantage for us. } )
9. O-O
9. Nbd7
10. Qe2
10. Be7
11. Rd1
11. O-O( { A worthy alternative is to postpone castling for now and start with }11...a5!? { , with the idea to meet }12.e4 { with }12...Nb6 13.Bb3 Ba6!? { , creating some discomfort for White. Given a few moves }{ like ... O-O , ... Nf6 - d7 , and ... c6 - c5 , Black may be doing very well. } )
12. e4( { Again, the plan }12.Bd2 a5 13.Nc1 { is possible but doesn't quite equalize. We play }13...c5!? 14.Nb3 Qb6 { , with a small edge. }{ Our  b7 -bishop does a great job restricting White. } )
12. a5( { It is interesting for the evolution of this line though, to hear what Alekhine has to say about this position. Through a transposition, we have returned back into his game with Tarrasch.    Alekhine points out 'the  a5 -pawn could become weak, but not playing }12...a5 { would run }{ into  Na2 - c1 - b3  and  a4 - a5 - a6 .' For modern standards, calling the pawn on  a5  a potential weakness is a bit abstract, and so far Tarrasch played very well. It is only after Alekhine's next move that he falters. } )
13. Bg5
13. c5( { The game saw }13...Re8 { , }{ which is logical, as Black protects the bishop on  e7 , thereby freeing the queen on  d8 , yet it gave White the time for }14.Nc1 { , when }14...Qb6 15.Nb3 h6 16.Be3 { gave White a clear advantage. The pawn on  e4  can't be captured because of  d4 - d5 . } )( 13...c5! { is a typical modern concrete solution, which works wonders. } )
14. dxc5
14. Qc7( { The point! Less good is }14...Nxe4 15.Rxd7 Qxd7 16.Bb5 Qc7 17.Bxe7 Qxe7 18.c6 { , which gives White some advantage following }18...Nd6 19.cxb7 Qxb7 20.Bd3 { . The two pieces should outweigh the rook and pawn. } )
15. Rxd7{ If not for this move, Black just recaptures a pawn, either on  e4  or  c5 , with an otherwise excellent position. }
15. Qxd7
16. c6
16. Bxc6( { The alternative }16...Qxc6 { seems attractive as well since }17.e5 Nh5!? 18.Bxe7 Nf4 19.Qc2 Rfc8 20.b3 Nxg2 { looks decisive. Unfortunately though, White has }21.Nd4! { forcing the queen off the long diagonal, with an unclear game. Perhaps   }20...Ba6 { is better, when I’d still take Black. } )
17. Ne5
17. Qc7
18. Nxc6
18. Qxc6
19. e5{ This looks troublesome at first, aren't we losing material? }
19. Nd5
20. Bxd5
20. exd5
21. Bxe7{ It turns out we are. But White is lacking coordination, and that gives us just enough time to organize counterplay. }
21. Rfe8
22. Bg5
22. h6
23. Bd2
23. Qxa4{ Black is slightly better, as White's issues on the queenside are far from solved. The knight on  a2  and rook on  a1  are in a particularly peculiar spot. }
