[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) Slav 5.g3"]
[Black "Slav 5.g3 − 7.O-O #2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. g3{ The only  g3 -system in which we take the pawn on  c4 . We couldn't help it though, as White pushed the pawn on  g3  only after we took the pawn!    Against this system, which has gained some popularity over the years, play is closely related to the Catalan Variation, but the fact that White has committed to an early  Nb1 - c3  should give us a good version. I propose an entirely new setup − somewhat inspired by lines we have seen earlier. }
5. b5
6. Bg2
6. e6
7. O-O( { The other big move, which is likely to transpose to the }7.Ne5 { variation. } )
7. a5
8. Bg5{ White has finished development with this move and yet is not better! Chess is not fair sometimes. The key of course is that the position is relatively closed, and we are a pawn up for now. }
8. h6( { Even the calm }8...a4!? { might work, as the complications after }9.b3 Qa5! 10.Qc2 axb3 11.axb3 Qxa1 12.Rxa1 Rxa1+ 13.Bf1 b4 14.Bxf6 gxf6 15.Ne4 c3! 16.Nxf6+ Kd8 { don't seem that bad for Black. } )( { Last but not least, the normal developing move }8...Nbd7 { is fine as well. } )
9. Bxf6
9. gxf6( { Not }9...Qxf6 10.a4! b4 11.Ne4 { followed by  Nf3 - e5 , and now White's lead in development will start telling. } )
10. a4{ Trying to soften Black's grip on the queenside. }
10. b4
11. Ne4
11. Ba6
12. Ned2
12. Nd7
13. Qc2
13. Nb6( { Holding on to the pawn with all our might! A sample line is }14.Rfd1 Bg7 15.Bf1 O-O 16.e4 { , intending to win back }{ the  c4 -pawn. Now }16...f5! 17.exf5 Qd5! { gives Black an excellent game. } )
