[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. g3{ The only  g3 -system in which we take the pawn on  c4 . We couldn't help it though, as White pushed the pawn on  g3  only after we took the pawn!    Against this system, which has gained some popularity over the years, play is closely related to the Catalan Variation, but the fact that White has committed to an early  Nb1 - c3  should give us a good version. I propose an entirely new setup − somewhat inspired by lines we have seen earlier. }
5. b5
6. Bg2
6. e6
7. Ne5
7. Qb6{ Not at all the most popular move in the position, but we play it with a new idea in mind. }
8. O-O
8. a5( { Played only once in a 2017 correspondence game. Just as in   }5.e4 b5 6.Be2 { , we try to push the pawn }{ to  a4  to fix the queenside in a favorable way. Engines don't disapprove! } )
9. b3( { The critical test. Taking on  b3  is dangerous, as }9...cxb3 10.Qxb3! { gives White dangerous compensation. For instance }10...Bb7 11.Bf4 Be7 12.Nc4! { and White is already winning, as }12...Qxd4 13.Nxb5! { is crushing. } )
9. Bb4{ That's why instead of taking on  b3 , we attack the vulnerable knight on  c3 . }
10. Ne4
10. Nxe4
11. Bxe4
11. cxb3( { It is tempting to play }11...Bc3 { , but }12.Be3!? Bxa1 13.Qxa1 { is quite dangerous given our lack of development. } )
12. Qd3( { Given what we have seen after }12.axb3 { , this makes sense! White ignores the b-pawn for now and focuses on the kingside. } )
12. bxa2{ When in doubt, grab material! On a serious note, taking on  a2  provides Black with a massive long-term potential with two passed pawns on the a- and b-files. }( 12...f6 13.Bg6+ Kf8 14.Nf7 Rg8 { may work, but it's rather tricky. Believe it or not, the following lines seem to be forced. }15.Bxh7 Kxf7 16.Qg6+ Kf8 17.Bxg8 Kxg8 18.Qe8+ Kh7 19.Qxc8 Bc3 20.Be3 Bxa1 21.Rxa1 bxa2 22.d5 c5 23.Rxa2 { and White still keeps some initiative in a position that is otherwise, of course, very hard to evaluate. It's important to note that }23...exd5? 24.Qf5+ { loses on the spot. } )
13. Rxa2
13. f5( { In order to prepare our king for castling. I found it remarkable how hard the position is after }13...Bb7 14.Rc2! { For instance, }14...Be7 15.Rc5!? { with very interesting compensation, as }15...Bxc5 16.dxc5 Qxc5 17.Rd1 Qe7 18.h4! { (preparing  Bc1 - g5 ) }18...h6 19.Nxf7! Kxf7 20.Bg6+ Kg8 21.Qd8+ Qf8 22.Qc7 Na6 23.Qxb7 Nc5 24.Qxc6 { is already crushing. } )
14. Bg2
14. O-O{ White has some compensation, but two pawns are a lot. We will play ... Bb7  next and will be eyeing a well-timed ... c6 - c5  break. }
