4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. e4{ The Geller Gambit is named after Efim Petrovich Geller, who started using it with great success in the late '40s and early '50s. His successes inspired many top players to pick up the line, including various World Champions. }
5. b5
6. e5{ This is how Geller used to play, but fast-forward to 2023 it has lost most of its appeal. }( 6.a4 { is premature because of }6...b4 { followed by ... Nf6xe4 . } )
6. Nd5
7. a4
7. e6( { We should make sure not to fall for }7...a6 8.axb5 Nxc3 9.bxc3 cxb5 10.Ng5! { , when Black is in dire }{ straits.  Qd1 - f3  is a huge threat, and }10...Ra7 11.e6! Bxe6 12.Nxe6 fxe6 13.Qh5+ g6 14.Qe5 { is no fun either. } )( { Faced with a fresh position, Smyslov played }7...Be6 { against Tolush, in 1947. Here the 7th World Champion had no doubt wanted to meet }8.Ng5 { with }8...Nxc3 9.bxc3 Bd5 { , but after }10.e6! fxe6 { (or }10...Bxe6 11.Nxe6 fxe6 12.axb5 cxb5 13.Qh5+! { )   }11.Be2 { , Black is, somewhat surprisingly, completely busted. }{ The next moves are  O-O ,  Be2 - g4 , and  Rf1 - e1 . } )
8. axb5{ The old main line, but one that has not been able to stand the test of time. }
8. Nxc3
9. bxc3
9. cxb5
10. Ng5( { We can immediately appreciate the difference with the move   }7...a6 { , which we discussed earlier. }{ In this position, the threat of  Qd1 - f3  is easily parried. } )
10. Bb7
11. Qg4( { Usually, White starts with }11.Qh5 { in order to provoke }11...g6 { before retreating to this square. } )
11. h6{ Effectively refuting White's play. }
12. Ne4( 12.Nxe6 fxe6 13.Qxe6+ Qe7 { can't really bother us. } )
12. Qd5{ Provoking White's next move, which makes it much harder to get the  f1 -bishop into the game. }
13. f3
13. Nd7( { It is not an exaggeration to say that Black is close to winning here. We can think of pushing our queenside forward and don't need to fear }14.Ba3 { since }14...Bxa3 15.Rxa3 O-O 16.Nf6+ Nxf6 17.exf6 g6 { doesn't lead anywhere for White. } )
