7. e6( { We should make sure not to fall for }7...a6 8.axb5 Nxc3 9.bxc3 cxb5 10.Ng5! { , when Black is in dire }{ straits.  Qd1 - f3  is a huge threat, and }10...Ra7 11.e6! Bxe6 12.Nxe6 fxe6 13.Qh5+ g6 14.Qe5 { is no fun either. } )( { Faced with a fresh position, Smyslov played }7...Be6 { against Tolush, in 1947. Here the 7th World Champion had no doubt wanted to meet }8.Ng5 { with }8...Nxc3 9.bxc3 Bd5 { , but after }10.e6! fxe6 { (or }10...Bxe6 11.Nxe6 fxe6 12.axb5 cxb5 13.Qh5+! { )   }11.Be2 { , Black is, somewhat surprisingly, completely busted. }{ The next moves are  O-O ,  Be2 - g4 , and  Rf1 - e1 . } )
