9. e5{ The only serious follow-up, as moving the knight just drops the  e4 -pawn. }
9. Nd5
10. Ne4
10. c3{ Keeping our extra pawn. White has a lead in development, but the center is closed, which makes it hard to do anything with it. In the meantime, our play is simple: we have to get our pieces out. }
11. bxc3
11. bxc3
12. Ba3{ White wants to exchange bishops and plant a knight on  d6 . }
12. Bb4
13. Nd6+
13. Kf8{ A very calm response. We can play around the knight on  d6 , as we will slowly improve our position with moves like ... Ba6  and ... Kg8 , ... h6 , etc. }
14. Bc4{ The only move that keeps the balance. By eliminating the knight on  d5 , White can create just enough counterplay on the queenside. }
14. Ba6
15. Bxd5
15. cxd5
16. Nb5
16. Kg8
17. Qb3
17. Nc6( { We can end the line here. White just about equalizes with }18.Rfc1 Qb6 19.Qd1! Bxb5 20.axb5 Qxb5 21.Bxb4 Qxb4 22.Qd3 Qc4 23.Qxc3 Qxc3 24.Rxc3 { , but obviously there is not a worry in the world for Black in this variation. } )
