[White "18) Geller Gambit 5.e4"]
[Black "Geller Gambit 5.e4 b5 6.Be2 #9"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nc3( { Obviously, the most natural move, bringing another piece into the game. At the same time, it is not surprising that the last decades have seen an enormous rise in the popularity of the move }4.e3 { . The reason is that after }4.Nc3 { , Black has an enormous amount of options: the Chebanenko with }4...a6 { , Semi-Slav with }4...e6 { , and the move this repertoire is based on − the Classical Slav with }4...dxc4 { . All those systems require quite a lot of knowledge from the first player, and that's why the 'Slow Slav' has become an attractive alternative. } )
4. dxc4( { We are grabbing the pawn on  c4 , which takes play into the Classical Slav. Since }4...Bf5 5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { leads to direct issues, }{ we take on  c4  first, before developing the bishop. } )
5. e4{ The Geller Gambit is named after Efim Petrovich Geller, who started using it with great success in the late '40s and early '50s. His successes inspired many top players to pick up the line, including various World Champions. }
5. b5
6. Be2( 6.a4 { is premature because of }6...b4 { followed by ... Nf6xe4 . } )
6. e6( { Contrary to  6.a4 , now }6...b4 7.Na4 Nxe4 8.Bxc4 { does give White plenty of compensation. The difference lies }{ in the positioning of White's knight on  a4 . In the previous variation, it was poorly placed on  a2 . } )
7. O-O( 7.Qc2 { will  transpose  after }7...a5 8.O-O { . } )
7. a5{ We transpose to a line I also cover in the Triangle Slav, a course for which I teamed up with Christof Sielecki. I see no reasons to deviate from our recommendation in that course and will repeat it here. }( { It took me a while to warm up to the move }7...a5 { , but it does make perfect sense. As White has omitted to }{ play  a2 - a4 , we have the opportunity to make this bold move on the queenside, which carries the positional threat of locking up the queenside with ... a5 - a4 . }{ Note that this idea is not good on move 6, as   }6...a5 7.O-O a4 { gets hit with }8.d5!  )( 7...Bb7 { is a pretty serious battleground these days. In 2019, for instance, Daniil Dubov introduced the interesting idea of }8.Rb1 { intending  b2 - b3 . Besides this modern invention, }8.b3 { , }8.e5 { , }8.Bg5 { , and }8.Qc2 { are moves as well. We are quite happily sidestepping all of this with the text move. } )
8. Bg5
8. Be7( { We generally like to fix the queenside with }8...a4 { , but here }9.e5 h6 10.Bh4 g5 11.Nxg5 hxg5 12.Bxg5 { is a particularly bad version of the Botvinnik Variation. White is several tempi up compared to that very sharp line. } )
9. a4
9. b4( 9...Ba6!? 10.e5 Nd5 11.Bxe7 Nxe7 { is certainly fine as well since it's hard for White to make use of }{ the  d6 -square in an effective way. } )
10. Bxf6
10. Bxf6
11. e5
11. Be7
12. Ne4{ By taking on  f6  and throwing  e4 - e5  in, White has gained the  e4 -square for the knight. }
12. Qd5{ Defending the  c4 -pawn and attacking the  e4 -knight. }
13. Ned2
13. c3
14. bxc3
14. bxc3
15. Nb1
15. Bb4( 15...c2!? 16.Qxc2 Na6 { prepares the knight for the }{ excellent  b4 -square and is very playable as well. } )
16. Qc2
16. Ba6( { We are following Blank-Mikhailov, ICCF email 2019, where Black equalized without much trouble. After the further }17.Rc1 O-O 18.Bxa6 Nxa6 19.Nxc3 Bxc3 20.Ng5 f5! 21.Qxc3 h6 22.Nf3 Rfc8 23.Qc4 { , the game quickly fizzled to a draw. } )
