1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2{ An interesting waiting move that always had a decent following. While protecting  c4 , Black is given the move yet deprived of the natural ... Bc8 - f5  development. }( 4...g6 { is a popular move in this position yet commits to a kingside fianchetto, which may not be to everyone's liking. In choosing the move }4...dxc4 { , I also took into account that we can use this against both   }4.Qc2 { and }4.Qb3 { , saving us the trouble of having to learn two different systems. }4.Qb3 dxc4 5.Qxc4 { transposes to  4.Qc2 . } )
4. dxc4( { We react in the same way as after  4.Nc3 . White now has a choice to simply recapture, or play in gambit style with }5.e4 { . } )
5. Qxc4{ An interesting position. We have voluntarily given up some control of the center by taking the pawn on  c4 , but it has taken White two queen moves to recapture it. That trade-off should give us a fine game. }
5. Bf5( { I always found this to be the most obvious square for the bishop, controlling the  e4 -square. Instead, }5...Bg4 { also has a decent following, but I don't like the resulting positions after }6.Nc3 Nbd7 7.Bf4 { . See for instance the recent victory of Sargissian against Shirov in the Chennai Olympiad. } )
6. Nc3{ A little move order subtlety. }
6. Nbd7( 6...e6 { is possible as well but allows the extra option }7.Qb3 Qb6 8.Nd2!? { for White. While this doesn't promise much of an advantage, it is something we may as well avoid. } )
7. e3{ A modest move that prepares  Nf3 - h4 , to hunt the bishop on  f5 . }( { The immediate }7.Nh4 { runs into the surprising reply }7...Bc2! { White's best would've been to  transpose  back to the main line with   }7.g3 e6 8.Bg2 Be7 9.O-O O-O { , which we'll look at in detail later on. } )
7. e6
8. Nh4( 8.Be2 h6! { gives Black a small edge. The queen }{ on  c4  is simply misplaced. } )
8. Be4{ A new move, but the first one indicated by the engine. The move allows us to hold on to our bishop for now, as taking on  e4  is dangerous. }
9. Nxe4
9. Nxe4{ Recapturing the bishop and simultaneously attacking the knight on  h4 . }
10. Nf3
10. Qa5+{ A very disturbing check! }
11. Bd2
11. Nxd2
12. Nxd2
12. Bb4{ Black was slightly better in Korchnoi-Ivanovic, Rogaska Slatina 2012. }
