6. Nbd7( { I like to start with this one, giving us the option of playing ... e7 - e5  in one go. It should be said though, that }6...e6 7.Bd3 Nbd7!? { is perfectly fine as well. We don't need to fear the structure after }8.Bxf5 exf5 { (more on this structure when we delve into the so-called Dutch Variation of the Slav), }{ as we have perfect control over the squares  d5  and  e4 , which are great outposts for our pieces. }{    Note that the natural-looking sequence   }7...Bxd3 8.Qxd3 Nbd7 9.Nc3 Be7 10.O-O O-O 11.e4 { is exactly what we need to be avoiding and what White is aiming for. Suddenly we land in a slightly passive position where White has nice central control. } )
7. Bd3( { The most played move in this position. }7.Nc3 { transposes to the  6.Nc3 line . } )
7. Bxd3
8. Qxd3
8. e5{ The point behind our 6th move. We get to push the e-pawn to  e5  in one go, already making White worry about equalizing the game. The tactics all work. }
9. dxe5
9. Qa5+
10. Bd2{ After other moves, Black just takes on  e5 . }
10. Nxe5{ We have time for this intermediate move since the queen on  d3  is hanging as well. Black is in fine shape! }
