1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Qc2{ An interesting waiting move that always had a decent following. While protecting  c4 , Black is given the move yet deprived of the natural ... Bc8 - f5  development. }( 4...g6 { is a popular move in this position yet commits to a kingside fianchetto, which may not be to everyone's liking. In choosing the move }4...dxc4 { , I also took into account that we can use this against both   }4.Qc2 { and }4.Qb3 { , saving us the trouble of having to learn two different systems. }4.Qb3 dxc4 5.Qxc4 { transposes to  4.Qc2 . } )
4. dxc4( { We react in the same way as after  4.Nc3 . White now has a choice to simply recapture, or play in gambit style with }5.e4 { . } )
5. Qxc4{ An interesting position. We have voluntarily given up some control of the center by taking the pawn on  c4 , but it has taken White two queen moves to recapture it. That trade-off should give us a fine game. }
5. Bf5( { I always found this to be the most obvious square for the bishop, controlling the  e4 -square. Instead, }5...Bg4 { also has a decent following, but I don't like the resulting positions after }6.Nc3 Nbd7 7.Bf4 { . See for instance the recent victory of Sargissian against Shirov in the Chennai Olympiad. } )
6. g3{ The traditional main move, intending a kingside fianchetto. It makes sense to develop the bishop on the  h1 - a8  diagonal since the queen already occupies the other diagonal and in many lines, after a subsequence  e2 - e3 , wants to drop back to  e2 . }
6. e6{ We don't determine the position of our  b8 -knight just yet, and first focus on castling. }
7. Bg2( { The alternative }7.Nc3 Be7 8.Bg2 O-O 9.O-O { transposes to  7.Bg2 . } )
7. Be7
8. O-O
8. O-O
9. Qb3{ A sideline that aims to lure our queen to  b6 , before hitting it with  Nb1 - d2 - c4 . }
9. Qb6( 9...Na6!? { is possible, inviting }10.Qxb7 Nb4 { , but the knight }{ may simply be misplaced on  a6  after a move like }10.Bd2 { or }10.a3 { . } )
10. Nbd2
10. Rd8( { In one of the first online rapid events that would later become the Champions Chess Tour, Nakamura and Caruana discussed this position twice. In their match, Caruana initially played }10...Nbd7 { , which is slightly worse after }11.Nc4 Qa6 { ( }11...Qxb3 12.axb3 { is an endgame that gives White some serious pressure.)   }12.Bf4 { because }12...Nb6 13.Bd6! { keeps the pressure. } )( 10...Rd8 { effectively rules out any infiltration on }{ the  d6 -square and was played by Caruana the second time he got this position on the board in the match. } )
11. Nc4
11. Qa6( { Again, the endgame after }11...Qxb3 12.axb3 { , just isn't very pleasant. Keeping the queens on is a much better option. } )
12. Bg5
12. Nbd7( 12...Be4!? { is possible as well, }{ ready to exchange on  g2  the moment White's  f3 -knight jumps to  e5 . } )
13. Rfe1
13. h6
14. Bf4( { This is a bit odd. More natural, though not giving any advantage, is }14.Bxf6 { with an approximately equal game after Black's two most natural recaptures. } )
14. Nb6
15. Nce5
15. Qa4{ Black was for choice in MVL-Caruana, chess24.com rapid 2020. }
