10. Qe2{ This may look a bit mysterious at first, but as we have already seen, the queen is sometimes a bit vulnerable on  c4  and from  e2  it supports  e3 - e4  sometimes. }( 10.Nc3 b5 { transposes to the  9.Nc3 move order . } )
10. Rc8( { This modern move, liked by the engines, is a distinct change from how this position used to be handled. A look in the database reveals that the two by far most popular options are }10...Ne4 { , and }10...Qc7 { , with the idea to meet }11.Nc3 { with }11...e5 { . In both cases, Black is playing in the center. We will not be doing that whatsoever, as there is no need! } )
11. Rd1( 11.Nc3 Bg6 12.Rd1 b5 { transposes to  11.Rd1 , while }12.e4 b5! { is fine as well. White's center isn't very stable. } )
11. Bg6{ An excellent preparatory move. Waiting for the knight to appear on  c3 , to hit it with ... b7 - b5 . }( { Tucking the bishop away to  h7  is more time-consuming and, as a result, less effective: }11...h6 12.Nc3 Bh7 13.e4 b5 14.a3 { and Black's position is very cramped. }14...a5 15.d5! { also doesn't help. } )( { The immediate }11...b5 { feels a bit odd right now when there is nothing on the queenside to attack. The engine doesn't hate it, but does give White a small edge after }12.Ne5 { ( }12.Bd2!? { )   }12...Nxe5 13.dxe5 Nd7 14.e4 Bg6 15.h4 { with some initiative on the kingside. } )
12. Nc3
12. b5{ Fully justified now, harassing the knight on  c3 . }
13. a3( 13.e4 b4!  )
13. a5{ Further expansion on the queenside. }
14. Bd2
14. Qb6( { We have an improved version of the  main line  and can calmly continue with ... Rf8 - d8  next. Note that }15.e4 b4 16.axb4 axb4 17.Na4 { runs into }17...Qb5!  )
