[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. Nbd2( { Of course, }4.Nc3 { and }4.e3 { are much more popular and logical. }{ On  d2  the knight hinders the development of the  c1 -bishop. The move has always had a following though, and to this day you will encounter it from time to time. } )
4. Bf5{ Given that there isn't much pressure on our center, it is easy to make this developing move. }
5. Nh4{ Only this move makes the line interesting. I am not aware whether the variation after  4.Nbd2  carries any name, but if we are to give it one, it makes sense to name it after the Czech Master, Karel Opocensky.    In the tournament of Parnu 1937, he got this position on the board twice, thirty years before anyone dared to repeat it. Perhaps it had something to do with the fact that he lost both games. That was not because of the opening though! }
5. e6( { Opocensky's opponents both played }5...Be6 { , but that gives White some edge after }6.e3 { . } )( 5...Be4 { is the big main line, but both }6.Qb3 { and }6.f3 { ask some serious questions. } )( 5...e6 { is a fresh battleground that modern engines don't dislike. What's more: it is much less of a burden on our memory! } )
6. Nxf5( 6.Qb3 Qd7 7.Nxf5 exf5 { transposes to  6.Nxf5 . } )
6. exf5
7. Qb3
7. Qd7{ A new and very important move. Given that we have given up on the bishop pair and slightly fractured our pawn structure, we should try and keep the queens on. }( { After }7...Qb6 8.cxd5!? Nxd5 { ( }8...cxd5 9.Qxb6! axb6 10.e3 { is the type of slightly worse endgame that could turn into real suffering over time.)   }9.g3 Nd7 10.Bg2 { and White has something to work with. } )
8. cxd5{ With the queen on  d7  instead of  b6 , this exchange is less effective. }
8. cxd5{ In the other line mentioned on move 7, White exchanged on  b6  here, which is obviously not possible now. Black is already slightly better according to the engine, and indeed it is very easy to play. Our next moves are ... Nb8 - c6 , ... Bf8 - d6 , and ... O-O  before centralizing our rooks and starting active operations. }
