11. dxc4( { We will see more of this structure in the course when we discuss the so-called Dutch Variation of the Slav, which arises after   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.a4 Bf5 6.Nh4 { , and now }6...e6 7.Nxf5 exf5 { reaches the same pawn structure we are discussing here. At first, it seems counterintuitive to give up the central tension, but we intend to use }{ the  d5  and  e4 -squares for our knights. } )
12. Bxc4
