[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) Slow Slav 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 − 5th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "Slow Slav 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 Bf5 5.cxd5 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3( { The Slow Slav, which is a very practical weapon against the abundance of theory that has amassed after }4.Nc3 { . At first sight, the }4.e3 { move looks somewhat timid, but White is simply }{ protecting  c4 .    We are allowed to bring the  c8 -bishop into the game, but doing so will mean it will likely be exchanged against the  f3 -knight; }{ for instance after }4...Bg4 5.h3 Bxf3 { , or, our repertoire choice,   }4...Bf5 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nh4 { . } )( { Let the shy appearance of the move }4.e3 { not fool you: the resulting positions are strategically complex and are in practice often won by either side. } )
4. Bf5
5. cxd5{ A specialty of English GM Mark Hebden, who has played it on dozens of occasions. This line is a bit of a mixture between an Exchange and Slow Slav. }
5. cxd5
6. Qb3
6. Qc7( { The right way of stopping  Qxb7 . The endgame after }6...Qb6 7.Qxb6 axb6 { is quite unpleasant for Black. A practical example ran }8.Nc3 e6 9.Bb5+ Nfd7 10.Ne5 Bd6 11.Nxd7 Nxd7 12.Bd2 Kd8 13.O-O Nf6 14.f3 Bg6 15.Rfc1 Ne8 16.Na4 Bc7 17.Bb4 { and Black was completely tied up in Hebden-Crouch, 4NCL 1998. Of course, Black could have improved along the way, but it's an illustration of how things can get out of hand. } )
7. Nc3( 7.Bb5+ Nc6 8.Bd2 e6 { transposes to the  7.Bd2 line . } )
7. e6
8. Bd2
8. Nc6
9. Bb5
9. a6( { In Reggio Emilia 1992, Vishy Anand introduced }9...Bd6 10.Rc1 Rb8!? { which is also very fine for Black. After   }9...a6 { though, it looks like White doesn't even manage to equalize. } )
10. Bxc6+
10. bxc6{ I suppose previous generations of players assumed that it was positionally dangerous to play this way as Black. Indeed, if White is allowed to play  Ra1 - c1 ,  Nf3 - e5 ,  Nc3 - a4 , etc, things could get tricky. Luckily we are also allowed to make moves. }
11. Rc1
11. Bd6
12. Na4
12. O-O{ We have finished development and are ready to play ... Rf8 - b8 . }
13. Bb4{ Positionally sound, yet flawed for concrete reasons. }
13. Bxb4+
14. Qxb4
14. Rab8( { White can't prevent a check on  a5  either after }15.Qa3 Qa5+ { , or after   }15.Qc3 Ne4! { followed by  16... Qa5 + . } )
