7. Bd2{ When White delays the move  Nb1 - c3 , it means the idea is to give a check on  b5  and follow it up with the move  Bd2 - b4 , to exchange the dark-squared bishops. White hopes to gain a small advantage this way, but it's doubtful that is the case. }( 7.Bb5+ Nc6 8.Bd2 e6 { transposes to  7.Bd2 . } )
7. Nc6
8. Bb5
8. e6
9. Bb4( { At first sight, it makes more sense to play }9.O-O { first, and only after we have played }9...Bd6 { , White goes }10.Bb4 { so as to gain time. White has a different plan though, and that is to prevent us from castling. } )
9. Bxb4+( 9...Bd6!? { is possible as well, to  transpose  into  9.O-O  after }10.O-O { . } )
10. Qxb4
10. Qe7( { Resolving the situation around our king. }10...Nd7 { can be answered with the tricky }11.Qa3!? { , which invites enormous complications. I am not sure we want to get ourselves involved in }11...Nxd4 12.Bxd7+ Kxd7 13.exd4 Qc1+ 14.Ke2 Qxh1 15.Nc3! Qxa1 16.Ne5+ Ke8 17.Nb5 { , with absolutely crazy complications. } )
11. Bxc6+
11. bxc6
12. Qxe7+
12. Kxe7{ There is some potential for White in this endgame. If we allow something along the lines of  O-O ,  Rf1 - c1 ,  Nb1 - c3 - a4 , we are under some pressure. Luckily, we have plenty of time to prevent this from happening. }
13. Nc3
13. Nd7{ Covering the important squares on  e5  and  c5 . }
14. Na4
14. Rhc8
15. Rc1
15. Be4( { Getting rid of the light-squared bishop since it could potentially become a bad piece. Our pawns, after all, are all placed on light squares, making a nightmare scenario of good knight versus bad bishop not completely unlikely.    It should be said that there are other moves as well. For instance, }15...Kd6 { , }{ preparing ... f7 - f6  and ... e6 - e5 . Remarkably, }16.Nc5 Nxc5 17.Rxc5 { is something White should avoid, as Black just plays }17...a5 { and ... f7 - f6  (preventing  Nf3 - e5 ), ... Rc8 - b8  next, with pressure on  b2 . } )
16. Ke2
16. Bxf3+
17. gxf3
17. Kd6{ The endgame is approximately equal. }
