[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "22) Slow Slav 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 − 5th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "Slow Slav 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.e3 Bf5 5.Nh4 #3"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3( { The Slow Slav, which is a very practical weapon against the abundance of theory that has amassed after }4.Nc3 { . At first sight, the }4.e3 { move looks somewhat timid, but White is simply }{ protecting  c4 .    We are allowed to bring the  c8 -bishop into the game, but doing so will mean it will likely be exchanged against the  f3 -knight; }{ for instance after }4...Bg4 5.h3 Bxf3 { , or, our repertoire choice,   }4...Bf5 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nh4 { . } )( { Let the shy appearance of the move }4.e3 { not fool you - the resulting positions are strategically complex and are in practice often won by either side. } )
4. Bf5
5. Nh4( { One of those trendy lines that suddenly sprung up in a few high-level rapid/blitz games some years ago. White's idea is that }5...Bg6 6.Nxg6 hxg6 { leads to an improved version of the main line (  }5.Nc3 e6 6.Nh4 Bg6 7.Nxg6 hxg6 { ), as White retains more flexibility with the knight }{ on  b1 . As a surprise weapon, it is ideal, but without that element of surprise, it loses most of its strength. } )
5. Bxb1{ Given that White failed to develop the knight to  c3 , it is only fitting we chop it off! On a serious note though taking on  b1  gives up the bishop pair but temporarily weakens White's guard on the  e1 - a5  diagonal. On top of that, the knight on  h4  is temporarily out of play as well.    As I used the word temporary twice already, it should be noted that taking on  b1  is a very concrete move that needs to be backed up fast. Otherwise, White will just have been handed the bishop pair. }( { The engine also doesn't mind }5...Be6!? { and if }6.Qb3 { just }6...Qb6 { . This is certainly a solid alternative, and if   }6.Nd2 { instead, }6...g5 7.Nhf3 g4 { could be fun. } )
6. Rxb1
6. e5( { Played with the right sense of urgency. }6...e6 7.a3 { is far from awful for Black but touches upon the scenario I outlined earlier. If White can }{ play  Bf1 - d3 ,  Nh4 - f3 , and  O-O , Black will be slightly worse. } )( 6...Qa5+ { is bad for many reasons, but the biggest one is }7.Bd2 Qxa2 8.Qc1 { and the queen is in deep trouble with  Rb1 - a1  coming. } )
7. dxe5( { The only critical continuation. }7.Nf3 e4 8.Ne5 Nbd7 { gives us an easy game, and   }7.a3 e4 { prevents the knight }{ on  h4  from finding a clear route home. } )
7. Ne4
8. Nf3
8. Bb4+{ A critical juncture, White can now either interpose on  d2  or move the king. }
9. Bd2
9. Nxd2
10. Nxd2
10. d4{ Trying to further weaken the dark squares in White's camp. }
11. Qe2{ The engine's choice, and, as so often, there is logic to it. White wasn't to be able to recapture on  e3  with the queen. In the meantime,  a2 - a3  is also a threat, to expel the bishop. }
11. Qb6{ Intending to take on  e3  twice and isolate the  e5 -pawn. }
12. a3
12. Bxd2+
13. Kxd2
13. Nd7
14. exd4
14. Qxd4+
15. Kc2
15. O-O-O( { The position is equal, especially if White continues }16.Rd1 Qxe5 17.Qxe5 Nxe5 { . } )
