9. Ke2{ I feel this is the most critical response, introduced by Ray Robson at the Sharjah Masters. Here we will remain a pawn down for some time, but obviously, the king on  e2  provides ample compensation. }
9. O-O
10. g3
10. Nd7{ The most active continuation, in keeping with how we have been playing thus far. }( { Instead, }10...Qd7 11.h4 Rd8 12.Bh3 Qe7 13.Qc2 Nd7 14.a3 Ba5 15.b4 Bc7 16.cxd5 cxd5 17.Qxc7 Rac8 18.Qxb7 Rc2+ 19.Ke1 Rxf2 20.Nd2! { saw White winning in Robson-Sanal, Sharjah 2023. Black can improve with }11...dxc4 { , but I feel the endgame after }12.Qxd7 Nxd7 13.Bh3 f5 14.Rd1 Ndc5 15.Rd4 b5 16.a3 Ba5 17.Bd2 { , gives White some practical chances, regardless of what the engine says. } )
11. cxd5( 11.a3 Bc3 12.cxd5 Qa5 { transposes to  11.cxd5 . } )
11. Qa5( 11...Ndc5!? { is also worth considering, when the engine spits out }12.a3 Bxa3 13.d6 Bb4 14.Qc2 { , and now the very unclear piece sac }14...f6 15.Qc4+ Kh8 16.Qxb4 fxe5 17.Bg2 Qxd6 18.Rd1 Qe6 19.b3! a5! 20.Qe1 a4 { is a total mess. } )
12. a3
12. Bc3( { Using the fact that the bishop is untouchable on  c3 . Of course, }12...Be7 13.d6 { would be awful. } )
13. dxc6{ It is very risky to open the d-file. }
13. Nxe5
14. Nxe5
14. Qxe5
15. Bg2
15. Rad8( { White's king is in deep trouble. }16.Qa4 Nd2! 17.Ra1?! Rd4! { is a nice sample, gaining access }{ to the  b5 -square after }18.Qc2 Qb5+ { . } )
