1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3( { The Slow Slav, which is a very practical weapon against the abundance of theory that has amassed after }4.Nc3 { . At first sight, the }4.e3 { move looks somewhat timid, but White is simply }{ protecting  c4 .    We are allowed to bring the  c8 -bishop into the game, but doing so will mean it will likely be exchanged against the  f3 -knight; }{ for instance after }4...Bg4 5.h3 Bxf3 { , or, our repertoire choice,   }4...Bf5 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nh4 { . } )( { Let the shy appearance of the move }4.e3 { not fool you: the resulting positions are strategically complex and are in practice often won by either side. } )
4. Bf5
5. Nc3
5. e6
6. Bd3{ Avoiding the main theoretical debates and aiming for a quiet strategic battle. }
6. Bg6( { I prefer this over }6...Bxd3 7.Qxd3 { , which seems to fall into White's plans somewhat. } )
7. O-O
7. Nbd7{ Retaining flexibility with our  f8 -bishop for now. We aren't yet sure if  e7 ,  d6 , or  b4  is the right square, and it largely depends on White's next moves. }
8. b3
8. Bd6
9. Bb2
9. Qe7( { Staying flexible with the king for now. Note that, White isn't threatening  e3 - e4  here, so }9...Ne4 { is not well-timed. White is better after }10.Qc2 f5 { (or }10...Ndf6 11.Ne2! { )   }11.Ne2! { , preparing the typical }{ regrouping  Ne2 - f4 ,  Bd3 - e2 , and  Nf4 - d3 , with total control. } )
10. Re1
10. Ne4{ The threat was  e3 - e4 , meaning this is the right moment to make the jump. }
11. Qc2
11. Ndf6( 11...Nxc3 12.Bxc3 Nf6 { is fine as well. } )
12. Ne2
12. Ng4{ Black makes use of the fact that the rook has left  f1 . The tactics continue... }
13. Rf1
13. Qf6
14. h3
14. Nexf2
15. Rxf2
15. Bh2+( { White loses just as   }15.Bxg6 Nxh3+ 16.gxh3 Nxe3 { does. } )
