8. a3{ A bit of a mysterious move to me, introduced at the highest level by Veselin Topalov in the above-mentioned match. Surely the pawn is well placed on  a3 , covering the  b4 -square, but it would seem there are more useful moves to make for now. }( { The move can also be connected to the plan of expanding on the queenside, with  c4 - c5  and  b2 - b4 , but in this case }8.Rb1 { seems a more useful preparatory move, as White's play is faster that way. Evidently, Topalov and his team came to that same conclusion during the match, as he switched to  8.Rb1  in his next White game. } )
8. Nbd7
9. c5{ In general this is a very serious plan, but in the given position, it is just too slow. }
9. g5( { A move we will see more often in this chapter, amongst others in the line with   }8.Rb1 { . } )
10. b4
10. g6{ There is no need to stop  b4 - b5 , as our play in the center will be very fast. }
11. b5
11. Bg7{ With ... e6 - e5  coming, White has to be very careful already. }
