8. Rb1( { As mentioned, introduced by Topalov in the World Championship match. It is also a bit of a Hikaru Nakamura specialty. He played it in many online events and defeated that same Veselin Topalov with }8.Rb1 { in the 2016 Candidates tournament! The idea behind this move is pretty straightforward, White is preparing to expand on the queenside.    The immediate }8.c5 { is a bad move, because of }8...b6 9.b4 a5! { breaking up White's pawns, but }8.Rb1 { steps out of the a-file which makes the above line possible. } )
8. Nbd7
9. c5{ One can imagine how hard it must have been for Kramnik to find his way over the board. There are many options: to play in the center with ... e6 - e5 , or to just develop with ... Bf8 - e7 ? We go for the third option, first slowing White down on the queenside, before starting our own play. }
9. a5( { Nakamura also faced the move }9...g5 { in a few online events. It worked well for his opponents, because after }10.b4 a6 11.a4?! g6 12.b5 axb5 13.axb5 Bg7 { , Black will }{ play ... e6 - e5  next and have an excellent game.    Much stronger is }{   }11.g3 g6 12.Bg2 { , when Black faces an issue: }12...Bg7 13.e4! { is problematic. }13...dxe4 14.Bxg5 { just wins, and   }13...Nxe4 14.Bxe4! dxe4 15.Nxe4 { isn't much better. In short,  9...g5  is not well-timed. } )
10. a3
10. g5( { The same move under slightly different circumstances. }10...e5 11.b4 axb4 12.axb4 Be7 { isn't bad either, but  10...g5  }{ is very ambitious and can get our opponents into trouble if they aren't careful. We have a very clear plan of play in the center, connected to our bishop going to  g7  and pawn to  e5 . } )
11. b4{ Similar to the note on move 9, this move doesn't meet the demands of the position. }
11. axb4
12. axb4
12. g6
13. g3
13. Bg7
14. Bg2
14. e5{ White's position is strategically suspect. }
