10. exd5
11. O-O-O{ And this is the point, getting the king out of the center quickly, and preparing action in the center with  f2 - f3  and  e3 - e4 . }( { If White had played   }10.O-O-O { , we would have gotten fine counterplay with }10...dxc4 11.Bxc4 b5 { . Having }{ captured on  d5  first, White no longer has to worry about that. } )
11. a5{ Very precise! We simply intend to push the pawn to  a4  and, if allowed to  a3 . Slow play doesn't work here. }( { For instance }11...Be7 12.f3! O-O 13.Kb1 { is already pretty bad, as White is ready to push in the center }{ with  e3 - e4 , or play on the kingside with  g2 - g4  and  h2 - h4 . } )( 11...Nb6 { , }{ with the idea of protecting  b7  and threatening to take on  h2 , also isn't a clear solution. White just plays }12.h3 { , after which the same issues remain. }{ White will play  f2 - f3  and  e3 - e4  next. } )
12. Kb1{ Played by Nakamura in a blitz game. It doesn't stop our main idea though. }
12. a4{ A pawn sac to speed things up on the queenside. }
13. Nxa4( 13.Qc2 a3 { is excellent as well. } )
13. b5
14. Nc3
14. b4( 14...Nb6 { to  c4  is a typical idea as well, but }15.Nxb5! { is a good counter in this case. After }15...cxb5 16.Bxb5+ Kd8 17.Rc1 { , White has fine compensation, though it surely isn't that clear }{ ( }17...Ne4! 18.Be1! Qa7 { ) }{ . } )
15. Ne2( 15.Na4 Qa5 { leaves the knight on  a4  in trouble. } )
15. Be7{ We simply castle next and start setting up threats on the queenside. The engine likes ... O-O , ... Rf8 - b8 , ... Ra8 - a3 !? as a means of attack. Needless to say, Black is better here already. }
