2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nf3
3. Nf6
4. e3( { The Slow Slav, which is a very practical weapon against the abundance of theory that has amassed after }4.Nc3 { . At first sight, the }4.e3 { move looks somewhat timid, but White is simply }{ protecting  c4 .    We are allowed to bring the  c8 -bishop into the game, but doing so will mean it will likely be exchanged against the  f3 -knight; }{ for instance after }4...Bg4 5.h3 Bxf3 { , or, our repertoire choice,   }4...Bf5 5.Nc3 e6 6.Nh4 { . } )( { Let the shy appearance of the move }4.e3 { not fool you: the resulting positions are strategically complex and are in practice often won by either side. } )
4. Bf5
5. Nc3
5. e6
6. Nh4{ Here we are faced with a major choice. Where to move our bishop? Moving it we must since  Nh4xf5  can't be allowed − it would harm our structure too much. }( { Historically, the move }6...Bg6 { has been played most, but it's still an open debate whether first }{ provoking  f2 - f3 , }{ with }6...Be4 7.f3 { before dropping back to  g6  is an improved version. On the one hand, the pawn on  f3  could just indeed be ruining the integrity of White's pawn structure, but it can also be the launching pad for a future  e3 - e4  push. The jury is still out! } )( { For this repertoire, I have chosen the solid }6...Bg6 { . I like the resulting positions, which are very straightforward in nature and understandable, whereas the lines after }6...Be4 { are often sharper. } )( { On a final note, I should mention }6...Bg4 { , which is not that popular anymore these days. That probably has to do with Veselin Topalov who, after   }4...Bg4 { , introduced the line }5.Nc3 e6 6.Qb3 Qb6 7.Nh4!? { in 2008, playing against the }{ bishop on  g4 . } )( { If we switch back to }6...Bg4 { , here }7.Qb3 Qb6 { reaches that same position but with a full extra tempo for White. That can't be good news! Jorden van Foreest made an attempt to revive this line by playing }7...dxc4 8.Qxb7 Nbd7 { , but venturing here is at your own risk! } )
6. Bg6
7. Nxg6{ There is something to say for delaying the exchange on  g6  as well, but clarifying the position this way is by far the most popular way to play. }
7. hxg6( { The theory of this variation exploded after the famous Kramnik-Topalov World Championship match in Elista 2006. Topalov, with White, introduced the moves }8.a3 { and }8.Rb1 { in this match, showing that besides the standard moves like }8.Bd2 { , }8.Bd3 { , }8.Qb3 { , etc, there are also other, more original ways of approaching the position, each having their own merit. In the final game of the classical portion of the match, the players reversed colors as Kramnik used the }8.g3 { line with White! } )
8. Bd2{ The main move, and one that still keeps Black guessing as to which setup White chooses. }
8. Nbd7
9. Qc2{ A trendy line that has been picked up recently by the likes of Magnus Carlsen and Wesley So, though it's Polish theoretician and top grandmaster Radoslaw Wojtaszek who introduced it at the top level some 8-9 years ago at the time of writing. }( { After }9...Bd6 { , White intends to play }10.O-O-O { and even though }10...Ng4 11.Be1 Rxh2 12.Rxh2 Nxh2 13.Be2 Qg5 14.g3 Ng4 { , as in Yussupow-Giri, Dutch league 2009, can't be outright refuted, both }15.f4 { and }15.cxd5 exd5 16.Ne4 { , give White fine prospects. } )
9. Rc8
10. h3{ A bit too quiet move for it to pose any problems. }
10. Bb4
11. Bd3( { We have been following the online rapid game Carlsen-Saric, 2022, and here we will deviate from }11...dxc4 12.Bxc4 c5 13.dxc5 O-O 14.O-O Nxc5 15.Rfd1 { , which gives White an edge in the game. } )
11. O-O
12. O-O
12. c5{ Black is super comfortable. }
