11. f4
11. g5{ This is very important since we can't be allowing ourselves to get into total passivity. A scenario we should avoid is illustrated in the following line which, for the record, is not forced at all, but merely serves to show the dangers. }( 11...Be7 12.Be2 b6 13.b4 a5 14.a3 { , first White secures the queenside. }14...O-O 15.g4 Ra8 16.O-O Rfb8 17.g5 Ne8 18.h4 { and now the kingside is secured as well. Long-suffering is ahead, as we have no pawn breaks and can only wait for White to improve the position further. This line explains the necessity for a move like  11...g5 , as White should be prevented from completely surrounding us. } )
12. fxg5( { The critical line. Instead, }12.Bd3 gxf4 13.exf4 g6 { is fine for }{ us, with the bishop coming to  g7 . White's pawn structure is no longer as impressive, having lost some integrity after ... gxf4   exf4 . } )
