7. hxg6( { The theory of this variation exploded after the famous Kramnik-Topalov World Championship match in Elista 2006. Topalov, with White, introduced the moves }8.a3 { and }8.Rb1 { in this match, showing that besides the standard moves like }8.Bd2 { , }8.Bd3 { , }8.Qb3 { , etc, there are also other, more original ways of approaching the position, each having their own merit. In the final game of the classical portion of the match, the players reversed colors as Kramnik used the }8.g3 { line with White! } )
8. Bd2{ The main move, and one that still keeps Black guessing as to which setup White chooses. }
8. Nbd7
9. g3
9. Bb4{ This was Topalov's choice in 2006 against Kramnik, and we will be following in his footsteps. }( { ➢ }9...Be7 10.b3 Bb4 { is how one of the world's best correspondence players, Ron Langeveld, treated this position. I would say it's a typical correspondence solution and is unlikely to be played in practical games.    }{ The reason Black waited for  10.b3  before posting the bishop on  b4 , }{ is }11.Bg2 Bxc3 12.Bxc3 Ne4 { . Now }13.Bb2 { runs into }13...Qa5+ { , which means   }13.Bxe4 dxe4 { is forced. Black was OK after }14.Qg4 Nf6 15.Qe2 Qe7 16.h4 g5 17.O-O-O g4 { , but I am not sure it's a very clear solution for a practical game. } )( { ➢ }9...Bd6 { gives White quite a good version of the  8.g3  line, with }10.Qb3 Rb8 11.Bg2 O-O 12.O-O { . } )
10. Qb3( { In case of }10.Bg2 { , we can simply reply }10...dxc4 { , and hang on to that pawn for the time being. } )
10. a5( { A small update over the Kramnik-Topalov game. After }10...Bxc3 11.Bxc3 Ne4 12.Bg2 Nxc3 { , perhaps Kramnik should have gone for }13.bxc3!? { , which the engine slightly favors over the solid }13.Qxc3 { that was played in the game. } )
11. Be2( { This wasn't the idea behind playing  g2 - g3 , but as we have seen }11.Bg2 Nb6! { is an issue. } )
11. dxc4( 11...g5!? { can be considered as well. Have a look at the following beautiful line: }12.O-O Nb6! 13.c5 Nc4 14.Bxc4 dxc4 15.Qxc4 g4 { , when Black has interesting compensation for the pawn, but how to meet }16.Nb1? { The answer is }16...Ke7!! { and if }17.Bxb4 Rxh2!! 18.Kxh2 Qh8+ 19.Kg1 Qh3 20.Qc2 Rh8 21.f3 gxf3 22.Kf2 Ne4+! 23.Kxf3 Qxf1+ 24.Kxe4 Qf5# { mate!   }23.Ke1 Qxf1+! { is mate as well, as is }23.Qxe4 Qg2+ 24.Ke1 Qe2# { . } )
12. Bxc4
12. c5{ Three correspondence games went down this path. White now needs to deal with the positional threat of receiving an isolated d-pawn. }
13. a3
13. cxd4
14. exd4( { White can't take the bishop pair as }14.axb4 dxc3! 15.Bxc3 axb4 16.Rxa8 Qxa8 17.Bxb4 { loses to }17...b5!  )
14. Bxc3
15. bxc3{ An interesting position. If White can play something like  O-O ,  Bc4 - e2 - f3 ,  Bd2 - e3 ,  c3 - c4 , and centralize the rooks, we are in big trouble. That's why we have to play energetically, not allowing White to get the ideal setup. }
15. Ne4
16. Be3
16. O-O
17. Be2( { After }17.O-O a4 18.Qb4 Ndf6 { , the threat }{ of ... Nf6 - d5  is very serious. } )
17. a4
18. Qb4
18. Ndf6{ Forcing White's reply since ... Nf6 - d5  threatens to win the  c3 -pawn. }( { The immediate }18...b5!? { is indicated by the engine as well but also needs a computer-like backup. I think the text move is easier. } )
19. c4
19. b5
20. Qxb5( 20.cxb5 { is asking for trouble. }20...Nd5 21.Qb2 Nxe3 22.fxe3 Qg5! { Now  e3  is dropping, and that won't be the end of things. } )
20. Nc3{ Exchanging the light-squared bishop will seriously weaken the light squares in White's camp. }
21. Qb2
21. Nxe2
22. Qxe2
22. Qa5+{ Just in time, before White consolidates by castling kingside. }
23. Bd2
23. Qb6{ Forcing the c-pawn up so that  d5  becomes an outpost for our knight. }
24. c5
24. Qb2
25. O-O
25. Rfd8{ We will win back the pawn on  d4 , with an approximately equal game. Our knight will find solid footing on  d5 . The game Sospedra Sebastian-Schulz, correspondence 2020, was drawn on move 36. }
