[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Slow Slav 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e3 Bf5 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Slow Slav 3.Nc3 − 5.Qb3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nc3( { For a long time it was thought that this move order would cause trouble to Slav players. What move to make after }3...Nf6 4.e3? {    }4...Bf5 { runs into }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { as had been known for decades. }{ The problem on  b7  caused many players to play }6...Bc8 { here.   }4...e6 { transposes to a Meran after }5.Nf3 { , which is well outside the scope of our repertoire, and   }4...a6 { is also not to everyone's liking. } )( { Some players sought refuge in }3...dxc4 { , but I have never been a fan of the resulting positions after }4.e3 b5 5.a4 b4 6.Ne4 Qd5 7.Nd2 c3 8.bxc3 bxc3 9.Nb1 { , and White has other options as well. The question remains, what to do? } )
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. Bf5{ In 1886 Zukertort and Steinitz played a match for the World Championship. The story of the match was an amazing one, far exceeding the topic of this course, but where I am going to is the fact that in games 1, 3, and 5, Steinitz used the Slav Defense − a rare opening at the time.    In game 1, Steinitz won in great style, a game that is usually added to his collection of best games. Game 3 saw Steinitz getting a big advantage from the opening, and later a completely winning position, before inexplicably giving his opponents counterplay and even the win shortly thereafter.    For Game 5 though, Zukertort came better prepared, and took on  d5  followed by  6.Qb3 . Steinitz continued to lose a miserable game and dropped the Slav altogether. This loss had a devastating effect on the opening, as for decades(!) it did not get the proper attention. It was only during the match between Alekhine and Euwe in 1935, that the Slav found its rightful place once again, back into the limelight. }
5. Qb3( { Before delving into the complications after }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3 { , we should first see the alternatives. } )( { Playing }5.Qb3 { immediately is less accurate since after our reply, White can no longer win a pawn. In fact,  5.Qb3  is known to lead to extremely dry positions, as White's best bet is to enter an equalish endgame. } )
5. Qb6{ If White had taken on  d5  first,  Nc3xd5  would now be possible. }
6. Qxb6( 6.c5 { is a positional mistake, as after }6...Qc7 { , we are ready to }{ go ... b7 - b6 , and other 6th moves allow us to play ... e7 - e6 , with a good game. } )
6. axb6
7. cxd5
7. Nxd5( { It's important to take a set of knights off. The endgame, or queenless middlegame, after }7...cxd5 8.Nf3 { offers White more chances. } )
8. Nxd5
8. cxd5
9. Bd2
9. Nc6
10. Bb5
10. Bd7( { A maneuver that has been around since the famous game between Janowski and Capablanca, from New York 1916. Capablanca played it after   }10.Nf3 { , but here I would prefer to continue }10...f6!? { as Spielmann did, 7 years later. After Capablanca's }10...Bd7 { , the move }11.Ne5! { gives White a small but risk-free advantage, as was confirmed 76 years later in Tilburg 1992, when Karpov played it against Chernin. } )
11. Nf3( 11.Ne2 { is better, }{ to get the knight to  c3 . } )
11. e6
12. Ke2{ In the endgame, the king should be in the center, but perhaps this is one of those exceptions. }
12. g5( { Everyone played }12...Bd6 { here, but the text move is stronger. After   }13.Nxg5 { , there is }13...Nxd4+ { , when we just want to grab space on the kingside. } )
13. h3
13. f6
14. Bc3
14. Bd6{ The position is close to equal, but Black is slightly on the better side of things. }
