5. f3( { Before moving to the main line, connected to }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3 { , we first look at some alternatives. I found this move in preparation for this course, but in the meantime, it has already been played by several strong players. Things are moving fast these days and the times when one could 'sit' on a novelty, waiting to apply it sometimes for several years, is a thing of the past.    One point is that   }5...e6 { leads to fascinating complications after }6.g4 Bg6 7.h4 { , which we will be avoiding.      }5...h6 { I also don't like since after }6.Qb3 Qb6 { , the endgames become a bit more favorable with the }{ moves  f2 - f3  and ... h7 - h6  included. This eventually lead me to the move of our choice. } )
5. h5{ Stopping  g2 - g4  altogether, and claiming the inclusion of these moves favor us. }
6. Qb3{ An attempt to play the endgame again, with the moves  f2 - f3  and ... h7 - h5  included. }
6. Nbd7( { A sharp alternative to the quiet }6...Qb6 { . We sacrifice the pawn and put our trust in the lead in development. This is a new move, which means we are in fresh territory! } )
7. Qxb7{ Very dangerous. White had better take on  d5  first, before capturing this pawn. }
7. e5{ The well-known story of the oil and the fire and us throwing. }
8. Qxc6
