9. Rb8( { This is an important inclusion since }9...Nxe5 { allows }10.Bb5+ { . } )
10. Qxa7( 10.Qc6 Rb6 11.Qa4 Rb4 12.Qd1 Nxe5 { also seems to give Black excellent play for the sacrificed pawn. Indeed, the lead in development is significant. } )
10. Bc5{ Another tempo move, it's such a pleasure to bring pieces into the game this way. }
11. Qa4
11. d4( { Certainly not the only move, but probably the most correct. There is also the entertaining }11...Rb4 12.Qd1 { ( }12.Qc6 Rb6 13.Qa4 Rb4 { repeats.)   }12...Nxe5 13.a3! Rb7 14.b4 Ba7 { . }{ The rook went to  b7 , so that the bishop is now protected against  Qd1 - a4 +. }15.Bb5+ Rxb5!? { Of course! }16.Nxb5 Nd3+ 17.Kf1 Ne4!? 18.Nxa7 Qf6 { and even the engine, at least at first, seems to be confused. } )
12. exf6
12. O-O{ Calmly finishing development! It is clear this is a very dangerous position for White. }
13. Nge2{ Probably wisest, giving back a piece to get some pieces into the game. }
13. dxc3
14. Nxc3
14. Bb4
15. Be2
15. Qxf6( { Had we taken this pawn one move earlier with   }14...Qxf6 { , then }15.Bb5! { would have prevented us from }{ playing ... Bc5 - b4 . } )
16. O-O
16. Nc5
17. Qd1
17. Rfd8{ All our pieces enter the game with tempo, which is usually a good sign. }
18. Nd5{ An only move! }
18. Qe6
19. e4
19. Nxe4{ This was obviously planned, otherwise, our previous move would not have made much sense. }
20. fxe4
20. Bxe4
21. Bxh5
21. Rxd5{ Despite being still two pawns down, Black is so active that we are completely fine. }
22. Qe2
22. Rxh5{ Raising the stakes even more. }
23. Qxh5
23. Bd3( 23...Bc6!? { , }{ preparing ... Rb8 - b5 , can also be considered and assessed with the famous 0.00 by Stockfish. } )
24. Qf3( { Instead, }24.Bf4 Rb5 25.Qf3 Bxf1 26.Rxf1 Bc5+ { followed by ... Rxb2  and the inevitable loss of the a-pawn as well, is greeted with triple zeros again. } )
24. Bxf1
25. Qxf1
25. Bd6{ Time to bail out for White. }
26. Bf4
26. Bc5+
27. Kh1
27. Rxb2{ The  a2 -pawn will drop as well, with a drawn game. }
