[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "26) Slow Slav 3.Nc3 Nf6 4.e3 Bf5 − 5th Moves"]
[Black "Slow Slav 3.Nc3 − 6.Qb3 Nbd7 Alternative #8"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. Nc3( { For a long time it was thought that this move order would cause trouble to Slav players. What move to make after }3...Nf6 4.e3? {    }4...Bf5 { runs into }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3! { as had been known for decades. }{ The problem on  b7  caused many players to play }6...Bc8 { here.   }4...e6 { transposes to a Meran after }5.Nf3 { , which is well outside the scope of our repertoire, and   }4...a6 { is also not to everyone's liking. } )( { Some players sought refuge in }3...dxc4 { , but I have never been a fan of the resulting positions after }4.e3 b5 5.a4 b4 6.Ne4 Qd5 7.Nd2 c3 8.bxc3 bxc3 9.Nb1 { , and White has other options as well. The question remains, what to do? } )
3. Nf6
4. e3
4. Bf5{ In 1886 Zukertort and Steinitz played a match for the World Championship. The story of the match was an amazing one, far exceeding the topic of this course, but where I am going to is the fact that in games 1, 3, and 5, Steinitz used the Slav Defense − a rare opening at the time.    In game 1, Steinitz won in great style, a game that is usually added to his collection of best games. Game 3 saw Steinitz getting a big advantage from the opening, and later a completely winning position, before inexplicably giving his opponents counterplay and even the win shortly thereafter.    For Game 5 though, Zukertort came better prepared, and took on  d5  followed by  6.Qb3 . Steinitz continued to lose a miserable game and dropped the Slav altogether. This loss had a devastating effect on the opening, as for decades(!) it did not get the proper attention. It was only during the match between Alekhine and Euwe in 1935, that the Slav found its rightful place once again, back into the limelight. }
5. f3( { Before moving to the main line, connected to }5.cxd5 cxd5 6.Qb3 { , we first look at some alternatives. I found this move in preparation for this course, but in the meantime, it has already been played by several strong players. Things are moving fast these days and the times when one could 'sit' on a novelty, waiting to apply it sometimes for several years, is a thing of the past.    One point is that   }5...e6 { leads to fascinating complications after }6.g4 Bg6 7.h4 { , which we will be avoiding.      }5...h6 { I also don't like since after }6.Qb3 Qb6 { , the endgames become a bit more favorable with the }{ moves  f2 - f3  and ... h7 - h6  included. This eventually lead me to the move of our choice. } )
5. h5{ Stopping  g2 - g4  altogether, and claiming the inclusion of these moves favor us. }
6. Qb3{ An attempt to play the endgame again, with the moves  f2 - f3  and ... h7 - h5  included. }
6. Nbd7( { A sharp alternative to the quiet }6...Qb6 { . We sacrifice the pawn and put our trust in the lead in development. This is a new move, which means we are in fresh territory! } )
7. cxd5{ White does well to include this capture before taking on  b7 . }
7. cxd5
8. Qxb7
8. e5( { The most aggressive approach, but there is something to say for }8...e6 { as well. } )
9. dxe5( 9.Bb5 Bd6 { followed by ... O-O  is fine for Black. Development is the keyword! } )
9. Rb8( { This is an important inclusion since }9...Nxe5 { allows }10.Bb5+ { . } )
10. Qxa7( 10.Qc6 Rb6 11.Qa4 Rb4 12.Qd1 Nxe5 { also seems to give Black excellent play for the sacrificed pawn. Indeed, the lead in development is significant. } )
10. Bc5{ Another tempo move, it's such a pleasure to bring pieces into the game this way. }
11. Qa4
11. d4( { Certainly not the only move, but probably the most correct. There is also the entertaining }11...Rb4 12.Qd1 { ( }12.Qc6 Rb6 13.Qa4 Rb4 { repeats.)   }12...Nxe5 13.a3! Rb7 14.b4 Ba7 { . }{ The rook went to  b7 , so that the bishop is now protected against  Qd1 - a4 +. }15.Bb5+ Rxb5!? { Of course! }16.Nxb5 Nd3+ 17.Kf1 Ne4!? 18.Nxa7 Qf6 { and even the engine, at least at first, seems to be confused. } )
12. exd4{ Essentially, a queen sacrifice. }
12. Rb4
13. Qc6( 13.Qa6 Bxd4 14.exf6 O-O { gives Black great play for the piece. Just look at the poor king }{ on  e1 . } )
13. Rb6
14. Qxc5( 14.Qa4 Rb4 { would force a repetition. } )
14. Nxc5
15. dxc5
15. Rb4( { The knight on  f6  is sacrificed for the greater good. Instead, }15...Re6 16.Bb5+ Kf8 17.Bf4 { is a position that I find attractive for White, with two pieces and four(!) pawns for the queen. } )
16. exf6
16. O-O{ Nobody will play this position perfectly, but knowing the engine feels it's fine for Black, and having easy moves such as ... Qd8 - d4  and ... Rf8 - e8  at our disposal, makes me think this position is very hard to play for White. }( { Given that   }6...Nbd7 { is a new move, we shouldn't be expecting all the analysis we have seen here to appear on the board. It merely serves as a guideline to what is a very sharp and interesting pawn sacrifice. I look forward to seeing it introduced in practice. } )
