3. Nf6
4. e3
4. Bf5{ In 1886 Zukertort and Steinitz played a match for the World Championship. The story of the match was an amazing one, far exceeding the topic of this course, but where I am going to is the fact that in games 1, 3, and 5, Steinitz used the Slav Defense − a rare opening at the time.    In game 1, Steinitz won in great style, a game that is usually added to his collection of best games. Game 3 saw Steinitz getting a big advantage from the opening, and later a completely winning position, before inexplicably giving his opponents counterplay and even the win shortly thereafter.    For Game 5 though, Zukertort came better prepared, and took on  d5  followed by  6.Qb3 . Steinitz continued to lose a miserable game and dropped the Slav altogether. This loss had a devastating effect on the opening, as for decades(!) it did not get the proper attention. It was only during the match between Alekhine and Euwe in 1935, that the Slav found its rightful place once again, back into the limelight. }
5. cxd5
5. cxd5
6. Qb3( { It is hard to cover the weak points in Black's position.  b7  is hanging, and after }6...Qb6 7.Nxd5! { wins a pawn. } )( 6...Qd7 7.Nf3 { is also highly unpleasant, as the queen is exposed }{ to  Nf3 - e5 , while }{   }6...b6 7.Bb5+ { is not much better. } )( { Steinitz played }6...Bc8 { , and following }7.Nf3 Nc6 8.Ne5 e6 9.Bb5 Qd7 10.Bd2 Bd6 11.f4 O-O 12.Rc1 Bxe5 13.fxe5 Ne8 { , he got into an awful position and lost without a chance. Curiously, at the tournament of New York 1924, Capablanca fell for the same opening trap as Steinitz.    He did improve on Steinitz's play with   }7...e6 8.Bd3 Nc6 9.Bd2 { , but now, instead of a move like }9...Be7 { , which keeps White's advantage to a minimum, he played }9...Qb6?! { after which }10.Qxb6 axb6 { would have given his opponent, Alekhine, a considerable advantage in the endgame. In his notes to the game, Alekhine writes that '...an exchange of queens would surely not have been of advantage to White.' It is exemplary of the leap technical chess has taken in the past century. It is obvious now that after, for instance, }11.Ne5 Be7 12.Nb5 { , Black is under enormous pressure.    All in all, it is clear that something has gone wrong if Black must return the bishop }{ to  c8  on move 6. }{ Of course, the position is far from lost, but White gets a pleasant and lasting advantage for free. I should add that White can also play   }7.f4!? { after  6...Bc8 , with the idea that after }7...e6 8.Nf3 Nc6 9.Bd3 { , White has strong central control. } )
6. Nc6{ This is the move that has changed the evaluation of  4...Bf5 . Some 10 years ago it was still an oddity when it was first introduced in tournament practice, but fast forward to today, it has become accepted as fully rehabilitating the line. We give up the pawn on  b7 , and get a big lead in development in return. }
7. Qxb7
7. Bd7
8. Bb5{ Trying to gain additional time by attacking the  c6 -knight. }
8. Rb8( { Not }8...Rc8 9.Nf3 { , when White is catching up in development. } )
9. Qa6( 9.Qxc6 { is a bit too optimistic, as after }9...Bxc6 10.Bxc6+ Nd7 { , White has only two pieces for the queen. } )
9. Nb4{ Forcing White to trade on  d7  and drop the queen back to  e2  since there is no other way of protecting against the check on  c2 . }
10. Qa4( { This move is wrong on many levels, }10...Nd3+ { already being one of them. } )
10. Rxb5
11. Nxb5
11. e5( { The pin on the  b5 -knight makes Black's position already winning. The game Zubarev-Vysochin, Kyiv 2020, continued }12.Bd2 Nd3+ 13.Ke2 Qb8 { and White will suffer heavy material losses. } )( 12.dxe5 { doesn't help either, as after }12...Ne4 { , }{ the ... Ne4 - c5  and ... Qd8 - b6  threats will force White to shed material anyway. } )
