5. Nc6
6. Bf4( { The big roadblock. We have two options here, }6...Bf5 { being what I would call, the 'professional' line. If we know what we are doing, it will be very hard for White to do much. There is a vast amount of theory here though, and as the recent game Duda-Firouzja, Bucharest 2023 shows, it is easy to mix up and get in trouble as Black.    I have therefore chosen to go with }6...a6 { , which is a bit more flexible and requires less direct knowledge. In a way, you could also say it's more ambitious, as we break the symmetry. I would caution against getting too excited though. As I explained earlier, our first task is to equalize before we can think of more. } )
6. a6
7. e3{ The most popular move in the position, but it does allow us to solve the issue with our  c8 -bishop. }
7. Bg4
8. Be2( { This feels slightly less precise than }8.h3 { . }{ I think the bishop is better placed on  d3 , while the queen recaptures on  f3 . } )
8. e6( { People have also played the direct }8...Bxf3 9.Bxf3 e6 { , but I don't see the need to take immediately. } )
9. Qb3( { The only critical move, as }9.O-O Bd6 { is very equal. } )
9. Bxf3( { Avoiding }9...Na5 10.Qa4 b5 11.Bxb5+! axb5 12.Nxb5 { , which is crushing.    }{ A nice rule of thumb is that sacrifices like these only tend to work for White after we have moved our  c8 -bishop and played ... e7 - e6 . The bishop can then no longer drop back to  d7  to assist in the defense. } )
10. gxf3( 10.Bxf3 Na5 11.Qa4+ b5! { can no longer be met with a }{ capture on  b5 , meaning Black is doing well. } )
10. Bd6( 10...Na5!? 11.Qa4+ Nc6 { is possible as well. } )( { After }10...Bd6 { , it is not possible to play }11.Qxb7 { because of }11...Na5 { , while   }11.Bxd6 Qxd6 12.Qxb7 O-O 13.Qb3 { (... Rfb8  was threatened) }13...e5! { gives Black an active game. } )
