8. Rc8( { In order to recapture on  c6  with the rook. Instead, }8...Nxe5 9.dxe5 d4 { would be an easy route to equality after }10.exf6 dxc3 { , but   }10.e4! { is a better try. I would prefer to avoid these complications. } )
9. e3{ This position looks very quiet but some strong grandmasters have gotten into trouble here as Black, so we should continue to be vigilant. }( 9.Qb3 { is easily met with }9...Na5 { . } )
9. e6( { The immediate }9...Nxe5 { can be played as well but requires a bit more accuracy. }10.dxe5 Ne4 11.Nxe4 dxe4 12.Qxd8+ Kxd8 13.Bc4 { puts some pressure on an unprepared opponent and having to memorize }13...b5 14.Rd1+ Ke8 15.Bd5 e6 16.Bb7 Bb4+ 17.Kf1 Rc2 18.Bxa6 Ke7 19.Bxb5 Rb8 20.Be2 Rbc8! { and realize that we have enough compensation to hold the balance here, seems excessive and unnecessary. } )
10. Qb3( { Our go-to response here is }10...Na5 { , but }11.Qa4+ b5 12.Bxb5+! { spells trouble, meaning we take a different path. } )
10. Nxe5
11. Bxe5( 11.dxe5 { is just bad since }11...Ne4 12.Qxb7 { loses to }12...Nc5!  )
11. Qd7
12. Be2
12. Ne4( { The last precise move and an important one. It is very easy to slip into a worse position after }12...Be7 13.O-O O-O 14.Na4! { , when White holds all the trumps on the queenside. For instance }14...Rxc1 15.Rxc1 Rc8 16.Rxc8+ Qxc8 17.Nc5! Bxc5 18.dxc5 { and both Movsesian and Karjakin (in blitz) were unable to hold this position as Black. } )
13. f3( 13.O-O Nd2! { is one of the points behind }{ going ... Nf6 - e4 . } )
13. Nd6( { On the way to  c4 . Less good is }13...Nxc3 14.Rxc3 Rxc3 15.Qxc3 { , when White keeps some small, yet annoying, pressure. } )
14. Kf2
14. Nc4{ The position is approximately equal. After White moves the bishop from  e5 , we can play ... Bf8 - e7 . }
