[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "28) Exchange Variation − Introduction"]
[Black "Exchange Slav 4.Nf3 − 6.Bf4 #14"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. cxd5{ The Exchange Variation − often described as boring, but I beg to differ. The resulting positions, especially when White is playing for a win, are very interesting and in fact full of life. If White wishes to make a draw, then we have to learn to be patient and seize every small opportunity we get. Taking this task seriously can truly improve your strength as a player.    Looking at the database, one sees that on all levels there are many decisive games in this variation. Humans make mistakes, and having a symmetrical pawn structure doesn't change the fact we still have a board full of pieces. Our first task is to acquaint ourselves with the necessary theoretical knowledge, so as not to get into trouble.    I often see players behind the black pieces rushing to make active moves in this variation; a completely wrong approach. Patience is key, and that means we first have to neutralize White's extra move, before thinking about taking over. }( { A few things about the move order. I believe the best move order for White is connected to }3.cxd5 cxd5 4.Bf4 { , but White can also play   }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 5.Bf4 { , which will transpose. The move order   }3.Nf3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 { is covered under   }3.cxd5 cxd5 4.Nf3 { . } )
3. cxd5
4. Nf3{ Generally, it is considered that the lines in which White has already committed the  g1 -knight to  f3  are slightly less critical. Starting with  Nb1 - c3 ,  Bc1 - f4 , and  e2 - e3 , the modern setup of the Exchange Variation, gives the option of sometimes flicking in  f2 - f3  or developing the  g1 -knight to  e2 , if need be. }
4. Nf6
5. Nc3
5. Nc6
6. Bf4( { The big roadblock. We have two options here, }6...Bf5 { being what I would call, the 'professional' line. If we know what we are doing, it will be very hard for White to do much. There is a vast amount of theory here though, and as the recent game Duda-Firouzja, Bucharest 2023 shows, it is easy to mix up and get in trouble as Black.    I have therefore chosen to go with }6...a6 { , which is a bit more flexible and requires less direct knowledge. In a way, you could also say it's more ambitious, as we break the symmetry. I would caution against getting too excited though. As I explained earlier, our first task is to equalize before we can think of more. } )
6. a6
7. Rc1( { A tricky move, preventing us from playing }7...Bg4 { . Preventing may not actually be the right word, since the position after }8.Ne5 Nxe5 9.Bxe5 { isn't that bad, but it isn't great either, and rather one-sided. That's why, just this once, we develop the bishop }{ to  f5  instead. } )
7. Bf5
8. e3
8. e6( { Some sources recommend }8...Rc8 { here, in order to be able to play  9...Na5  after }9.Qb3 { . I do not like the position we get in the main line of this variation though. After the straightforward moves }9.Be2 e6 10.O-O Bd6 11.Bxd6 Qxd6 { , White holds a small and risk-free advantage.    A good example of that is the game Le Quang Liem-Mishra, online rapid 2021, which continued }12.Na4 O-O 13.Nc5 Rc7 14.Qb3 Qe7 15.Rc3 Bg4 16.Rfc1 Ne4 17.R3c2 Nxc5 18.Rxc5 f5 19.h3 Bh5 20.Qd1 Rfc8 21.Ne1! Bxe2 22.Qxe2 Nb8 23.Nd3 b6 24.Rxc7 Rxc7 25.Rxc7 Qxc7 26.Nf4 Qd6 27.g4! { and because }27...g6 { loses to }28.gxf5 gxf5 29.Qh5 { , Black is already in deep trouble. Of course, Black could improve upon this game, but the general gist of it is clear:  8...Rc8  leads to a very one-sided type of game. I don't think White deserves that. } )
9. Bd3{ The solid option, aiming for as dry a game as possible. }
9. Bxd3
10. Qxd3
10. Be7( { This is slightly more playful than }10...Bd6 { . We keep the bishops on in the hope of one day proving that it's better than its counterpart. We castle next, and the position is approximately equal. Judging by the number of decisive games in the database though, there is plenty of play left. } )
