7. e5( { Excellent. We try to break down White's center in the same way as in the Fantasy Variation of the Caro-Kann, which arises after   }1.e4 c6 2.d4 d5 3.f3 { and now }3...dxe4 4.fxe4 e5 { . It shows the importance of studying the game of chess thoroughly, and not just the openings that are part of your repertoire. Very often ideas seen in one opening, can be applied in another. } )
8. Bb5+( 8.dxe5 Ng4 { already gives Black the better game. } )
8. Nc6{ In the 37(!) games I found of Aditya in the database, no one ever reached this position, showing you that it is indeed a nice blitz weapon for White. }( 8...Bd7 9.dxe5 Bxb5 10.exf6 { may still continue after }10...Bb4 { or }10...Bc4 { , but why would we see these complications when there is a healthy alternative? } )
9. d5{ The one question remaining. Why aren't we losing a piece? }
9. Bb4{ Pinning the knight and thereby threatening to take the  b5 -bishop. }
10. Qd3
10. a6
11. Ba4
11. Qa5{ Again, threatening the bishop. }
12. Bd1
12. Nd4{ Having solved the issues with the pinned knight, Black is for choice. }
