5. Nc3( { This may just lead to a transposition if we play }5...Nf6 { here, but there is an interesting alternative. } )
5. e5{ Of the lines where Black throws in ... e7 - e5 , this is probably the best version, as we have already developed the  b8 -knight, and the bishop on  f4  is awkwardly placed. }
6. Bxe5{ Taking the pawn while also getting a set of minor pieces off the board is White's best bet. }
6. Nxe5
7. dxe5
7. d4
8. Ne4
8. Bb4+
9. Nd2
9. Ne7{ Our compensation lies in the fact that the  d4 -pawn somewhat hampers White's development, and the  e5 -pawn is weak and is likely to fall. On top of that, we have the pair of bishops. }
10. Ngf3
10. O-O
11. g3
11. Nd5( { The key idea. There is no fun in }11...Nc6 12.Bg2 { , when Black is either a bit worse or forced to play }12...d3 13.O-O Nxe5! 14.Nxe5 dxe2 15.Qxe2 Qxd2 16.Qxd2 Bxd2 { , where White is still a bit better, and what's worse, it's risk-free. } )
12. Bg2{ Given one more move, White can claim an advantage by castling kingside. }( 12.a3 Ba5 { transposes to the  11.a3 line . } )
12. Ne3{ Just in time! }
13. fxe3
13. dxe3
14. a3
14. exd2+
15. Nxd2
15. Bc5( { We have pleasant compensation for the pawn even if the queens get off the board: }16.Nb3 Bb6 17.Qxd8 Rxd8 { brings no relief since }{ the king is awkwardly placed on  e1 , and the pawns on the e-file are susceptible to a ... Rd8 - e8  assault as well. } )
