5. Nf6
6. Nc3{ Reaching what I feel is the optimal setup in the Exchange Slav, though these terms are of course very relative, as all lines are objectively fine for Black. Delaying the development of the  g1 -knight and doing so via this move order, not allowing any early ... e7 - e5  break or other such ways for Black to complicate things, is the most challenging for Black. }
6. a6( { We have spoken about choosing this setup over the 'professional' line }6...Bf5 { , before. I feel }6...a6 { is less heavy on the memory and, every so slightly, more playful. } )
7. Be2{ It is pretty obvious which move White is trying to stop this way! In his 2016 book on the Queen's Gambit and Exchange Slav, Alexei Dreev recommends this way of playing for White. Given that we can't play ... Bc8 - g4 , and ... e7 - e6  is generally not very desirable with the bishop still on  c8 , there is certainly a point behind this setup. }
7. Bf5
8. g4{ An aggressive thrust, advocated by Dreev in his book. Modern engines manage to neutralize it quite effectively. }
8. Be4{ Typically, we first provoke a small weakness in White's camp. }
9. f3( { Instead, }9.Nxe4 { gives Black a fine game after both recaptures. } )
9. Bg6
10. h4( { Unfortunately, White can force a repetition with }10.Qb3 Na5 11.Qa4+ Nc6 12.Qb3 { , though }12...Ra7 { can be considered. } )
10. h6( 10...h5!? { can also be considered, as }11.g5 Nd7 { is a promising pawn sacrifice. After }12.Nxd5 Qa5+ 13.Nc3 e5! 14.dxe5 Rd8 { , the engine slightly leans towards White, but in a practical game this is just chaos! } )
11. Nh3( { Again, }11.Qb3 Na5 12.Qa4+ Nc6 13.Qb3 { is available to White, and }13...Ra7 { a daring way to continue the game. } )
11. e6
12. Bg3{ Freeing up the  f4 -square for the knight. We have a strong response though. }
12. h5
13. g5( 13.Nf4 Bd6 14.g5 Ng8 { and ... Ng8 - e7  is just better. All our pieces have ideal squares. } )
13. Ng8{ Modern engines can be baffling at times. We want to play ... Bf8 - d6  next, followed by ... Ng8 - e7  and we already have an edge at this point! White is overextended on the kingside. }
14. Qb3( 14.Nf4 Bd6 { transposes to the note on move 13. } )
14. Bb4( { Again, we want to play ... Ng8 - e7  next, and besides that, }15.a3 Ba5 16.Qxb7?! Nge7 { gives Black fantastic compensation. White's position lacks harmony. } )
