[Black "Exchange Slav 4.Bf4 Nc6 5.e3 #16"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. c4
2. c6( { The starting point of the Slav Defense. Rather than capturing the gambit pawn on  c4 , which would hand White more central control, Black reinforces the pawn on  d5  so that after }3.cxd5 cxd5 { , no influence in the center is lost. } )( { Another advantage over, say, }2...e6 { , is that }{ the  c8 -bishop is unobstructed and can still get developed outside the pawn chain to  f5 , before going ... e7 - e6 . } )
3. cxd5{ The Exchange Variation − often described as boring, but I beg to differ. The resulting positions, especially when White is playing for a win, are very interesting and in fact full of life. If White wishes to make a draw, then we have to learn to be patient and seize every small opportunity we get. Taking this task seriously can truly improve your strength as a player.    Looking at the database, one sees that on all levels there are many decisive games in this variation. Humans make mistakes, and having a symmetrical pawn structure doesn't change the fact we still have a board full of pieces. Our first task is to acquaint ourselves with the necessary theoretical knowledge, so as not to get into trouble.    I often see players behind the black pieces rushing to make active moves in this variation; a completely wrong approach. Patience is key, and that means we first have to neutralize White's extra move, before thinking about taking over. }( { A few things about the move order. I believe the best move order for White is connected to }3.cxd5 cxd5 4.Bf4 { , but White can also play   }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 5.Bf4 { , which will transpose. The move order   }3.Nf3 Nf6 4.cxd5 cxd5 { is covered under   }3.cxd5 cxd5 4.Nf3 { . } )
3. cxd5
4. Bf4( { Having seen the other move orders we can now appreciate why this is considered the cleanest one. }4.Nc3 { allows }4...e5 { , while   }4.Nf3 { commits the knight to  f3  when White would prefer to stay flexible. } )
4. Nc6( 4...Nf6 5.e3 Nc6 { would  transpose . } )
5. e3( { Not allowing the complications after   }4.Nc3 e5!? { , which seem to be fine for Black. } )
5. Nf6
6. Nc3{ Reaching what I feel is the optimal setup in the Exchange Slav, though these terms are of course very relative, as all lines are objectively fine for Black. Delaying the development of the  g1 -knight and doing so via this move order, not allowing any early ... e7 - e5  break or other such ways for Black to complicate things, is the most challenging for Black. }
6. a6( { We have spoken about choosing this setup over the 'professional' line }6...Bf5 { , before. I feel }6...a6 { is less heavy on the memory and, every so slightly, more playful. } )
7. Bd3( { Contrary to }7.Be2 { , here White does }{ allow us to bring the  c8 -bishop to  g4  and hopes to exploit its position there. } )
7. Bg4
8. Nge2
8. e6
9. O-O
9. Bd6( 9...Be7 { isn't as convenient here, compared to having the moves  9.h3 Bh5  included. That is because if we follow the same line, }10.Rc1 O-O 11.Na4 Rc8 ( 11...Nh5!? 12.Be5 f6 13.Bg3 Nxg3 14.hxg3 { is close to equal, but not quite just yet. } )12.Nc5 Bxc5 13.Rxc5 Qb6 14.Qd2 { , we would continue with  14...Bg6  }{ (given that the white pawn was on  h3  there, and our bishop on  h5 ), exchanging the light-squared bishops. Here that is not an option. Trying to do it anyway, a tempo down, with }14...Bh5 { gives White many ways to play for an edge, of which }15.Ng3!? Bg6 16.Be2! { may be the most convincing one. }{ With  h2 - h4  coming, this could turn rather unpleasant for Black. } )
10. f3
10. Bh5
11. Rc1{ Quite a typical position, and one that has been played over 350 times in the database. White's play is not that sophisticated and largely based on bringing a knight to  c5 . The  e2 -knight is destined for  f4  and eventually  d3 . That seems far away now, but we will play our bishop to  g6  and when all the bishops get exchanged, the  e2 -knight will have a very direct route to  d3 . }
11. Bg6( { Having done its job on  h5 , we may as well bring the bishop back immediately. }11...O-O { is likely to transpose, as we will have to bring back our bishop anyway. } )
12. Na4
12. O-O
13. Nc5
13. Bxd3( { A fine alternative is }13...Bxc5!? 14.Rxc5 Nh5 { , exchanging even more pieces and securing a very solid game. } )
14. Qxd3
14. Bxf4
15. Nxf4
15. Qe7{ White has a pretty knight on  c5 , but we are ready to either go ... e6 - e5  and play in the center, or simply slow-play it with ... Rf8 - c8 . The engine gives its famous 0.00. Perhaps that's a fitting way to end this chapter on the Exchange Slav! }
