5. e4
6. Bc2{ This bishop makes this a rather weird case of an Advance French, where the  f8 -bishop never makes it to  c7 ! On  c2 , the bishop helps prepare the  f2 - f3  break. }
6. Bd6
7. f3
7. Be6( { If this position is already quite rare, this move is even rarer! Nearly everyone plays }7...O-O { , which is fine as well, but I like the surprise value of }7...Be6 { . } )( { We should not go for }7...exf3 8.Nxf3 { , as this opens up White's position, and }8...dxc4?! 9.e4 { is already huge. } )
8. cxd5
8. cxd5
9. Nh3
9. exf3{ Now that the knight can't recapture, we don't mind taking on  f3  anymore. }
10. Qxf3
10. O-O
11. O-O
11. Nc6{ The position is approximately equal. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Slav 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 c6 4.g3 − 6.Bg2 and 6.Qb3"]
[Black "Slav 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 c6 4.g3 − 6.Bg2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. c4
3. c6
4. g3( { After }4.Nc3 dxc4 5.g3 { , }{ this is the next  g3  setup we will be reviewing. We will also have a look at }{   }1.d4 d5 2.g3 { and   }1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 { . All these variations are, of course, closely intertwined, and it is recommended to make a careful study of them so as not to confuse the move orders. } )
4. Bf5{ In the same style as before. If possible, we always want to develop the  c8 -bishop before playing ... e7 - e6 . }
5. Nc3( 5.Bg2 e6 6.Nc3 { would transpose to  5.Nc3  after }6...h6 { . } )
5. e6
6. Bg2
6. h6( { Safeguarding the bishop against  Nf3 - h4 . Following }7.O-O Nbd7 { , this would  transpose  to   }1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 { , but White has the option of delaying castling. } )
7. Qb3{ Tricky, as it forces us to choose a different setup compared to the lines we saw earlier. }
7. Qb6
8. c5
8. Qc7( { With  O-O  and ... Nb8 - d7  included, we are happy to play }8...Qa6 { here, but now that runs into }9.Bf1! { , }{ when  e2 - e4  is a giant threat. } )( { When possible, I prefer to avoid the endgame, which is what White is aiming for. Having said that, }8...Qxb3 9.axb3 Be7 10.b4 O-O { is certainly very playable as well. } )( { With }8...Qc7 { , we keep the queens on and, now that we have provoked the move  8.c5 , we'll try to undermine White's structure with a }{ future ... b7 - b6 . We looked at this move before, but a big difference is that White castled there, and we already had ... Nb8 - d7  played. We will see why this is important momentarily. } )
9. Bf4
9. Qc8
10. O-O( { Instead, }10.Nd2 Be7 11.e4 Bg6 12.O-O { will transpose. } )( { The engine also suggests the line }10.a4 Nbd7 11.a5 { , fixing the queenside. I am not overly impressed with this sequence and think }11...g5 12.Be5 a6! { or   }12.Bd2 Bg7 { gives Black fine chances. Given that we have a fine presence in the center and kingside, it’s not clear whether closing down the queenside is the right thing to do for White. } )
10. Be7
11. Nd2
11. O-O
12. e4
12. Bg6( { Taking on  e4  is a bit risky. After }12...dxe4 13.Ndxe4 Nxe4 14.Nxe4 { , Black is forced to take }{ on  e4  in order not to allow an invasion on  d6 . }14...Bxe4 15.Bxe4 { and this position would be very acceptable if Black's pawn }{ were still on  h7 . Black would then play ... Nd7 - f6 , ... Rf8 - d8 , and perhaps ... g7 - g6  to bring the bishop to  g7  at an appropriate moment. With the pawn on  h6 , however, this is not so easy to achieve, and it gives White some hope of an initiative after }15...Nd7 16.Rad1 Nf6 17.Bb1 { , }{ with moves like  Qb3 - c2 / d3  and  Bf4 - e5  coming. } )
13. Rfe1
13. Rd8( 13...Nbd7 { is generally desirable but, as we have seen earlier, loses a pawn after }14.exd5 cxd5 15.Nxd5! { That's why the move order is so important. Our last move is prophylaxis }{ against  exd5 . } )
14. Rad1
14. b6( { I love the boldness of this move! Previous practice saw }14...Bf8 { , }{ intending ... Nb8 - d7  and ... b7 - b6 , which is very reasonable, but the engine believes the ... b6  break doesn't need further preparations. } )
15. cxb6( { There is the interesting option of }15.Bd6 { , using the fact that }15...Bxd6 16.cxd6 Rxd6? 17.e5 { loses a piece. Luckily, our 16th move isn’t forced, and we can improve with   }16...dxe4 { . }{ This capture means that the  d6 -pawn will become isolated and weak. } )
15. axb6
16. Qxb6{ If White doesn't take this pawn, Black will just have a structural advantage. }
16. Rd7( { Bringing the rook over to the b-file. }16...dxe4 { is possible as well. It's remarkable how, a pawn down, Black has various non-forcing ways to play. I especially like the line }17.Ndxe4 Nd5 18.Nxd5 cxd5 19.Nc3 Qc6! { , which is very instructive. Black, still a pawn down, offers the transition into an endgame. White should avoid that since }20.Qxc6 Nxc6 { already hands Black the }{ initiative.  d4  is a target (... Be7 - f6 ), and the a- and b-files give Black additional Benko-type compensation. } )
17. Qb3{ The only move to avoid getting trapped. }
17. Rb7
18. Qc2
18. Nbd7( { We are a pawn down, but the engine shows triple zeros. That is because our position is rock solid and our pieces are very harmonious. As mentioned earlier, Black has excellent play on the a- and b-files. What's more, another motive, after for instance }19.a3 { , that is worth remembering is }19...c5! { , hitting White in the center. } )
