[Round "?"]
[White "31) Slav 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 c6 4.g3 − 6.Bg2 and 6.Qb3"]
[Black "Slav 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 c6 4.g3 − 6.Qb3 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. c4
3. c6
4. g3( { After }4.Nc3 dxc4 5.g3 { , }{ this is the next  g3  setup we will be reviewing. We will also have a look at }{   }1.d4 d5 2.g3 { and   }1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 { . All these variations are, of course, closely intertwined, and it is recommended to make a careful study of them so as not to confuse the move orders. } )
4. Bf5{ In the same style as before. If possible, we always want to develop the  c8 -bishop before playing ... e7 - e6 . }
5. Nc3( 5.Bg2 e6 6.Nc3 { would transpose to  5.Nc3  after }6...h6 { . } )
5. e6
6. Qb3{ After this move, we have no choice but to play the endgame. }
6. Qb6( 6...b6 { is obviously very ugly. Simply }7.Nh4 Be4 8.f3 { gives White an advantage. } )
7. c5
7. Qxb3( { Forced, as }7...Qc7 8.Bf4 Qc8 9.Nh4 { gives White a pleasant game. Our light-squared bishop is about to be traded off. This line immediately illustrates the big difference with   }6.Bg2 { . There we played }6...h6 { , and after }7.Qb3 Qb6 8.c5 Qc7 { , our light-squared bishop could simply drop back }{ to  h7 . } )
8. axb3
8. Na6{ I like this move a lot. From  a6 , the knight stops  b3 - b4  for the moment, and it can drop back to  c7  (stopping a future  b4 - b5 ), or leap forward to  b4 , depending on the circumstances. }( { Let's see how easy it is to get in trouble in this endgame: }8...Be7 9.b4 O-O 10.Bf4 ( { The immediate }10.b5 cxb5 11.Nxb5 Nc6! { is excellent for Black, so White should be patient in executing }{ the  b4 - b5  push. Timing is of the essence! } )10...Ne4 { was played by French top GM Etienne Bacrot recently. Now }11.Rg1!! h6 { ( }11...h5 12.h3! { doesn't }{ stop  g3 - g4  either. }{ )   }12.g4 Bh7 13.h4 { would have given White a serious initiative.    Better is   }10...Nbd7 { , but I still like White's position after }11.h3!? h6 12.g4 Bh7 13.e3 a6 14.Rg1!? { or }14.Nd2 { . Black doesn't have a clear plan, while White has many ways to improve the position further. } )
9. Bf4( { While this move seems to stop only ... Na6 - c7 , it also stops the jump to  b4 . After }9...Nb4 10.Ra4 a5 11.Bg2 { (or the immediate }11.Bc7 { )   }11...Be7 12.O-O O-O 13.Bc7 { , White is better. } )
9. Ne4{ Now ... Na6 - b4  is a real threat since  c2  is a soft spot, and so is  f2 . }
10. Rxa6{ A remarkable suggestion by the engine! White hopes to exploit the weaknesses created on  a6  and  c6 , even at the cost of an exchange. }
10. bxa6
11. e3{ This is too slow and meets a swift refutation. }
11. g5
12. Nxg5
12. Nxg5
13. Bxg5
13. Rb8{ We take on  b3  next, with a winning game. }
