9. Bc2
10. Bg2{ The fastest way to bring the  h1 -rook into the game, as White intends to castle kingside. }( 10.Nd2 Be7 { leaves White completely tied up. } )
10. Bxb3( 10...Nd7!? { is very playable as well. The idea is to quickly }{ push ... e6 - e5 . } )
11. Ra3
11. Bc2
12. O-O{ A moment of great caution! White wants to play  Bc1 - f4  next, then  Rf1 - c1 , and when the bishop moves,  Ra3 - b3 , after which our queenside crumbles. That means we can't play it slow here. }( { The sample line }12...Be7 13.Bf4 O-O 14.Ne5 { illustrates the above line. Black is completely stuck. For instance, }14...Rfc8 15.Rc1 Bf5 16.Rb3 { , and it's already over. } )( 12.Bf4 Nd7! 13.O-O f6 { will transpose to  12.O-O . } )
12. Nd7
13. Bf4
13. f6{ This is the key idea. Black is aiming for direct counterplay in the center. }
14. Rfa1( 14.Rc1 { is not very effective here, as our counterplay comes right on time. }14...Bf5 15.Rb3 e5! 16.dxe5 Naxc5 { and Black is winning already. } )
14. e5
15. Bd2( { Obviously, }15.dxe5 Bxc5 { is excellent for Black. } )
15. Rb8( { A fantastic prophylactic measure. It no longer seems that mysterious if we look at the line }15...Ndxc5 16.dxc5 Bxc5 17.Ra5 Bb4 { , when }18.Rxa6! bxa6 19.Nxd5! { leads to a won game. }{ With the rook on  b8 , Black would simply recapture on  d5  here. } )
16. e3{ With the inclusion of  15...Rb8 , we are now ready to capture on  c5 . }
16. Ndxc5
17. dxc5
17. Bxc5
18. Ra5
18. Bb4( { Now the tactics work out just fine for Black. White is forced to give up the exchange, either on  a6  or after }19.R5a2 Bb3 { . } )
