6. Qb3{ After this move, we have no choice but to play the endgame. }
6. Qb6( 6...b6 { is obviously very ugly. Simply }7.Nh4 Be4 8.f3 { gives White an advantage. } )
7. c5
7. Qxb3( { Forced, as }7...Qc7 8.Bf4 Qc8 9.Nh4 { gives White a pleasant game. Our light-squared bishop is about to be traded off. This line immediately illustrates the big difference with   }6.Bg2 { . There we played }6...h6 { , and after }7.Qb3 Qb6 8.c5 Qc7 { , our light-squared bishop could simply drop back }{ to  h7 . } )
8. axb3
8. Na6{ I like this move a lot. From  a6 , the knight stops  b3 - b4  for the moment, and it can drop back to  c7  (stopping a future  b4 - b5 ), or leap forward to  b4 , depending on the circumstances. }( { Let's see how easy it is to get in trouble in this endgame: }8...Be7 9.b4 O-O 10.Bf4 ( { The immediate }10.b5 cxb5 11.Nxb5 Nc6! { is excellent for Black, so White should be patient in executing }{ the  b4 - b5  push. Timing is of the essence! } )10...Ne4 { was played by French top GM Etienne Bacrot recently. Now }11.Rg1!! h6 { ( }11...h5 12.h3! { doesn't }{ stop  g3 - g4  either. }{ )   }12.g4 Bh7 13.h4 { would have given White a serious initiative.    Better is   }10...Nbd7 { , but I still like White's position after }11.h3!? h6 12.g4 Bh7 13.e3 a6 14.Rg1!? { or }14.Nd2 { . Black doesn't have a clear plan, while White has many ways to improve the position further. } )
9. Ra4{ Not just preventing a knight jump to  b4 , but also preparing the  b3 - b4  advance. This direction was suggested by Srinath Narayanan in his Lifetime Repertoire on the Catalan. He rightly asserts that this line is relatively unexplored yet very interesting. }
9. Bc2
10. Bg2{ The fastest way to bring the  h1 -rook into the game, as White intends to castle kingside. }( 10.Nd2 Be7 { leaves White completely tied up. } )
10. Bxb3( 10...Nd7!? { is very playable as well. The idea is to quickly }{ push ... e6 - e5 . } )
11. Ra3
11. Bc2
12. O-O{ A moment of great caution! White wants to play  Bc1 - f4  next, then  Rf1 - c1 , and when the bishop moves,  Ra3 - b3 , after which our queenside crumbles. That means we can't play it slow here. }( { The sample line }12...Be7 13.Bf4 O-O 14.Ne5 { illustrates the above line. Black is completely stuck. For instance, }14...Rfc8 15.Rc1 Bf5 16.Rb3 { , and it's already over. } )( 12.Bf4 Nd7! 13.O-O f6 { will transpose to  12.O-O . } )
12. Nd7
13. Bf4
13. f6{ This is the key idea. Black is aiming for direct counterplay in the center. }
14. Rfa1( 14.Rc1 { is not very effective here, as our counterplay comes right on time. }14...Bf5 15.Rb3 e5! 16.dxe5 Naxc5 { and Black is winning already. } )
14. e5
15. Bd2( { Obviously, }15.dxe5 Bxc5 { is excellent for Black. } )
15. Rb8( { A fantastic prophylactic measure. It no longer seems that mysterious if we look at the line }15...Ndxc5 16.dxc5 Bxc5 17.Ra5 Bb4 { , when }18.Rxa6! bxa6 19.Nxd5! { leads to a won game. }{ With the rook on  b8 , Black would simply recapture on  d5  here. } )
16. Nd1( { Preparing for the knight sacrifice on  c5  and also introducing the idea of  b2 - b4 . Now }16...Ndxc5 17.dxc5 Bxc5 18.Rc3 { is promising for White, though obviously still a very complicated position. } )
16. Bxd1( { The most clear-cut, but }16...Be4 { is certainly worth a shot as well. }16...exd4 { is likely to transpose after }17.b4 Bxd1 18.Rxd1 { . } )
17. Rxd1
17. exd4
18. b4
18. Ne5
19. Nxd4
19. Nxc5{ An excellent and absolutely necessary piece sacrifice. White was threatening  f2 - f4  followed by taking on  a6  and  c6 . }
20. bxc5{ Other moves aren't very critical. }
20. Bxc5
21. Ra4
21. b5{ The final point, winning back the sacrificed piece. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "31) Slav 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 c6 4.g3 − 6.Bg2 and 6.Qb3"]
[Black "Slav 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 c6 4.g3 − 6.Qb3 #11"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. c4
3. c6
4. g3( { After }4.Nc3 dxc4 5.g3 { , }{ this is the next  g3  setup we will be reviewing. We will also have a look at }{   }1.d4 d5 2.g3 { and   }1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 { . All these variations are, of course, closely intertwined, and it is recommended to make a careful study of them so as not to confuse the move orders. } )
4. Bf5{ In the same style as before. If possible, we always want to develop the  c8 -bishop before playing ... e7 - e6 . }
5. Nc3( 5.Bg2 e6 6.Nc3 { would transpose to  5.Nc3  after }6...h6 { . } )
5. e6
6. Qb3{ After this move, we have no choice but to play the endgame. }
6. Qb6( 6...b6 { is obviously very ugly. Simply }7.Nh4 Be4 8.f3 { gives White an advantage. } )
7. c5
7. Qxb3( { Forced, as }7...Qc7 8.Bf4 Qc8 9.Nh4 { gives White a pleasant game. Our light-squared bishop is about to be traded off. This line immediately illustrates the big difference with   }6.Bg2 { . There we played }6...h6 { , and after }7.Qb3 Qb6 8.c5 Qc7 { , our light-squared bishop could simply drop back }{ to  h7 . } )
8. axb3
8. Na6{ I like this move a lot. From  a6 , the knight stops  b3 - b4  for the moment, and it can drop back to  c7  (stopping a future  b4 - b5 ), or leap forward to  b4 , depending on the circumstances. }( { Let's see how easy it is to get in trouble in this endgame: }8...Be7 9.b4 O-O 10.Bf4 ( { The immediate }10.b5 cxb5 11.Nxb5 Nc6! { is excellent for Black, so White should be patient in executing }{ the  b4 - b5  push. Timing is of the essence! } )10...Ne4 { was played by French top GM Etienne Bacrot recently. Now }11.Rg1!! h6 { ( }11...h5 12.h3! { doesn't }{ stop  g3 - g4  either. }{ )   }12.g4 Bh7 13.h4 { would have given White a serious initiative.    Better is   }10...Nbd7 { , but I still like White's position after }11.h3!? h6 12.g4 Bh7 13.e3 a6 14.Rg1!? { or }14.Nd2 { . Black doesn't have a clear plan, while White has many ways to improve the position further. } )
9. Ra4{ Not just preventing a knight jump to  b4 , but also preparing the  b3 - b4  advance. This direction was suggested by Srinath Narayanan in his Lifetime Repertoire on the Catalan. He rightly asserts that this line is relatively unexplored yet very interesting. }
9. Bc2
10. Ne5( { From a practical point of view, probably the most dangerous move since it involves an exchange sacrifice (after }10...Nd7 11.Rxa6!? { ) that we can't avoid and leads to serious complications. } )( { After }10.Ne5 { , White threatens }{ to take on  c6  and  a6  (not necessarily in that order), meaning we have no time for }10...Bxb3 11.Ra3 Bc2 12.Rxa6! bxa6 13.Nxc6 { , with excellent compensation for the exchange. The locked nature of the game means that it's hard for Black to make something of the extra material. } )
10. Nd7{ Aiming for an improved version of the variation above. }
11. Nxd7{ This should come as a relief. Obviously, taking on  a6  is far more critical. }
11. Kxd7
12. e4( { Remarkably, after a move like }12.Bf4 { , we could even go }12...Nxc5!? 13.dxc5 Bxc5 { , }{ when  b3  is also bound to fall, with an approximately equal game. } )
12. Bxb3( 12...dxe4!? { could be considered as well. } )
13. Ra3
13. Bc4
14. exd5
14. cxd5
15. Bxc4
15. dxc4
16. Ra4{ White finally wins back the sacrificed pawn but allows Black to set up a powerful blockade. }
16. Nc7{ The knight will come to  d5 , with comfortable equality. }
