2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. c4
3. c6
4. g3( { After }4.Nc3 dxc4 5.g3 { , }{ this is the next  g3  setup we will be reviewing. We will also have a look at }{   }1.d4 d5 2.g3 { and   }1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 { . All these variations are, of course, closely intertwined, and it is recommended to make a careful study of them so as not to confuse the move orders. } )
4. Bf5{ In the same style as before. If possible, we always want to develop the  c8 -bishop before playing ... e7 - e6 . }
5. Nc3( 5.Bg2 e6 6.Nc3 { would  transpose  to  5.Nc3  after }6...h6 { . } )
5. e6
6. Nh4{ This is why the move order that postpones  Bg2  is interesting, as it gives White the option to chase the bishop. }
6. dxc4{ This is popular as well, but I am not a huge fan. }
7. Nxf5
7. exf5
8. e3( { We have a slightly worse version of the so-called Bled Attack, which arises after   }1.d4 d5 2.c4 c6 3.Nf3 Nf6 4.Nc3 dxc4 5.a4 Bf5 6.Nh4 e6 7.Nxf5 exf5 8.e3 { . As we can see, the difference is that White's pawns }{ are on  g3  instead of  g2 , and on  a2  instead of  a4 . Having the pawn on  a2  is definitely a plus for White. }{    The reason   }5.a4 { is played, is to avoid  5...b5 , which would happen after }5.e4 { . }{ But after taking back the pawn on  c4 , White would love to place the pawn back on  a2 / a3 , not to weaken the  b4 -square. Having the pawn on  g3 , however, is not harmful at all, which makes for an easy conclusion: White is better off in the variation at hand than in the Bled Attack. } )
8. Nbd7( 8...b5 9.Bg2 { is too dangerous. } )( 8...Bd6 { is a decent alternative, not yet focusing on getting a knight }{ on  d5  but remaining a bit more flexible instead. I think this is very playable, and a critical direction is }9.Bxc4 O-O 10.Qf3 g6 ( 10...Qd7 11.h3 Na6 { would transpose to the earlier mentioned  Bled Attack  }{ but with the pawn on  a2 , instead of  a4 ! That means White won't go }12.g4 Nb4! { but simply   }12.a3! { with a better game. } )11.h3 { with the idea to break open the position }{ with  g3 - g4  next. A typical procedure in this line. The engine indicates }11...Qe7 12.g4 c5 13.O-O ( 13.gxf5 cxd4 14.Nd5 Nxd5 15.Bxd5 Nc6 { is quite attractive for Black, as White is somewhat underdeveloped. } )13...Nc6 14.Rd1 { and gives White a small plus. I tend to agree, though }14...fxg4 15.hxg4 Rad8 { certainly doesn't look bad for Black. } )
9. Bxc4
9. Nb6
10. Bb3{ We reach a position that has been seen in a couple of dozen high-level games. Engines aren't that unhappy here but White has a long-term advantage in the two bishops. }
10. Qd7( 10...Be7 11.O-O O-O 12.f3! { followed by  e3 - e4 , looks worse. } )
11. f3{ This gives White good hopes for an edge. The correspondence game Langeveld-Tleptsko, 2020 was eventually drawn after: }
11. h5
12. Bd2
12. h4
13. gxh4( 13.g4!? fxg4 14.fxg4 Qxg4 15.Qxg4 Nxg4 16.O-O Nf6 17.e4 O-O-O! { is not so clear because of }18.e5 Rxd4!  )
13. a5
14. a3
14. Nbd5( { With   }13.g4!? { in the line above in mind, I would propose   }12.Qe2 { . The idea becomes clear after }12...h4 13.g4 fxg4 14.fxg4 Qxg4 15.Qxg4 Nxg4 16.O-O Nf6 17.e4 { , when }17...O-O-O 18.e5 Rxd4 { is no longer possible: }{ there is no bishop on  d2 ! }{ This is by no means a full overview of   }6...dxc4 { , but I hope I got the point across that I think White has the better time in this variation. } )
