17. Ne8( 17...Bd8 18.Bd6 Re8 { , }{ preparing ... Bd8 - e7  is fine as well. The text move is more ambitious. } )
18. Bb6
18. Nxb6
19. Nxb6
19. Rd8{ The ... b7 - b6  break is no longer on the cards, but we have managed to exchange one of White's bishops. Next up we will regroup to try and get ... e6 - e5  in. }
20. a3
20. Bf6
21. b4
21. Qb8{ Threatening to push the e-pawn. }
22. f4( 22.bxa5 { allows us to illustrate the positional idea: }22...e5 23.e3 Nc7 { , when White is a pawn up but struggles to keep the structure together. }{ The pawn on  a5  is weak and so is the one on  d4 , which needs constant protection. Black is slightly better. } )
22. g5{ A very annoying move for White to face. The simple idea is to take on  f4 , play ... g7 - g6 , and bring our knight into the game via  g7  to  f5 . }
23. e3
23. gxf4
24. gxf4
24. axb4
25. axb4
25. Qc7{ Prophylaxis against  Ra1 - a8 . Next up we are set to bring the knight to  f5 . }
