[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "32) Slav 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 c6 4.g3 − 6.Nh4"]
[Black "Slav 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c4 c6 4.g3 − 6.Nh4 #19"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. c4
3. c6
4. g3( { After }4.Nc3 dxc4 5.g3 { , }{ this is the next  g3  setup we will be reviewing. We will also have a look at }{   }1.d4 d5 2.g3 { and   }1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.g3 { . All these variations are, of course, closely intertwined, and it is recommended to make a careful study of them so as not to confuse the move orders. } )
4. Bf5{ In the same style as before. If possible, we always want to develop the  c8 -bishop before playing ... e7 - e6 . }
5. Nc3( 5.Bg2 e6 6.Nc3 { would  transpose  to  5.Nc3  after }6...h6 { . } )
5. e6
6. Nh4{ This is why the move order that postpones  Bg2  is interesting, as it gives White the option to chase the bishop. }
6. Be4{ There is no avoiding the trade of our bishop, but before doing so we first provoke some weaknesses in White's camp. }
7. f3
7. Bg6
8. Qb3( 8.Nxg6 hxg6 9.Qb3 { will transpose to  8.Qb3 . } )( { Another move is the overly ambitious }8.e4 { . We are happy to see such moves by our opponents, as it’s just too much. We reply }8...dxe4 9.Nxg6 { (otherwise, the e-pawn would simply be lost) }9...hxg6 10.fxe4 e5! { , and after the further }11.dxe5 Qxd1+ 12.Kxd1 Ng4 { , Black won back the pawn while securing a large positional advantage in Manko-Sedina, Leukerbad 2023. } )
8. Qd7( { See the  Informational  for the explanation on why we choose }8...Qd7 { over the endgame with }8...Qb6 { . } )
9. Nxg6( 9.Be3 Be7 10.Nxg6 hxg6 { transposes to the  9.Nxg6 move order . } )
9. hxg6
10. Be3( { Prophylaxis against }10...dxc4 11.Qxc4 b5 { , after which White }{ can retreat to  b3 , as  d4  is now covered. } )
10. Be7
11. Bg2
11. a5{ I like the timing of this move, which aims for queenside expansion. }
12. c5{ The most principled reply. Our a-pawn having moved to  a5  makes it harder to engineer a ... b7 - b6  break. }
12. Qc8{ Making sure our  b8 -knight is in position the moment White wants to play  Na4 - b6 . }
13. Na4
13. Nbd7{ Covering the  b6 -square. }
14. O-O
14. O-O{ A very complex strategic struggle lies ahead. There are two breaks in the position that we may be aiming for: ... b7 - b6  and ... e6 - e5 . We have to tread carefully though, as playing these breaks ill-timed could easily destroy our position. }
15. Bf4{ The most logical approach. White wants to play  e2 - e4  sooner or later and in the meantime, the bishop on  f4  covering  b8 , makes it hard for us to regroup. }
15. Nh5{ Challenging the bishop. If it leaves the  h2 - b8  diagonal, we will be able to regroup with ... Qc8 - c7 , preparing the ... e6 - e5  or ... b7 - b6  break. }
16. Be5
16. g5{ Structurally speaking, a very desirable move. We want to make sure White will never be able to repair the pawn structure by getting  f3 - f4  in. The position is double-edged, but the engine's '0.00' is a good starting point. }
