6. dxc5
6. Nxf4
7. exf4{ We are temporarily a pawn down, which is why I thought it is useful to know what we are doing here. }
7. e6
8. b4
8. a5( { The most played move is }8...Qf6 { , but I believe it is inaccurate. White has the strong }9.g3 { , when }9...Nxb4 { ( }9...a5 10.Qa4! Bd7 11.b5 Nb8 12.Qd4 { also doesn't fully equalize.)   }10.cxb4! Qxa1 11.Bb5+ Ke7 12.O-O { gives White excellent compensation for the exchange. Black's king }{ is very unhappy on  e7 . } )
9. Bb5{ Protecting the  b4 -pawn by pinning the knight. Our response is one to remember! }
9. axb4
10. cxb4
10. g5{ Reminding White about the vulnerability of the  a1 - h8  diagonal. }
11. fxg5( { After }11.Nc3 Bg7 12.Rc1 Ra3 { , we have excellent play, while   }11.Nxg5 Qf6 12.Nd2 Qxf4 { drops not just the  f4 -pawn, but, on the next move,  b4  as well. } )
11. Bg7
12. Nbd2
12. h6( { No need to be greedy just yet. Instead, }12...Bxa1 13.Qxa1 O-O 14.Bxc6 bxc6 15.O-O { is horrible for Black, as White's knights will find beautiful outposts }{ on  d4  and  e5 . } )
13. gxh6
13. Rxh6
14. O-O
14. e5{ Continuing the fight for the initiative rather than taking on  a1 . We want to simply push ... e5 - e4  next and, if the knight moves, give checkmate with ... Qd8 - h4 , etc. Black is two pawns down but already better! }
