2. c5( { Not only is this a fine way of countering  2.Bf4 , but the automatic }2...Nf6 { could run into }3.Nc3 { , which is a Jobava London. As we are meeting   }2.Nc3 { with }2...c5 { as well, this would be a repertoire issue. } )( { Note that }2...c6 { is a mistake. As a }{ general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  after White has played  c2 - c4 . Now, after }3.Nf3 { , we simply have a bad version of the London System. In this line, }{ we often want to play ... c7 - c5 , and having already played our pawn to  c6  that would mean losing time. } )
3. e3( { The most played move in the position, intending to meet }3...cxd4 { with }4.exd4 { , the so-called Carlsbad structure. } )( 3.Nc3 { would  transpose  to   }2.Nc3 c5 3.Bf4 { . } )
3. Nc6
4. Nf3{ Logical development obviously, yet it does give us the option of effectively developing our problem bishop on  c8 . }
4. Bg4
5. c3{ Setting up the typical London pawn formation and preparing  Qd1 - b3 . Now that our bishop has left  c8 , our queenside is a bit more vulnerable, so this plan makes sense. }
5. e6
6. Qb3
6. Qd7( { Not fearing any ghosts connected to  Bf1 - b5 . Worse would be }6...Qc8 7.Ne5 Nxe5 8.Bxe5 Ne7 9.Qa4+ Nc6 10.dxc5! { when we can't recapture }{ on  c5 . } )
7. Ne5
7. Nxe5
8. Bxe5
8. Ne7( { The difference with   }6...Qc8 { becomes clear right away. White has no  9.Qa4+ . } )
9. dxc5
9. Nc6{ A double attack on  e5  and  c5 . }
10. Qa4
10. Bh5
11. Bb5
11. f6( { Otherwise, after }11...Bxc5 { ,  g7  would be hanging. }{ After kicking back the bishop from  e5 , we are ready to take on  c5 , with a good game. } )
