[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "33) London System 2.Bf4"]
[Black "London System 2.Bf4 c5 3.e3 #6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4
2. c5( { Not only is this a fine way of countering  2.Bf4 , but the automatic }2...Nf6 { could run into }3.Nc3 { , which is a Jobava London. As we are meeting   }2.Nc3 { with }2...c5 { as well, this would be a repertoire issue. } )( { Note that }2...c6 { is a mistake. As a }{ general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  after White has played  c2 - c4 . Now, after }3.Nf3 { , we simply have a bad version of the London System. In this line, }{ we often want to play ... c7 - c5 , and having already played our pawn to  c6  that would mean losing time. } )
3. e3( { The most played move in the position, intending to meet }3...cxd4 { with }4.exd4 { , the so-called Carlsbad structure. } )( 3.Nc3 { would  transpose  to   }2.Nc3 c5 3.Bf4 { . } )
3. Nc6
4. c3{ Reaching the pawn structure that is so typical for the London System. If allowed, White intends to develop harmoniously with the knights going to  d2  and  f3  and the bishop to  d3 . }( { Having played   }2.Bf4 { though, instead of }2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 { , we have not yet developed }{ our  g8 -knight. That gives us some extra options. } )
4. Qb6{ A very effective way of meeting this setup. The threat of taking on  b2  ruins White's natural flow of development. }
5. Qc2{ The other queen move in the position. Now we will chase the  f4 -bishop. }
5. Nf6( { The enterprising }5...Bf5 { doesn't quite work because of }6.Qxf5 Qxb2 7.Qxd5 Qxa1 8.Qb3 { and Black is just lost. } )
6. Nd2
6. Nh5{ With the White queen on  d1 , this move wouldn't be available. One of the upsides of including  4... Qb6  5.Qc2 . We will grab the  f4 -bishop and have a good game. }
