6. Qc2
6. e5( { Against  6.Qc2  we have to play very energetically given the strategic danger that we face with the aforementioned  b2 - b3  that is coming. However, the immediate }6...Bf5 7.Qxf5! Qxb2 8.Qxd5 Qxa1 9.Qb5 { doesn't quite work for Black. That's why we play  6...e5!  first. } )
7. Bxe5{ Now that this bishop blocks the road to our  d5 -pawn, we can develop our bishop. }
7. Bf5
8. Qc1{ The most obvious square for the queen given that it would obstruct the  b1 -knight on  d2 . }
8. Nxe5
9. dxe5
9. f6{ Rather than winning back the pawn on  e5 , we sacrifice it and focus on swift development. }
10. exf6( { What else? Giving the pawn back with }10.e6 { gives us an easy game after for instance }10...Bc5 11.Nf3 Bxe6 12.Nbd2 f5 { and ... Ng8 - f6  next. } )
10. Nxf6
11. Nf3
11. Bc5
12. Be2
12. O-O
13. O-O{ In positions like these, I often feel the rush to show immediate compensation for the pawn. I really like how the engine treats this position. Black has various moves at this point, but none of them rush things and rather calmly strengthen the position. }
13. Qd6{ Simply intending expansion of the queenside with ... b7 - b5  but also eying the  h2 -square. }
14. Nbd2{ The most obvious move, finishing development. }
14. Ng4{ Very hard to face. }
15. h3
15. Nxf2
16. Rxf2( 16.Kxf2 Qf4! { is even worse. } )
16. Bxe3
17. Qe1
17. Qb6{ Reminding White that  b2  can be attacked as well. It is often the poor foot soldiers that perish first in battle. }
18. Nf1
18. Bxf2+
19. Qxf2
19. Qxb2{ With two pawns and rook for two pieces, we are doing fine. It's important that we still have an ongoing initiative and White's pieces aren't coordinating all that well yet. }
