4. c3{ Reaching the pawn structure that is so typical for the London System. If allowed, White intends to develop harmoniously with the knights going to  d2  and  f3  and the bishop to  d3 . }( { Having played   }2.Bf4 { though, instead of }2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 { , we have not yet developed }{ our  g8 -knight. That gives us some extra options. } )
4. Qb6{ A very effective way of meeting this setup. The threat of taking on  b2  ruins White's natural flow of development. }
5. Qb3( { Played in hundreds of games. White hopes for }5...Qxb3 6.axb3 { , which gives a pleasant endgame advantage. We don't mind exchanging queens but preferably, on our terms. } )
5. c4{ A good but at the same time very responsible move. Giving up the pressure in the center means we have to follow up in a very precise manner. Otherwise, a future  b2 - b3  will just ruin our pawn structure. }
6. Qc2
6. e5( { Against  6.Qc2  we have to play very energetically given the strategic danger that we face with the aforementioned  b2 - b3  that is coming. However, the immediate }6...Bf5 7.Qxf5! Qxb2 8.Qxd5 Qxa1 9.Qb5 { doesn't quite work for Black. That's why we play  6...e5!  first. } )
7. dxe5{ Blocking the way to our  d5 -pawn. That means White's defense as shown in the note after  6...e5 , is no longer available. }
7. Bf5
8. Qc1{ The most obvious square, not obstructing the  b1 -knight from reaching  d2 . }
8. g5( 8...f6 { is possible as well, but this is even more energetic. } )
9. Bg3
9. h5{ Grabbing more space and giving the bishop on  g3  no rest! }
10. h3
10. Bg7{ We can win back the  e5 -pawn when we feel like, and the lead in development will do the rest. }
