1. d4
1. d5
2. Bf4
2. c5( { Not only is this a fine way of countering  2.Bf4 , but the automatic }2...Nf6 { could run into }3.Nc3 { , which is a Jobava London. As we are meeting   }2.Nc3 { with }2...c5 { as well, this would be a repertoire issue. } )( { Note that }2...c6 { is a mistake. As a }{ general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  after White has played  c2 - c4 . Now, after }3.Nf3 { , we simply have a bad version of the London System. In this line, }{ we often want to play ... c7 - c5 , and having already played our pawn to  c6  that would mean losing time. } )
3. e3( { The most played move in the position, intending to meet }3...cxd4 { with }4.exd4 { , the so-called Carlsbad structure. } )( 3.Nc3 { would  transpose  to   }2.Nc3 c5 3.Bf4 { . } )
3. Nc6
4. c3{ Reaching the pawn structure that is so typical for the London System. If allowed, White intends to develop harmoniously with the knights going to  d2  and  f3  and the bishop to  d3 . }( { Having played   }2.Bf4 { though, instead of }2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 { , we have not yet developed }{ our  g8 -knight. That gives us some extra options. } )
4. Qb6{ A very effective way of meeting this setup. The threat of taking on  b2  ruins White's natural flow of development. }
5. Qb3( { Played in hundreds of games. White hopes for }5...Qxb3 6.axb3 { , which gives a pleasant endgame advantage. We don't mind exchanging queens but preferably, on our terms. } )
5. c4{ A good but at the same time very responsible move. Giving up the pressure in the center means we have to follow up in a very precise manner. Otherwise, a future  b2 - b3  will just ruin our pawn structure. }
6. Qc2
6. e5( { Against  6.Qc2  we have to play very energetically given the strategic danger that we face with the aforementioned  b2 - b3  that is coming. However, the immediate }6...Bf5 7.Qxf5! Qxb2 8.Qxd5 Qxa1 9.Qb5 { doesn't quite work for Black. That's why we play  6...e5!  first. } )
7. dxe5{ Blocking the way to our  d5 -pawn. That means White's defense as shown in the note after  6...e5 , is no longer available. }
7. Bf5
8. Qc1{ The most obvious square, not obstructing the  b1 -knight from reaching  d2 . }
8. g5( 8...f6 { is possible as well, but this is even more energetic. } )
9. Bxg5{ Accepting the challenge! }
9. Nxe5
10. Nd2
10. f6( { This move looked a bit odd to me at first, but it will soon start to make sense. The direct }10...Nd3+ { misses the mark after }11.Bxd3 Bxd3 12.Ne2 { , when White will slowly disentangle. }12...Qg6 13.Bf4 Qxg2 14.Rg1 Qh3 15.Qd1! { is excellent for White. } )
11. Bf4
11. Ne7( { This is the point! There is no rush at all. We simply ask White which piece will be developed next. If }12.Ngf3 { , there is }12...Nd3+ { and now the difference after }13.Bxd3 Bxd3 { becomes immediately apparent. We have excellent compensation because it is hard for White to finish development. } )( { The few games that reached this position continued with }12.Bxe5 fxe5 13.Ngf3 { , but after }13...Bg7 { , that obviously gives us great play for the pawn. } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "34) London System 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4"]
[Black "London System 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 − 5.dxc5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. Bf4
3. c5{ We play in the same way. Besides that what we are about to study is obviously theoretically sound, playing in the same way as against  2.Bf4  makes it easier on our memory. }
4. e3
4. Nc6
5. dxc5( { This is not very critical, and }5.c3 { transposes to the  2.Bf4 variation . } )
5. e6{ We simply recapture on  c5  next move and the net result of  5.dxc5  is that White loses central control. }
