[Black "London System 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 − 5.Be2"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. Bf4
3. c5{ We play in the same way. Besides that what we are about to study is obviously theoretically sound, playing in the same way as against  2.Bf4  makes it easier on our memory. }
4. e3
4. Nc6
5. Be2( { The idea behind this move is that one of the main setups, after }5...e6 6.O-O Bd6 { , now is a bit worse because of }7.dxc5! { , when }7...Bxc5 8.c4! { is better for White. }{ In this line, the  b1 -knight will go to  c3  and White hasn't lost any time pushing the c-pawn to  c4 . }{ My game against Huschenbeth in the German Bundesliga continued   }7...Bxf4 8.exf4 Qa5 9.Nbd2 Qxc5 10.Nb3 Qb6 11.c3 O-O 12.Bd3 Bd7 13.Qe2 { , with a pleasant edge. } )( { Another point of this order is that }5...Qb6 { is well met with }6.Nc3! { , as }6...Qxb2 7.Nb5 { is already bad. We want none of the above. } )( 5.c3 { transposes to the  2.Bf4 variation . } )
5. Bg4{ Simply developing the bishop. Next, we'd like to play ... e7 - e6  and bring the  f8 -bishop into the game. Chess can be a simple game! }
6. O-O( 6.Nbd2 e6 7.O-O { transposes. } )
6. e6
7. Nbd2
7. cxd4( { Before playing ... Bf8 - d6 , we first capture on  d4 . We do so because }7...Bd6 8.dxc5! Bxc5 9.c4 { gives White something to work with. } )
8. exd4
8. Bd6
9. Bxd6
9. Qxd6{ We will castle next, with an approximately equal game. }
