2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. Bf4
3. c5{ We play in the same way. Besides that what we are about to study is obviously theoretically sound, playing in the same way as against  2.Bf4  makes it easier on our memory. }
4. e3
4. Nc6
5. Nbd2( 5.c3 { transposes to the  2.Bf4 variation . } )
5. Bg4( { As I said, we play the exact same setup, but there is a twist. Compared to   }2.Bf4 c5 3.e3 Nc6 4.Nf3 Bg4 { , }{ we have the moves  Nb1 - d2  and  Ng8 - f6  included. As we will see, that makes a difference in some of the lines because we often kept the option of developing our  g8 -knight to  e7  in reserve. } )( { Black has plenty of other systems as well, of which }5...Qb6 6.dxc5 Qxb2 { , and   }5...Nh5 6.dxc5 Nxf4 7.exf4 g6 { are the frontrunners. They are both quite heavy on the memory though, and don't offer better chances than the line we choose. } )( { Throughout this course, we generally develop our bishop to  f5 , but this is an exception. After }5...Bf5 6.dxc5 e6 7.Nd4!? { , we are forced to accept a weakening of our structure, as }7...Bg6 8.Bb5! { leads to trouble. The position after   }7...Bxc5 8.Nxf5 exf5 9.c3 { isn't that bad for Black, but I feel it does give White something to work with. That's why, }{ I prefer the development to  g4 . } )
6. c3
6. e6
7. Qb3{ The main question, trying to make something happen on the queenside while we are not fully developed yet and our light-squared bishop is away from home. }
7. Qc8( { A very important moment! If you recall, after   }2.Bf4 c5 3.e3 Nc6 4.Nf3 Bg4 5.c3 e6 6.Qb3 { , we went }6...Qd7 { , avoiding }6...Qc8?! 7.Ne5! { , with an advantage for White. } )( { Here it's the other way around, which is why I would urge the reader to make good note of this − it is easy to mix up! With the moves  Nb1 - d2  and ... Ng8 - f6  included, }7...Qd7?! 8.Bb5 { is dangerous for Black. } )
8. Bb5( { Threatening, after for instance }8...Be7 { , to follow up with }9.Ne5 { . } )( 8.Nh4 Bh5 9.h3 { transposes to the  8.h3 variation . } )
8. Nd7{ Very effective. Suddenly White's play comes to a total standstill. }
9. O-O
9. Be7{ Castling kingside is up next, when we are fully mobilized. }
