10. dxc5( { The only critical direction, as the slow }10.O-O O-O { allows us to finish our development and doesn't ask any questions. } )
10. Nd7{ New, but favored by engines. }( 10...Bxc5 11.g4! Bg6 12.Nh4 { as in Giri-Tari, Stavanger 2022, gains the bishop pair under supposed favorable circumstances. In fact, diving a bit deeper, }12...Bb6! { (Aryan played }12...Qd7?! { )   }13.O-O-O Bc7 { challenges White's bishop }{ on  f4 , and isn't that bad for Black. It's not going to be my recommendation though, as 'not that bad' isn't what we should be aiming for here. } )( { Another way of delaying the recapture of the  c5 -pawn is }10...O-O { , but now }11.g4 Bg6 12.h4!? { as in Van Foreest-Eljanov, Linares 2022, looks attractive for White. } )
11. Bd6{ After most other moves, we just capture on  c5  with the knight. }
11. Nxc5
12. Bxc5
12. Bxc5
13. c4{ Without this move, the whole sequence wouldn't make sense. In the long term, we are doing fine with our two bishops, but we haven't completely finished our development yet and White tries to take advantage of that by opening up the position. }
13. Bxf3( { I strongly dislike }13...dxc4 14.Qb5! { , when we are faced with some tactical issues. }14...Bxf3 { is the only move, but now }15.Bxf3 Be7 16.Nxc4 { gives White a very pleasant }{ edge.  Bxc6  is incoming, ruining our pawn structure and creating a typical good knight versus bad bishop scenario. Black is not lost, but prolonged suffering is guaranteed! } )
14. Bxf3( 14.Nxf3 { would allow }14...d4!  )
14. d4
15. Qb5
15. Be7( { Black is super close to completely equalizing after }15...dxe3 16.Qxc5 exd2+ 17.Kxd2 { but not quite. For instance, after }17...Qd8+ 18.Ke3 Qb6 19.Qxb6 axb6 20.a4!? { , or   }17...Qd7+ 18.Kc3 Rc8 19.Rhd1 Qe7 20.Bxc6+ Rxc6 21.Qxe7+ Kxe7 22.Rd4 { , White keeps some small pressure in the endgame. With  15...Be7  we temporarily sacrifice a pawn. } )
16. exd4
16. O-O{ Threatening to capture on  d4 . White needs to bend over backwards to protect that pawn. }
17. Bxc6{ Logical as well, to eliminate the attacker. }
17. bxc6
18. Qa4
18. Rb8
19. Rb1
19. Bb4{ The king doesn't get to leave the center. Black has fine compensation. }
