5. Bg4( { As I said, we play the exact same setup, but there is a twist. Compared to   }2.Bf4 c5 3.e3 Nc6 4.Nf3 Bg4 { , }{ we have the moves  Nb1 - d2  and  Ng8 - f6  included. As we will see, that makes a difference in some of the lines because we often kept the option of developing our  g8 -knight to  e7  in reserve. } )( { Black has plenty of other systems as well, of which }5...Qb6 6.dxc5 Qxb2 { , and   }5...Nh5 6.dxc5 Nxf4 7.exf4 g6 { are the frontrunners. They are both quite heavy on the memory though, and don't offer better chances than the line we choose. } )( { Throughout this course, we generally develop our bishop to  f5 , but this is an exception. After }5...Bf5 6.dxc5 e6 7.Nd4!? { , we are forced to accept a weakening of our structure, as }7...Bg6 8.Bb5! { leads to trouble. The position after   }7...Bxc5 8.Nxf5 exf5 9.c3 { isn't that bad for Black, but I feel it does give White something to work with. That's why, }{ I prefer the development to  g4 . } )
6. c3
6. e6
7. Qb3{ The main question, trying to make something happen on the queenside while we are not fully developed yet and our light-squared bishop is away from home. }
7. Qc8( { A very important moment! If you recall, after   }2.Bf4 c5 3.e3 Nc6 4.Nf3 Bg4 5.c3 e6 6.Qb3 { , we went }6...Qd7 { , avoiding }6...Qc8?! 7.Ne5! { , with an advantage for White. } )( { Here it's the other way around, which is why I would urge the reader to make good note of this − it is easy to mix up! With the moves  Nb1 - d2  and ... Ng8 - f6  included, }7...Qd7?! 8.Bb5 { is dangerous for Black. } )
8. h3( 8.Nh4 Bh5 9.h3 { transposes to the  8.h3 variation . } )
8. Bh5( { Whilst }8...Bxf3 9.Nxf3 a6 { isn't that bad, I see no point in giving up the bishop pair without any reason. } )
9. Be2
9. Be7( { The typical }9...c4 10.Qd1 b5 { can be considered as well, though it seems like Black is committing to this a bit too early in this version. } )
10. dxc5( { The only critical direction, as the slow }10.O-O O-O { allows us to finish our development and doesn't ask any questions. } )
10. Nd7{ New, but favored by engines. }( 10...Bxc5 11.g4! Bg6 12.Nh4 { as in Giri-Tari, Stavanger 2022, gains the bishop pair under supposed favorable circumstances. In fact, diving a bit deeper, }12...Bb6! { (Aryan played }12...Qd7?! { )   }13.O-O-O Bc7 { challenges White's bishop }{ on  f4 , and isn't that bad for Black. It's not going to be my recommendation though, as 'not that bad' isn't what we should be aiming for here. } )( { Another way of delaying the recapture of the  c5 -pawn is }10...O-O { , but now }11.g4 Bg6 12.h4!? { as in Van Foreest-Eljanov, Linares 2022, looks attractive for White. } )
11. Bd6{ After most other moves, we just capture on  c5  with the knight. }
11. Nxc5
12. Bxc5
12. Bxc5
13. c4{ Without this move, the whole sequence wouldn't make sense. In the long term, we are doing fine with our two bishops, but we haven't completely finished our development yet and White tries to take advantage of that by opening up the position. }
13. Bxf3( { I strongly dislike }13...dxc4 14.Qb5! { , when we are faced with some tactical issues. }14...Bxf3 { is the only move, but now }15.Bxf3 Be7 16.Nxc4 { gives White a very pleasant }{ edge.  Bxc6  is incoming, ruining our pawn structure and creating a typical good knight versus bad bishop scenario. Black is not lost, but prolonged suffering is guaranteed! } )
14. Bxf3( 14.Nxf3 { would allow }14...d4!  )
14. d4
15. Qb5
15. Be7( { Black is super close to completely equalizing after }15...dxe3 16.Qxc5 exd2+ 17.Kxd2 { but not quite. For instance, after }17...Qd8+ 18.Ke3 Qb6 19.Qxb6 axb6 20.a4!? { , or   }17...Qd7+ 18.Kc3 Rc8 19.Rhd1 Qe7 20.Bxc6+ Rxc6 21.Qxe7+ Kxe7 22.Rd4 { , White keeps some small pressure in the endgame. With  15...Be7  we temporarily sacrifice a pawn. } )
16. exd4
16. O-O{ Threatening to capture on  d4 . White needs to bend over backwards to protect that pawn. }
17. Nb3
17. a5{ Not giving the knight any rest, now ... a5 - a4  is on the cards. }
18. Rd1
18. a4
19. Nc5
19. Nxd4{ This small tactic immediately forces equality. }
20. Rxd4
20. Qxc5
21. Rd7
21. Rab8{ Triple zeros. }
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "35) Torre Attack 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5"]
[Black "Torre Attack 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bg5 Ne4 4.Bf4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. Bg5{ A tricky little sideline that has been used repeatedly in rapid and blitz by the likes of Vladimir Kramnik and Alexander Grischuk. If we know what we are doing, the line isn't too worrisome. There are in fact many ways for Black to play. }
3. Ne4{ The most obvious reply, as White will have to spend additional time moving the bishop now. }
4. Bf4{ Somewhat surprisingly, this is the most played move in the position, but the retreat to  h4  is more venomous, as it hinders our development; the  e7 -pawn is pinned meaning we have to spend some additional time to get the kingside into the game.    Essentially, what we have on the board now is a London System where Black has made the extra move ... Nf6 - e4 . While White will try to prove that the knight is overextended, I believe it is hard to do so. On the contrary,  e4  is a nice, active post for the knight. }
4. c5{ Consistent with the previous move, fighting for the initiative. }
5. c3{ Played in hundreds of games, yet already passing the advantage to Black. }
5. cxd4
6. Bxb8
6. Rxb8
7. Qxd4{ Something we will see more often in this chapter, but here it's not a particularly successful strategy for White. }
7. e6{ Preparing to bring the bishop out to  c5 . }
8. Qxa7
8. Bd7{ There is no stopping ... Bf8 - c5  with decisive threats. }
