1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. Bg5{ A tricky little sideline that has been used repeatedly in rapid and blitz by the likes of Vladimir Kramnik and Alexander Grischuk. If we know what we are doing, the line isn't too worrisome. There are in fact many ways for Black to play. }
3. Ne4{ The most obvious reply, as White will have to spend additional time moving the bishop now. }
4. Bf4{ Somewhat surprisingly, this is the most played move in the position, but the retreat to  h4  is more venomous, as it hinders our development; the  e7 -pawn is pinned meaning we have to spend some additional time to get the kingside into the game.    Essentially, what we have on the board now is a London System where Black has made the extra move ... Nf6 - e4 . While White will try to prove that the knight is overextended, I believe it is hard to do so. On the contrary,  e4  is a nice, active post for the knight. }
4. c5{ Consistent with the previous move, fighting for the initiative. }
5. e3
5. Nc6( 5...Qb6 { is a more direct alternative. White should play }6.Nc3 { and now I am not sure about recommending either }6...Qa5 7.Bb5+ Bd7 8.Bxd7+ Nxd7 9.O-O cxd4 10.exd4 Nxc3 11.bxc3 Qxc3 12.Rb1 { , which is pretty forced and leaves us far behind in development, nor   }6...Nxc3 7.bxc3 Qa5 8.Qd2 { , which is also a pretty tricky position in a strategic sense. } )( { After }5...Nc6 { , }6.Nc3 Qa5! { of course no longer makes any sense. } )
6. c3{ Most often played and a logical solidification of White's pawn structure. }
6. Qb6
7. Qb3{ A typical situation in these types of structures. The queens are having a staredown. }
7. c4{ Always a big decision, as it releases the pressure on White's center. In this case, as we are about to see, the decision is justified though. }
8. Qc2( { The endgame after }8.Qxb6 axb6 { is pleasant for Black. When given the chance, we }{ will play ... b6 - b5 - b4 , and otherwise, we just finish development with ... Bc8 - f5  and ... e7 - e6 . } )
8. Bf5{ Threatening the queen on  c2  once again and bringing the bishop out before playing ... e7 - e6 , which is a typical thing to do. }( { A scenario to avoid would be }8...e6 9.Nbd2 Nxd2 10.Nxd2 Be7 11.b3! { , when our bishop is stuck }{ on  c8  and we are forced to take on  b3 , which is a big structural concession. } )
9. Qc1{ This is a mistake, but a far from obvious one! The refutation is pretty. }
9. e5( { Not very subtle! However White captures on  e5 , trouble awaits. This is a good moment to point out that even on move 8, the move   }8...e5 { was possible, but in the current position, the timing is perfect. } )
10. dxe5{ This gives up the  c5 -square, which we will not hesitate to use. }
10. Nc5{ The knight will land on  d3  next, and after a capture of the  f1 -bishop, our bishop will take over the role. That monster on  d3  fully compensates for the missing pawn − even more so! }
