2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. Bg5{ A tricky little sideline that has been used repeatedly in rapid and blitz by the likes of Vladimir Kramnik and Alexander Grischuk. If we know what we are doing, the line isn't too worrisome. There are in fact many ways for Black to play. }
3. Ne4{ The most obvious reply, as White will have to spend additional time moving the bishop now. }
4. Bh4{ The most tricky move to meet, as it hampers our development; the  e7 -pawn is pinned meaning we have to spend some additional time to get the kingside into the game. }
4. c5{ The most obvious move, and one that is easiest on our memory. Black has some hilarious alternatives though that deserve mentioning. }( { What to think about the move }4...Qd6!? { , which sets a nice trap? If White plays }5.e3 { , there follows }5...Qh6! { threatening ... g7 - g5 . }{ Better is   }5.Nbd2 { , but still }5...Qh6 { is there, }{ threatening ... g7 - g5  once again. }{ Following }6.Qc1! { , which prevents Black's threat, the game is very unclear. } )( { Even more extravagant is }4...h5!? { , }{ which prepares ... f7 - f6  and ... g7 - g5  to go after the bishop. It is not that simple for White to meet this move. I won't go into too much detail here, but I do want to point out the line }5.e3 f6 6.Ng1!? g5 7.f3 gxh4 8.fxe4 dxe4 { and who knows what's going on?! } )
5. dxc5{ Played surprisingly often. Black has many good replies. }
5. Na6{ Preparing to capture on  c5  with the knight. We have an easy game. }
