1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. c3{ Whilst this obviously doesn't refute our repertoire, it's worth a look. We have a wide range of options at this point, but I like to stay close to our repertoire and develop the bishop. }
3. Bf5( { Simple chess. In the London, after   }1.d4 d5 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.Bf4 { , it is known that }3...c6?! { is not very accurate. With reversed colors, this position is now on the board and the only question is whether having the first move, White can make anything of this position. } )
4. Qb3{ The only move that puts any pressure. After others, we just continue developing and have an easy game. }
4. Qc8( { I mentioned the pawn sacrifice }4...e6 5.Qxb7 Nbd7 { in our  analysis  of the move  2.c3 , and I am not too fond of this pawn sacrifice. The queen will return }{ to  d1  and the onus will be on us to show compensation. } )
5. c4{ A specialty of the Iranian GM Tabatabaei. Now that the queen has left  d8 , White attacks the center and tries to induce a capture on  c4 . }
5. c6( { Keeping the structure intact. Instead, }5...dxc4 6.Qxc4 e6 7.Nc3 { gives White some hope for an advantage. } )
6. Bg5
6. Ne4( { Jorden van Foreest played }6...dxc4 7.Qxc4 { before }{ playing ... Ne4 , but I believe there is no reason to take on  c4  first. After }{   }6...Ne4 { , we just want to capture the bishop }{ on  g5 , and if it moves, play ... e7 - e6 , with an easy game. } )
7. cxd5
7. cxd5
8. Qxd5{ Losing on the spot. }
8. Nxg5
9. Nxg5
9. Qc1{ The point, and the reason why taking on  c4  isn't necessary! }
