1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. e3{ The Colle System − once a way to avoid opening theory and just play chess. These days though (small) advantages are sought in even the most remote areas, given that the main lines don't guarantee much either. Therefore, even in the Colle, some theory has already been amassing over time.    Last but not least, in his World Championship match against Ian Nepomniachtchi, Ding Liren used the Colle, so it is a system that shouldn't be underestimated. }
3. Bf5( { At first, I felt a bit bad about this recommendation. Isn't this a bit lazy, simply trying to transpose to the Slow Slav after }4.c4 c6? { However, it's not as if other 3rd moves 'refute' White's setup, which is solid in nature. } )( { Why then, for the occasional game where our opponent plays the Colle, would we burden our memory even more? After }3...c5 { , arguably the most principled move, White has a wide range of setups to choose from. Vincent Keymer has recently been experimenting with }4.Be2 Nc6 5.c3 { , with reasonable success. White can also choose a }{ different setup with  b2 - b3  followed by  Bc1 - b2 , and each one asks Black some slightly different questions. } )( { I think it's much more practical to simply ignore all of it, play }3...Bf5 { , and transpose into positions that are the core of our repertoire and that we are very familiar with. } )
4. c4{ As mentioned, this is the best move but takes us away from the Colle System. }
4. c6{ Transposing to the chapters on the  Slow Slav . }
