11. Bb4( { The complications after }11...Rg8 12.Nxh4 Ne4 13.Nxd5 g5 { are super interesting, yet very uncalled for. Following }14.f3 Ng3 15.Nf6 Qe6 16.Nxf5! { , White at the very least wards off any attack. Developing the bishop }{ to  b4  instead is very sound. } )
12. Ne2{ The idea is to trap the bishop with  c4 - c5  followed by  a2 - a3  and  b3 - b4 . }
12. Ne4{ Falling for it! }
13. c5
13. g5( { An extremely serious attack is coming White's way. For instance }14.a3 g4 15.Nh2 gxh3 16.axb4 Rdg8 { is just crushing. White's best is }14.Nxg5 Nxg5 15.a3 { , and now }15...Bxc5 16.dxc5 Rhg8 { is approximately equal according to engines. While that may be the case, I think most human beings would prefer playing with the black pieces here. } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "36) 2.Nf3 Nf6 − 3rd Move Sidelines"]
[Black "Sidelines 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.e3 #7"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. e3{ The Colle System − once a way to avoid opening theory and just play chess. These days though (small) advantages are sought in even the most remote areas, given that the main lines don't guarantee much either. Therefore, even in the Colle, some theory has already been amassing over time.    Last but not least, in his World Championship match against Ian Nepomniachtchi, Ding Liren used the Colle, so it is a system that shouldn't be underestimated. }
3. Bf5( { At first, I felt a bit bad about this recommendation. Isn't this a bit lazy, simply trying to transpose to the Slow Slav after }4.c4 c6? { However, it's not as if other 3rd moves 'refute' White's setup, which is solid in nature. } )( { Why then, for the occasional game where our opponent plays the Colle, would we burden our memory even more? After }3...c5 { , arguably the most principled move, White has a wide range of setups to choose from. Vincent Keymer has recently been experimenting with }4.Be2 Nc6 5.c3 { , with reasonable success. White can also choose a }{ different setup with  b2 - b3  followed by  Bc1 - b2 , and each one asks Black some slightly different questions. } )( { I think it's much more practical to simply ignore all of it, play }3...Bf5 { , and transpose into positions that are the core of our repertoire and that we are very familiar with. } )
4. Bd3( { The only independent move, but obviously not a very critical one. Taking on  d3  is fine, and so is }4...Bg6 { as recently played by Anish Giri, but I finally chose a third option. } )
4. e6{ Simply protecting the bishop and preparing further development. }
5. Bxf5{ If not for this move, what else? }
5. exf5{ We are taught early in life that doubled pawns are bad, and after that, we start learning about the exceptions: and there are plenty! Here the double f-pawns guarantee that we have a half-open e-file and a stronghold on  e4 . }
6. Qd3{ A double attack of sorts, as  f5  is hanging and a check on  b5  is in the air. }
6. Qd7( { Rare, but an excellent choice, and the top choice of the engine. It looks odd to prefer this move over }6...Qc8 { , but it turns out provoking }7.Ne5 { is a good thing, }{ and if White doesn't play  7.Ne5 , the queen is simply better placed on  d7 . } )
7. Ne5{ The most obvious reply, seemingly placing the knight on an active square with tempo. }
7. Qc8
8. O-O
8. Bd6
9. f4{ This type of mistake is often played on an amateur level. White weakens the  e4 -square for the remainder of the game and gets nothing in return. }
9. O-O
10. Nd2
10. c5( { Black is in fantastic shape. After, for instance, }11.c3 Nc6 12.Ndf3 c4 13.Qc2 Ne4 { , Black's positional advantage is already of a winning nature. }{ The  e4 -square is chronically weak but  e5  isn't. We can, at any given moment, play ... f7 - f6  and expel the knight from  e5 . } )
