8. Bd6
9. b3{ Intending to exchange our bishop on  d6 . Indeed, the  c1 -bishop is inferior to ours, meaning an exchange is desirable. }
9. O-O
10. Ba3
10. Qe6{ Moving the queen to  e6  feels harmonious. Now only the  b8 -knight needs developing for the rooks to be connected. }( { If what follows next is a bit too extravagant for you, }10...Bxa3 11.Nxa3 c6 { is a solid alternative. } )
11. Bxd6
11. cxd6{ The consequence of our previous move. We don't mind a second doubling of our pawns, as this time it opens the c-file and wins a tempo attacking the knight on  e5 . A fascinating picture, as it's not often we see pawns doubled this way! }
12. Nf3
12. Nc6{ The position is dynamically equal. We can proceed to double rooks on the c-file or simply establish a knight on  e4 . }
