3. Bf4( { Still intending to reach a standard Jobava London after }3...Nf6 { , but the move order we choose gives us some extra options. } )
3. Nc6( { We should avoid }3...cxd4 4.Qxd4 { , which is a double }{ attack!  d5  is hanging, and so is  a7  (after an exchange on  b8 ). }{ After }4...e6 5.Bxb8 Rxb8 6.Qxa7 { , }6...Bd7 { is not so clear, but   }6.e4! dxe4 7.Qxa7 Bd7 8.O-O-O { does look very unpleasant. } )
4. e4( { While optically more entertaining than }4.e3 { , this leads to a rather sad game for White. } )
4. cxd4
5. Nxd5{ This threatens a check on  c7 , but it's not very difficult to prevent that from happening. }
5. e5
6. Bd2
6. Be6{ Black is slightly better given the lead in development. }
