1. d4
1. d5
2. Nc3{ A few years ago this move was hardly ever seen in tournament play, yet these days, everything goes! I suggest meeting it heads on. }
2. c5( { If White doesn't play  c2 - c4 , we will take our chance! }2...Nf6 { is more often seen and leads to the infamous Jobava London after }3.Bf4 { . } )
3. e4{ This energetic response is the only way to fight for an advantage. It is also how Hans Niemann, a big proponent of this line, handles this position. }
3. dxe4( { Of course, }3...cxd4 4.Qxd4 { is just bad, as we are faced with an issue }{ on  d5 . The endgame after }4...dxe4 5.Qxd8+ Kxd8 6.Bf4!? { followed by castle queenside, is very sad for Black. } )
4. d5{ The point of White's play. Ideally, the  e4 -pawn is now regained while keeping a structural edge. The pawn on  d5  is indeed a bit of a pain, but for now, we can play around it and simultaneously don't make it too easy for White to regain the pawn. }( { Note that White can also play }4.Nge2 { , after which }4...Nf6 5.d5 { transposes, but it gives us the extra option of capturing }{ on  d4 . } )
4. Nf6
5. Bf4( { This prevents the }5...Nbd7 { response we play against  5.Bg5  (because of }6.Nb5! { ) }{ . } )
5. g6
6. Nb5{ Still! Here the knight sortie isn't nearly as effective though. }
6. Na6{ Preventing any check on  c7  while bringing another piece into the game. }
