1. d4
1. d5
2. Nc3{ A few years ago this move was hardly ever seen in tournament play, yet these days, everything goes! I suggest meeting it heads on. }
2. c5( { If White doesn't play  c2 - c4 , we will take our chance! }2...Nf6 { is more often seen and leads to the infamous Jobava London after }3.Bf4 { . } )
3. e4{ This energetic response is the only way to fight for an advantage. It is also how Hans Niemann, a big proponent of this line, handles this position. }
3. dxe4( { Of course, }3...cxd4 4.Qxd4 { is just bad, as we are faced with an issue }{ on  d5 . The endgame after }4...dxe4 5.Qxd8+ Kxd8 6.Bf4!? { followed by castle queenside, is very sad for Black. } )
4. d5{ The point of White's play. Ideally, the  e4 -pawn is now regained while keeping a structural edge. The pawn on  d5  is indeed a bit of a pain, but for now, we can play around it and simultaneously don't make it too easy for White to regain the pawn. }( { Note that White can also play }4.Nge2 { , after which }4...Nf6 5.d5 { transposes, but it gives us the extra option of capturing }{ on  d4 . } )
4. Nf6
5. Nge2
5. e6{ Certainly not the only move, but undermining White's stronghold on  d5  feels good. }( { Both }5...Nbd7 6.Ng3 Nb6!? { and   }5...g6!? 6.Ng3 Bg7 7.Ngxe4 Nxe4 8.Nxe4 O-O { are decent alternatives, and, the latter, perhaps a bit more ambitious as well. } )
6. Nf4{ The most logical reply, trying to preserve control over the  d5 -square. We are happy to remove the pawn from  d5  though, and exchange some pieces in the process. }
6. Nxd5( 6...exd5 { is possible as well, and will transpose after further }{ exchanges on  d5 . } )( { A move we should discard is }6...e5 { , as it relinquishes the pressure on }{ the  d5 -pawn and after }7.Nh5! { , we face direct issues. For instance }7...Nbd7 8.d6! Nxh5 { (or }8...a6 9.Bg5 { with a strong initiative.)   }9.Nb5! { and suddenly the threat }{ of  Nb5 - c7 + means Black is in huge trouble. } )( 6...a6 { certainly is possible though, and leads to sharp play following, for instance, }7.Be3 { , when }7...e5 8.Nh5 Nbd7 { is very different compared to the line above. With the moves  6...a6 7.Be3  included, Black's position seems playable. } )
7. Nfxd5
7. exd5
8. Qxd5( { It doesn't make much sense to recapture with the knight. }8.Nxd5 Be6 { is just better for Black. } )
8. Qxd5
9. Nxd5
9. Bd6{ It is clear that we have very little to worry about here. The queens have come off and we are still in possession of an extra pawn on  e4 . Our opponents that are playing  2.Nc3  will usually be looking for a lively game, with chances for attacking play or such. The position currently on the board is anything but lively and should therefore come as a bit of a disappointment. }
10. Be3
10. Nc6( 10...Bf5!? 11.O-O-O Nd7 { is playable as well, but the continuation we chose forces White's hand a bit more. } )
11. O-O-O
11. Bf5{ Threatening to castle queenside, meaning the next move is more or less forced. }
12. Nf6+
12. Ke7( { Not }12...gxf6 13.Rxd6 { , }{ when White not only captured the pair of bishops but both  f6  and  c5  are hanging. } )
13. Nd5+
13. Kf8( { Instead, }13...Ke6 14.Nc3 Ne5 { was seen in the blitz match Niemann-Shevchenko, chess.com 2022. Here, the engine improvement }15.Re1 { looks a bit unpleasant for Black. Even with queens off, our king isn't that comfortable }{ on  e6  with ideas like  f2 - f3  hanging in the air. } )
14. Bb5{ Not especially challenging, but it would be with the king on  e8 . This line makes it clear why we chose the  f8 -square instead. }
14. Nd4{ Giving back the pawn to further clarify the position and gain the pair of bishops. }
15. Bxd4
15. cxd4
16. Rxd4
16. Bc5{ After the rook retreats, we continue with ... g7 - g6  and ... Kf8 - g7 , with a fine game. }
