13. Kf8( { Instead, }13...Ke6 14.Nc3 Ne5 { was seen in the blitz match Niemann-Shevchenko, chess.com 2022. Here, the engine improvement }15.Re1 { looks a bit unpleasant for Black. Even with queens off, our king isn't that comfortable }{ on  e6  with ideas like  f2 - f3  hanging in the air. } )
14. Nc3
14. Nd4
15. Bc4( 15.Bxd4 cxd4 16.Rxd4 Be5 { is a tiny bit better for Black. } )
15. b6
16. Rhe1
16. Rc8( { We can safely end the line here, but I would like to point out the engine's 1st line. It continues }17.b3 { , to prepare capture }{ on  d4  and  e4 . We go along with that by playing }17...f6 18.Bxd4 cxd4 19.Nxe4 { and now first }19...Ba3+ 20.Kb1 Bb4 21.Re2 { , before playing }21...Bxe4 22.Rxe4 Bc3 { , when the game is pretty much locked.    Following }23.Re6 h5! { , }{ we want to play ... h5 - h4  next and bring the  h8 -rook into play via  h5 . If White prevents that with }24.h4 { , Black plays }24...Rh6 { and prepares to enter the game }{ via  g6 . The key is that the  d1 -rook is out of play and can't easily be brought into the game because of the construction with the pawn on  d4  and bishop on  c3 . } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "38) Pseudo-Trompowsky 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Pseudo-Trompowsky 2.Bg5 c5 3.dxc5 #1 | Informational − Black's Alternatives to 3...h6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Bg5( { The Hodgson Attack, perhaps better known as Pseudo-Trompowsky these days. The normal Trompowsky arises after   }1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 { , and at least }{ attacks the knight on  f6 .    What could be the idea of placing the bishop on  g5  in this instance though? Quite frankly, I have a hard time explaining that, apart from the reason that it probably takes most opponents 'out of book'. There aren't that many pitfalls though, and most lines leave Black comfortably equal. The saying 'knight before bishops' certainly applies here! } )
2. c5( { Simply hitting the center. }2...f6 { is probably the strongest and most principled response but also requires some knowledge of concrete lines. We aren't going to face  2.Bg5  all that much in our lifetime and therefore I prefer a more practical and healthy choice that we can also whip out half a year from now, without remembering much. What's more, here too, it ain't much fun for White. } )
3. dxc5{ The most common move in the position... after which White is worse! Essentially, there is a reversed Queen's Gambit Accepted on the board where White has the 'extra' move  Bc1 - g5 . That doesn't do much to improve White's position. Even more, we can gain time attacking that bishop. }
3. f6{ It certainly is logical to set up a broad center, but the move ... f6  is always very committal. }( { A typical response to }3...Nc6 { is }4.e4! { with the idea that }4...dxe4 5.Qxd8+ Nxd8 6.Bb5+ { leads to a very pleasant endgame for White. The white queenside pawns will prove more menacing than our kingside majority. A sample line runs }6...Nc6 7.Nc3 f5 8.f3! exf3 9.Nxf3 { and White castling queenside coming up next, Black's position is in ruins. } )( 3...Qa5+ { is a move to avoid as well since }4.Nc3 e6 5.e4! { wins a pawn, as }5...dxe4 6.b4! { is already winning. } )( 3...Na6 { meets a similar refutation after }4.e4! { , when }4...dxe4 5.Qxd8+ Kxd8 { is a horrible endgame for Black. For instance }6.Nc3 { ( }6.Bxa6 bxa6 7.Ne2 { is simple and strong as well.)   }6...Nxc5 7.O-O-O+ Bd7 8.b4! Na6 9.Bb5 Nb8 10.Nxe4 { with a large advantage. } )( { Last but not least }3...Nf6 { is also a move, but I feel it gives substance to the fact that White has a bishop }{ on  g5 . White could, for instance, play }4.Bxf6 { and after both }4...exf6 { and }4...gxf6 { , play is approximately equal. The above lines show that even a move like  2.Bg5  can still contain some venom! } )
4. Bd2
4. e5
5. b4{ I am not a big fan of this position, and what is perhaps more important in this day and age, neither is the engine. We are yet to win back the pawn on  c5  and the downside of having played ... f6  is that our kingside isn't that easy to develop. }
