[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "38) Pseudo-Trompowsky 2.Bg5"]
[Black "Pseudo-Trompowsky 2.Bg5 c5 3.e3 #5"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Bg5( { The Hodgson Attack, perhaps better known as Pseudo-Trompowsky these days. The normal Trompowsky arises after   }1.d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 { , and at least }{ attacks the knight on  f6 .    What could be the idea of placing the bishop on  g5  in this instance though? Quite frankly, I have a hard time explaining that, apart from the reason that it probably takes most opponents 'out of book'. There aren't that many pitfalls though, and most lines leave Black comfortably equal. The saying 'knight before bishops' certainly applies here! } )
2. c5( { Simply hitting the center. }2...f6 { is probably the strongest and most principled response but also requires some knowledge of concrete lines. We aren't going to face  2.Bg5  all that much in our lifetime and therefore I prefer a more practical and healthy choice that we can also whip out half a year from now, without remembering much. What's more, here too, it ain't much fun for White. } )
3. e3{ Not the most played move in the position but certainly the best way to keep the central tension. }
3. Nc6
4. Nf3
4. h6( { We hold on to our strategy of keeping things simple. For the adventurous souls, }4...f6 5.Bh4 { ( }5.Bf4 g5 { leads to the same.)   }5...g5 6.Bg3 h5 { is also an option. White should play }7.h3 { and meet }7...cxd4 8.exd4 Nh6 { with }9.c4 Nf5 10.Nc3 { , with an unclear game. } )( 4...Qb6 { would be a decent option if not for }5.c4! { , when both }5...Qxb2 { (and }5...e6 6.Nc3 Qxb2 7.Nb5! { )   }6.cxd5 Qxa1 7.dxc6 { look dangerous for Black. } )
5. Bh4( 5.Bf4 Nf6 { is a London with a tempo down for White. Given }{ that ... h7 - h6  is a very useful move, Black is already on the good side of things. } )
5. cxd4( { In keeping with our strategy. Whilst }5...g5 { is certainly fine, it is also very committal, and I prefer to keep things clean. }5...Qb6 6.c4 { is playable, after }6...e6 { , but we are trying to get a better version of this. } )
6. exd4
6. Qb6{ An annoying move to face for White, now that we have included the capture on  d4 . }
7. b3{ A very undesirable move to make. Of course, the ideal structure is  b2 ,  c3 ,  d4 , and White's last move seriously weakens the chain. }
7. Bg4{ Threatening to win the d-pawn. }
8. c3
8. g5
9. Bg3
9. f5{ Boldy threatening to trap the bishop. }
10. h3
10. Bxf3
11. Qxf3
11. f4( { White's position is in ruins. Note that }12.Qh5+ Kd8 { is not a big deal, as the line continues }13.Bh2 { (what else?) }13...Nxd4! { and White is in big trouble. } )
