[Black "Blackmar-Diemer Gambit 2.e4 #1"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. e4( { This sacrifice is the brainchild of Emil Joseph Diemer and retains a loyal following to this day. The line can also arise from   }1...Nf6 2.f3 d5 3.e4 dxe4 4.Nc3 { , which is how Diemer often played. On the upside, playing this line with White means you have a very high probability of your preparation arising on the board.    The downside, however, is that Black is a pawn up and with accurate play should be able to claim a significant advantage. The idea of the gambit is to obtain a lead in development and sweep Black away in a dazzling attack. Diemer won many such games! } )
2. dxe4
3. f3{ An imprecise move. }
3. e5
4. dxe5( 4.fxe4 { instead loses immediately to }4...Qh4 { , }{ when White has a big problem on  e4 . } )
4. Qxd1+
5. Kxd1
5. exf3
6. Nxf3
6. Nc6( { White just landed on a very sad endgame. After the correct move order   }3.Nc3 Nf6 4.f3 { , the thrust }4...e5? { doesn't work for Black, as }5.dxe5 { attacks the knight. } )
*
[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "39) Blackmar-Diemer Gambit 2.e4"]
[Black "Blackmar-Diemer Gambit 2.e4 #2 | Informational − Black's alternatives to 5...g6"]
[FEN "rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1"]
[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. e4( { This sacrifice is the brainchild of Emil Joseph Diemer and retains a loyal following to this day. The line can also arise from   }1...Nf6 2.f3 d5 3.e4 dxe4 4.Nc3 { , which is how Diemer often played. On the upside, playing this line with White means you have a very high probability of your preparation arising on the board.    The downside, however, is that Black is a pawn up and with accurate play should be able to claim a significant advantage. The idea of the gambit is to obtain a lead in development and sweep Black away in a dazzling attack. Diemer won many such games! } )
2. dxe4
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. f3{ White's intended follow-up. The issue is that the lead in development is just not significant enough for White to have full compensation. }
4. exf3( 4...Bf5 { is excellent as well. Diemer would always play }5.fxe4 Nxe4 6.Qf3 { here, but }6...Nxc3 7.bxc3 e6! { , not caring about the b-pawn, }8.Qxb7 Nd7 { gives Black a pleasant advantage, both in terms of pawn structure and a lead in development.      }5.g4 { may be a better try, but here too Black looks for choice after }5...Bg6 6.g5 Nd5 7.Nxe4 Nc6 { , as }8.c4?! Ndb4 9.d5 { gets hit with }9...Nd4! { when the check }{ on  c2  makes the knight on  d4  untouchable. } )
5. Nxf3( { The most obvious recapture, but Diemer also played dozens of games with }5.Qxf3 { , sacrificing yet another pawn. While Black can certainly take that pawn with }5...Qxd4 { , it was the move }5...g6 { that eventually persuaded Diemer to switch to  5.Nxf3 .    Indeed, the position after }6.Bd3 Bg7 7.Nge2 O-O 8.Bf4 Nc6 9.O-O-O Bg4 { , as in Diemer-Bogoljubow 1949, makes a sad impression for White. I would advise everyone to simply follow in Bogoljubow's footsteps, as it doesn't give White any hope. In any case, it persuaded Diemer }{ never to take on  f3  with the queen again! } )
5. Bg4{ The most played move in the position but not the best at all! This shows how gambits like these can easily catch the opponent unaware. }( 5...e6 { is already more decent and aims at developing the bishop }{ to  e7  instead of  g7 . I prefer the bishop on  g7  though, especially since this gives us also more flexibility with our  c8 -bishop, which may at some point want to come out to  f5  or  g4 . } )( 5...Bf5 { isn't nearly as popular as the two other alternatives mentioned but likely stronger. What Diemer aficionados go for here, is usually something along the lines of }6.Bc4 e6 7.O-O c6 8.Ne5 Nbd7 9.Rxf5 exf5 10.Nxf7 { and White wins. If only chess were that easy! The simple   }8...Bg6 { rules out any sacrifices and prepares to extinguish the knight }{ on  e5  with ... Nb8 - d7  next.  5...Bf5  should indeed also give Black a seizable advantage. } )
6. h3
6. Bxf3( 6...Bh5 7.g4 Bg6 { also gives White attractive options such as }8.h4!? Nxg4 9.h5 Bf5 10.Qe2 { , with a very messy position, or the more obvious   }8.Ne5 { , with decent compensation. } )
7. Qxf3{ Black doesn't have time to take on  d4  since  b7  is hanging. }
7. c6
8. g4( { White has serious compensation. On }8...e6 { , White marches on with }9.g5 { . } )
8. Qxd4
9. Be3{ This looks even more dangerous now than in previous versions. }
