1. d4
1. d5
2. e4( { This sacrifice is the brainchild of Emil Joseph Diemer and retains a loyal following to this day. The line can also arise from   }1...Nf6 2.f3 d5 3.e4 dxe4 4.Nc3 { , which is how Diemer often played. On the upside, playing this line with White means you have a very high probability of your preparation arising on the board.    The downside, however, is that Black is a pawn up and with accurate play should be able to claim a significant advantage. The idea of the gambit is to obtain a lead in development and sweep Black away in a dazzling attack. Diemer won many such games! } )
2. dxe4
3. Nc3
3. Nf6
4. f3{ White's intended follow-up. The issue is that the lead in development is just not significant enough for White to have full compensation. }
4. exf3( 4...Bf5 { is excellent as well. Diemer would always play }5.fxe4 Nxe4 6.Qf3 { here, but }6...Nxc3 7.bxc3 e6! { , not caring about the b-pawn, }8.Qxb7 Nd7 { gives Black a pleasant advantage, both in terms of pawn structure and a lead in development.      }5.g4 { may be a better try, but here too Black looks for choice after }5...Bg6 6.g5 Nd5 7.Nxe4 Nc6 { , as }8.c4?! Ndb4 9.d5 { gets hit with }9...Nd4! { when the check }{ on  c2  makes the knight on  d4  untouchable. } )
5. Nxf3( { The most obvious recapture, but Diemer also played dozens of games with }5.Qxf3 { , sacrificing yet another pawn. While Black can certainly take that pawn with }5...Qxd4 { , it was the move }5...g6 { that eventually persuaded Diemer to switch to  5.Nxf3 .    Indeed, the position after }6.Bd3 Bg7 7.Nge2 O-O 8.Bf4 Nc6 9.O-O-O Bg4 { , as in Diemer-Bogoljubow 1949, makes a sad impression for White. I would advise everyone to simply follow in Bogoljubow's footsteps, as it doesn't give White any hope. In any case, it persuaded Diemer }{ never to take on  f3  with the queen again! } )
5. g6{ Again, Bogoljubow's recipe, just developing the bishop to  g7  and preparing to castle. Simple and strong. A full overview on Black's alternatives at this point is offered in the  Informational . }
6. Bg5{ Correspondence player Peter Leisebein has played a ton of games on the White side of this position. The intention is to play  Qd1 - d2 ,  O-O-O , and  h2 - h4 - h5  followed by mate. A scenario that will never unfold. }
6. Bg7
7. Qd2
7. O-O{ We make our usual developing moves. }
8. O-O-O
8. c5( { The most direct approach. }8...c6!? { is good as well, preparing queenside play }{ with ... Qd8 - a5  or ... b7 - b5 - b4 , and just to illustrate that Black is for choice here, }8...Bg4 { is fine too. } )
9. d5( 9.dxc5?! Qa5 { makes things very easy for us. }{ The  c5 -pawn will drop soon enough, and White's king may also come under siege soon. } )
9. a6( { We want to play ... b7 - b5  next! Since }10.h4 h5 { doesn't do much, Black is better. } )
