[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. g3{ Committing to the development of the light-squared bishop to  g2  this early makes it easier for Black to choose the appropriate setup. }
2. Bf5{ In general in the Slav, when not pressed in the center, I like to solve the problem that is our  c8 -bishop. }
3. Bg2( 3.c4 e6 4.Bg2 c6 5.Nf3 h6 { would transpose. } )
3. e6
4. Nf3
4. h6{ A precaution against a future  Nf3 - h4 . Again, because White hasn't put any pressure in the center, we can take these liberties. }
5. c4( 5.O-O c6 6.c4 Nd7 7.Nc3 { will transpose to the  5.c4 move order . } )
5. c6
6. Nc3
6. Nd7{ We are very close to reaching our perfect setup, with the  g8 -knight coming to  f6 , the  f8 -bishop to  d6 / e7 , and our king castled kingside. There isn't much White can do to stop that. }
7. Qb3
7. Qb6
8. c5{ It's important to look at this sequence, as it's a typical way for our opponents to play. }
8. Qxb3
9. axb3
9. g5{ Now it's clear why we first developed our knight to  d7 , instead of the  g8 -knight to  f6 . The bishop comes to  g7 , threatening ... g5 - g4 . Black is already slightly better. }
