1. d4
1. d5
2. g3{ Committing to the development of the light-squared bishop to  g2  this early makes it easier for Black to choose the appropriate setup. }
2. Bf5{ In general in the Slav, when not pressed in the center, I like to solve the problem that is our  c8 -bishop. }
3. Bg2( 3.c4 e6 4.Bg2 c6 5.Nf3 h6 { would transpose. } )
3. e6
4. Nf3
4. h6{ A precaution against a future  Nf3 - h4 . Again, because White hasn't put any pressure in the center, we can take these liberties. }
5. c4( 5.O-O c6 6.c4 Nd7 7.Nc3 { will transpose to the  5.c4 move order . } )
5. c6
6. Nc3
6. Nd7{ We are very close to reaching our perfect setup, with the  g8 -knight coming to  f6 , the  f8 -bishop to  d6 / e7 , and our king castled kingside. There isn't much White can do to stop that. }
7. O-O
7. Be7( { The text move isn't strictly necessary, but }7...Ngf6 8.Qb3 Qb6 9.c5 Qxb3 10.axb3 a6 11.b4 { is an often-seen endgame that we are trying to reach in a somewhat more favorable version.    If we now play as we will be doing after  7...Be7 , then }11...Rd8 12.Nd2 Bc2 13.b5!? { is very interesting, as }13...cxb5 14.Na2! { prepares to expel the bishop from  c2  with  Na2 - b4  next, followed by  Nd2 - b3 - a5 . }{ Also   }13...axb5 14.b4 { gives White some play on the a-file. } )
8. Qb3{ After any other move we just play ... Ng8 - f6  and castle next. }
8. Qb6
9. c5
9. Qxb3( { A decent alternative is }9...Qa6 { as long as }10.Re1 { is met with }10...b6! { and not }10...Ngf6 11.Bf1! { , when the threat }{ of  e2 - e4  spells trouble. With our knight still on  g8 , I think we get a favorable version of the endgame though, which is why I don’t object to the exchange. } )
10. axb3
10. a6
11. b4
11. Rd8{  b4 - b5  was a positional threat so the rook had to go. }
12. Nd2{ Typical, the knight is headed for  a5  from where it will exert enormous pressure on Black's queenside. }
12. Bc2{ Of course, we won't make it easy for White to reach  a5 . This bishop move, a standard reply to  Nf3 - d2 , is one to remember. }
13. Re1
13. g5{ I like this flexible move, simply keeping all options open and taking space on the kingside. The  f6 -square, for now, can still potentially be used by both knight and bishop, depending on developments. }
14. e4( { The prepared break, but it's a big question of how effective it is. We can even ignore it, and just play }14...Ngf6 { , but I like taking a bit more. } )
14. dxe4
15. Ncxe4
15. Ngf6{ Black is very comfortable and without weaknesses. }
