1. d4
1. d5
2. c3( { A modest-looking move. White simply reinforces the pawn on  d4  and prepares a London-type setup. The most ambitious way to reply is }2...Bf5 { , to immediately develop the problem bishop }{ on  c8 . White has the reply }3.Qb3 { though, and I am not 100% sure about the compensation we have after }3...Nf6 4.Qxb7 Nbd7 5.Nf3 { . }{ White will play  e2 - e3  next and bring the queen back, while it's not easy to make something out of the lead in development. } )( 2...c5 { is another move to consider, but here White plans to take with }3.dxc5 { and hold on to the pawn }{ with  b2 - b4 , etc. I feel this is something we should be avoiding, as there is no need to make things harder for ourselves − unless it promises an advantage. } )
2. Nf6( 3.Nf3 { would now transpose to the chapter on the  3rd Move Sidelines . } )
3. Bf4{ An easy development scheme for White. The next moves are easy to make with  e2 - e3 ,  Nb1 - d2 ,  Ng1 - f3 , etc. }
3. Bf5{ Not the only move, of course, but the one I like most. With a white pawn on  c4 , this developing move is usually not as easy to make since  Qd1 - b3  would pressure both  b7  and  d5 ; here there is no pressure on  d5  though. We continue ... e7 - e6 , ... Nb8 - d7 , ... Bf8 - e7  and castle, with fine prospects.    What I like about playing  3...Bf5  is that at the end of the day, we won't be stuck with any bad piece. All our pieces develop harmoniously. }
