1. d4
1. d5
2. h4( { Magnus Carlsen played the move   }1.h4 { on two occasions, transposing to our line after }1...d5 2.d4 { . There is even a point behind it, though it's way too subtle to be good, obviously. If Black plays }2...c5 { now, as Wei Yi did, Carlsen played }3.e3 Nc6 4.c4 { taking play into a reversed Tarrasch.    Usually, the main setup there is to play }4...cxd4 5.exd4 Nf6 6.Nc3 { and now }6...g6 { , as Rubinstein showed in the previous century, to fianchetto the king's bishop. With that weird move  2.h4  included though, there is suddenly }7.h5! { and White is doing well. After this little excursion, let's just make a few natural developing moves and get this line over with! } )
2. c5
3. e3
3. Nf6
4. c4
4. cxd4
5. exd4
5. Bg4( { Simplest I believe. Now }6.Qb3 Nc6! { is just bad, but other moves also don't appeal. } )
6. f3{ A very ugly move to make − this square was designated for the knight, certainly not the pawn! }
6. Bd7
7. Nc3
7. dxc4( 7...e6 { can also be considered. } )
8. Bxc4
8. e6{ Black has the better game. Both  h2 - h4  and  f2 - f3  have not improved White's position. I dare say  2.h4  is not a big issue! }
