[Result "*"]

1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. g3{ Given that our knight is already on  f6 , we can't play in the same way we do as against  2.g3 . That doesn't mean this line should be considered very critical though. }( 3.c4 c6 { transposes to the main lines. } )
3. Bf5( { Black has many alternatives at this point. I feel }3...c5 4.Bg2 cxd4 { is a fine system as well. The move I choose aims to solve the issue of the light-squared bishop immediately. } )
4. Bg2
4. e6
5. Nh4( { If this move would result in Black needing to retreat with }5...Bg6 { , White would get a pleasant edge after }6.Nxg6 { . } )
5. Be4{ Before giving up the bishop, we first induce some weaknesses. }
6. f3
6. Bg6
7. Nxg6
7. hxg6{ A completely different picture now that White's pawn is on  f3  instead of  f2 . We are ready to play ... c7 - c5  next, with pressure in the center. }
