1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. g3{ Given that our knight is already on  f6 , we can't play in the same way we do as against  2.g3 . That doesn't mean this line should be considered very critical though. }( 3.c4 c6 { transposes to the main lines. } )
3. Bf5( { Black has many alternatives at this point. I feel }3...c5 4.Bg2 cxd4 { is a fine system as well. The move I choose aims to solve the issue of the light-squared bishop immediately. } )
4. Bg2
4. e6
5. O-O
5. h6( { Now }5...c6 6.Nh4! Be4 7.f3 Bg6 8.e4! { would give White the initiative, }{ which is why we make some luft for the bishop on  f5 . } )
6. c4
6. c6
7. Nc3
7. Nbd7{ A position we discussed briefly in the  2.g3 line , where we cunningly played ... Bf8 - e7  instead of ... Ng8 - f6 . As mentioned there, this position is also in no way problematic for Black. White merely has a slightly favorable version of the line we discussed after  2.g3 . }
8. Nd2( { Together with }8.Qb3 { , the most popular move in the position. The two moves do differ significantly in the direction they take the game. The move at hand aims for the }{ central  e2 - e4  push. } )
8. Be7( { I think it is best to allow  e2 - e4 . The alternative would be to play }8...Bb4 { , but that would come down to giving up on the pair of bishops after }9.Qb3 Qa5 10.a3 { , while   }9.e4 Bxc3 10.exf5 { can't be discarded completely either. } )
9. e4
9. dxe4
10. Ndxe4
10. O-O( 10...Nxe4 11.Nxe4 Nf6 { , or }11...O-O { , is likely to transpose. } )
11. Be3
11. Nxe4
12. Nxe4
12. Nf6{ Offering trades is a trustworthy technique for the side with less space; the more pieces come off, the easier it is to maneuver with the limited space available. }
13. Nc3( 13.Nxf6+ Bxf6 { would only make our lives easier. } )
13. Rc8{ Getting out of the long diagonal, which is useful in case of a future  d4 - d5 , or ... b7 - b5  from our side. We have the perfect setup and can look at the future with confidence! }
