1. d4
1. d5
2. Nf3( { It's important to talk move orders at this point. After }2.c4 { , we play }2...c6 { , so it may seem logical to do the same here. Indeed, after   }2...c6 3.c4 { , we transpose back to known Slav territory. However, White is not forced to play }3.c4 { , but can play }3.Bf4 { instead.    }{ In the London System, the move ... c7 - c6  is not at all part of our setup, as we usually aim to move the pawn to  c5  in one go. That means White has reached a favorable setup of the London System. Therefore, we meet  2.Nf3  differently. As a general rule, we only play ... c7 - c6  when White plays  c2 - c4 . } )
2. Nf6( { Now all is well after }3.c4 c6 { , when we transpose back into known lines. } )
3. g3{ Given that our knight is already on  f6 , we can't play in the same way we do as against  2.g3 . That doesn't mean this line should be considered very critical though. }( 3.c4 c6 { transposes to the main lines. } )
3. Bf5( { Black has many alternatives at this point. I feel }3...c5 4.Bg2 cxd4 { is a fine system as well. The move I choose aims to solve the issue of the light-squared bishop immediately. } )
4. Bg2
4. e6
5. O-O
5. h6( { Now }5...c6 6.Nh4! Be4 7.f3 Bg6 8.e4! { would give White the initiative, }{ which is why we make some luft for the bishop on  f5 . } )
6. c4
6. c6
7. Nc3
7. Nbd7{ A position we discussed briefly in the  2.g3 line , where we cunningly played ... Bf8 - e7  instead of ... Ng8 - f6 . As mentioned there, this position is also in no way problematic for Black. White merely has a slightly favorable version of the line we discussed after  2.g3 . }
8. Qb3( { Together with }8.Nd2 { , the most popular move in the position. The two moves do differ significantly in the direction they take the game. The move at hand aims to play for a queen trade, after our next move, and play an endgame. } )
8. Qb6( { In fact, }8...Qc7 { is rarely ever played but is a very fine and tricky alternative. At first sight, it looks like we are walking into }9.Bf4 { , but paradoxically, }9...Qb6 10.c5 Qxb3 11.axb3 g5! { is a very good version for Black of the endgame that can arise after  8...Qb6 . Rather than gaining time with the extra move  Bc1 - f4 , we gain time in attacking that bishop with ... g7 - g5 . According to the engines, Black is already slightly better. }{ I assume   }9.Nd2 { is a better way to play, }{ preparing  e2 - e4 . } )
9. c5( { White should push the c-pawn, as }9.Bf4 g5! { followed by ... Bf8 - g7 , only plays into Black's hands. } )
9. Qa6( 9...Qxb3 10.axb3 { transposes to  the note on move 7  in  2.g3 . There isn't much wrong with this endgame, but I prefer to keep the queens on }{ and aim to chip away at White's center with ... b7 - b6 . It is a slightly more ambitious way of playing. } )( 9...Qc7 { is a move we will see more of later, but here it's not very good. White gets a pleasant edge after }10.Bf4 Qc8 11.Rfe1 Be7 12.Nd2! O-O 13.e4 { , when Black is forced to }{ take on  e4 , as }13...Bg6 14.exd5 cxd5 15.Nxd5! { drops a pawn. } )
10. Re1
10. b6( { It is important to play this move immediately. There is no time for }10...Be7 { , as }11.Bf1! { shows the idea behind moving the rook }{ to  e1 , and suddenly puts our queen on  a6  in grave danger. } )
11. cxb6
11. Qxb6{ Largely a matter of choice. I like the idea of keeping the b-file open for now and offering the trade of queens. Note that the exchange of White's c-pawn for our b-pawn is a major strategic victory for us. }( 11...axb6 { is fine as well, but the lines after }12.Ne5 Nxe5 13.dxe5 Nd7 14.e4 { have a rather forced nature, and I don't see the huge upside of that. Following }14...Nc5 15.Qd1 dxe4 16.Nxe4 Nxe4 17.Bxe4 Bxe4 18.Rxe4 { , the position is around equal but given the choice, I'd probably take White due to the slight lead in development. } )( { Last but not least, the remarkable }11...Be7!? { should be noted, simply ignoring White's capture }{ on  b6 ! We get }{ Benko-like (the Benko is an opening that arises after   }1.d4 Nf6 2.c4 c5 3.d5 b5 4.cxb5 a6 { ) compensation after   }12.bxa7 Qxa7 { , }{ with ... O-O  coming followed by a rook swing to  b8  (if allowed). } )
12. Na4{ Given that the engine gives us the choice between three moves that are all assessed as 0.00, White's last move can't be considered overly critical. }
12. Qxb3
13. axb3
13. Bc2{ With a comfortable game. For the moment, White needs to worry about the b-pawn. }
